entries.notes: â€œYou can feel a lot of motion and energy,â€ Caroline Polachek tells Apple Music of her second solo studio album. â€œAnd chaos. I definitely leaned into that chaos.â€ Written and recorded during a pandemic and in stolen moments while Polachek toured with Dua Lipa in 2022, Desire, I Want to Turn Into You is Polachekâ€™s self-described â€œmaximalistâ€ album, and it weaponises everything in her kaleidoscopic arsenal. â€œI set out with an interest in making a more uptempo record,â€ she says. â€œSongs like â€˜Bunny Is a Riderâ€™, â€˜Welcome to My Islandâ€™ and â€˜Smokeâ€™ came onto the plate first and felt more hot-blooded and urgent than anything Iâ€™d done before. But of course, life happened, the pandemic happened, I evolved as a person, and I canâ€™t really deny that a lunar, wistful side of my writing can never be kept out of the house. So it ended up being quite a wide constellation of songs.â€ Polachek cites artists including Massive Attack, SOPHIE, Donna Lewis, Enya, Madonna, The Beach Boys, Timbaland, Suzanne Vega, Ennio Morricone and Matia Bazar as inspirations, but this broad church only really hints at Desireâ€¦â€™s palette. Across its 12 songs we get trip-hop, bagpipes, Spanish guitars, psychedelic folk, â€™60s reverb, spoken word, breakbeats, a childrenâ€™s choir and actual Didoâ€”all anchored by Polachekâ€™s unteachable way around a hook and disregard for low-hanging pop hits. This is imperial-era Caroline Polachek. â€œThe albumâ€™s medium is feeling,â€ she says. â€œItâ€™s about character and movement and dynamics, while dealing with catharsis and vitality. It refuses literal interpretation on purpose.â€ Read on for Polachekâ€™s track-by-track guide. â€œWelcome to My Islandâ€ â€œâ€˜Welcome to My Islandâ€™ was the first song written on this album. And it definitely sets the tone. The opening, which is this minute-long non-lyrical wail, came out of a feeling of a frustration with the tidiness of lyrics and wanting to just express something kind of more primal and urgent. The song is also very funny. We snap right down from that Tarzan moment down to this bitchy, bratty spoken verse that really becomes the main personality of this song. Itâ€™s really about ego at its coreâ€”about being trapped in your own head and forcing everyone else in there with you, rather than capitulating or compromising. In that sense, it's both commanding and totally pathetic. The bridge addresses my father [James Polachek died in 2020 from COVID-19], who never really approved of my music. He wanted me to be making stuff that was more political, intellectual and radical. But also, at the same time, he wasnâ€™t good at living his own life. The song establishes that there is a recognition of my own stupidity and flaws on this album, that itâ€™s funny and also that we're not holding back at allâ€”weâ€™re going in at a hundred percent.â€ â€œPretty in Possibleâ€ â€œIf â€˜Welcome to My Islandâ€™ is the insane overture, â€˜Pretty in Possibleâ€™ finds me at street level, just daydreaming. I wanted to do something with as little structure as possible where you just enter a song vocally and just flow and there's no discernible verses or choruses. Itâ€™s actually a surprisingly difficult memo to stick to because it's so easy to get into these little patterns and want to bring them back. I managed to refuse the repetition of stuffâ€”except for, of course, the opening vocals, which are a nod to Suzanne Vega, definitely. Itâ€™s my favourite song on the album, mostly because I got to be so free inside of it. Itâ€™s a very simple song, outside a beautiful string section inspired by Massive Attackâ€™s â€˜Unfinished Sympathyâ€™. Those dark, dense strings give this song a sadness and depth that come out of nowhere. These orchestral swells at the end of songs became a compositional motif on the album.â€ â€œBunny Is a Riderâ€ â€œA spicy little summer song about being unavailable, which includes my favourite bassline of the albumâ€”this quite minimal funk bassline. Structurally on this one, I really wanted it to flow without people having a sense of the traditional dynamics between verses and choruses. Timbaland was a massive influence on that songâ€”especially around how the beat essentially doesn't change the whole song. You just enter it and flow. â€˜Bunny Is a Riderâ€™ was a set of words that just flowed out without me thinking too much about it. And the next thing I know, we made â€˜Bunny Is a Riderâ€™ thongs. I love getting occasional Instagram tags of people in their â€˜Bunny Is a Riderâ€™ thongs. An endless source of happiness for me.â€ â€œSunsetâ€ â€œThis was a song I began writing with Sega Bodega in 2020. It sounded completely nothing like the others. It had a folk feel, it was gypsy Spanish, Italian, Greek feel to it. It completely made me look at the album differentlyâ€”and start to see a visual world for them that was a bit more folk, but living very much in the swirl of city life, having this connection to a secret, underground level of antiquity and the universalities of art. It was written right around a month or two after Ennio Morricone passed away, so I'd been thinking a lot about this epic tone of his work, and about how sunsets are the biggest film clichÃ©s in spaghetti westerns. We were laughing about how it felt really flamenco and Spanishâ€”not knowing that a few months later, I was going to find myself kicked out of the UK because I'd overstayed my visa without realising it, and so I moved my sessions with Sega to Barcelona. It felt like the song had been a bit of a premonition that that chapter-writing was going to happen. We ended up getting this incredible Spanish guitarist, Marc Lopez, to play the part.â€ â€œCrude Drawing of an Angelâ€ â€œâ€˜Crude Drawing of an Angelâ€™ was born, in some ways, out of me thinking about jokingly having invented the word â€˜scornyâ€™â€”which is scary and horny at the same time. I have a playlist of scorny music that I'm still working on and I realised that it was a tone that I'd never actually explored. I was also reading John Berger's book on drawing [2005â€™s Berger on Drawing] and thinking about trace-leaving as a form of drawing, and as an extremely beautiful way of looking at sensuality. This song is set in a hotel room in which the word â€˜drawingâ€™ takes on six different meanings. It imagines watching someone wake up, not realising they're being observed, whilst drawing them, knowing that's probably the last time you're going to see them.â€ â€œI Believeâ€ â€œâ€˜I Believeâ€™ is a real dedication to a tone. I was in Italy midway through the pandemic and heard this song called â€˜Ti Sentoâ€™ by Matia Bazar at a house party that blew my mind. It was the way she was singing that blew me awayâ€”that she was pushing her voice absolutely to the limit, and underneath were these incredible key changes where every chorus would completely catch you off guard. But she would kind of propel herself right through the centre of it. And it got me thinking about the archetype of the diva vocallyâ€”about how really it's very womanly that itâ€™s a woman's voice and not a girl's voice. That thereâ€™s a sense of authority and a sense of passion and also an acknowledgement of either your power to heal or your power to destroy. At the same time, I was processing the loss of my friend SOPHIE and was thinking about her actually as a form of diva archetype; a lot of our shared taste in music, especially â€™80s music, kind of lined up with a lot of those attitudes. So I wanted to dedicate these lyrics to her.â€ â€œFly to Youâ€ (feat. Grimes and Dido) â€œA very simple song at its core. It's about this sense of resolution that can come with finally seeing someone after being separated from them for a while. And when a lot of misunderstanding and distrust can seep in with that distance, the kind of miraculous feeling of clearing that murk to find that sort of miraculous resolution and clarity. And so in this song, Grimes, Dido and I kind of find our different version of that. But more so than anything literal, this song is really about beauty, I think, about all of us just leaning into this kind of euphoric, forward-flowing movement in our singing and flying over these crystalline tiny drum and bass breaks that are accompanied by these big Ibiza guitar solos and kind of Nintendo flutes, and finding this place where very detailed electronic music and very pure singing can meet in the middle. And I think it's something that, it's a kind of feeling that all of us have done different versions of in our music and now we get to together.â€ â€œBlood and Butterâ€ â€œThis was written as a bit of a challenge between me and Danny L Harle where we tried to contain an entire song to two chords, which of course we do fail at, but only just. Itâ€™s a pastoral, it's a psychedelic folk song. It imagines itself set in England in the summer, in June. It's also a love letter to a lot of the music I listened to growing upâ€”these very trance-like, mantra-like songs, like Donna Lewisâ€™ â€˜I Love You Always Foreverâ€™, a lot of Madonnaâ€™s Ray of Light album, Savage Gardenâ€”that really pulsing, tantric electronic music that has a quite sweet and folksy edge to it. The solo is played by a hugely talented and brilliant bagpipe player named Brighde Chaimbeul, whose album The Reeling I'd found in 2022 and became quite obsessed with.â€ â€œHopedrunk Everaskingâ€ â€œI couldn't really decide if this song needed to be about death or about being deeply, deeply in love. I then had this revelation around the idea of tunnelling, this idea of retreating into the tunnel, which I think I feel sometimes when I'm very deeply in love. The feeling of wanting to retreat from the rest of the world and block the whole rest of the world out just to be around someone and go into this place that only they and I know. And then simultaneously in my very few relationships with losing someone, I did feel some this sense of retreat, of someone going into their own body and away from the world. And the song feels so deeply primal to me. The melody and chords of it were written with Danny L Harle, ironically during the Dua Lipa tourâ€”when I had never been in more of a pop atmosphere in my entire life.â€ â€œButterfly Netâ€ â€œâ€˜Butterfly Netâ€™ is maybe the most narrative storyteller moment on the whole album. And also, palette-wise, deviates from the more hybrid electronic palette that we've been in to go fully into this 1960s drum reverb band atmosphere. I'm playing an organ solo. I was listening to a lot of â€™60s Italian music, and the way they use reverbs as a holder of the voice and space and very minimal arrangements to such incredible effect. It's set in three parts, which was somewhat inspired by this triptych of songs called â€˜Chansons de Bilitisâ€™ by Claude Debussy that I had learned to sing with my opera teacher. I really liked that structure of the finding someone falling in love, the deepening of it, and then the tragedy at the end. It uses the metaphor of the butterfly net to speak about the inability to keep memories, to keep love, to keep the feeling of someone's presence. The children's choir [London's Trinity Choir] we hear on â€˜Billionsâ€™ comes in againâ€”they get their beautiful feature at the end where their voices actually become the stand-in for the light of the world being onto me.â€ â€œSmokeâ€ â€œIt was, most importantly, the first song for the album written with a breakbeat, which inspired me to carry on down that path. Itâ€™s about catharsis. The opening line is about pretending that something isn't catastrophic when it obviously is. It's about denial. It's about pretending that the situation or your feelings for someone aren't tectonic, but of course they are. And then, of course, in the chorus, everything pours right out. But tonally it feels like I'm at home base with â€˜Smokeâ€™. It has links to songs like [2019â€™s] â€˜Pangâ€™, which, for me, have this windswept feeling of being quite out of control, but are also very soulful and carried by the music. We're getting a much more nocturnal, clattery, chaotic picture.â€ â€œBillionsâ€ â€œâ€˜Billionsâ€™ is last for all the same reasons that 'Welcome to My Islandâ€™ is first. It dissolves into total selflessness, whereas the album opens with total selfishness. The Beach Boysâ€™ â€˜Surfâ€™s Upâ€™ is one of my favourite songs of all time. I cannot listen to it without sobbing. But the non-linear, spiritual, tumbling, open quality of that song was something that I wanted to bring into the song. But 'Billions' is really about pure sensuality, about all agenda falling away and just the gorgeous sensuality of existing in this world that's so full of abundance, and so full of contradictions, humour and eroticism. Itâ€™s a cheeky sailboat trip through all these feelings. You know that feeling of when you're driving a car to the beach, that first moment when you turn the corner and see the ocean spreading out in front of you? That's what I wanted the ending of this album to feel like: The song goes very quiet all of a sudden, and then you see the water and the children's choir comes in.â€

entries.title: Nine

entries.notes:
At the turn of the century, Radiohead released two albums that forever altered their identity. Now, Kid A and Amnesiac are reissued as a pair, along with whatever worthy B-sides, alternate versions, and outtakes they can find.
Kid A and Amnesiac, released eight months apart, have always had a big brother/kid brother relationship. They were recorded at the same time, during the same sessions, but Amnesiac inevitably became seen as a repository, the place where the music that wasnâ€™t on Kid A found a home. As a standalone album, its reputation has been unsettled since the minute it was releasedâ€”in a glowing New Yorker profile that same year, Alex Ross watches them tersely correct a hapless young MTV News reporter who accidentally refers to Amnesiac as the â€œouttakes.â€ â€œTry again,â€ snapped Phil Selway.

The band separated the two releases because they wanted to avoid releasing a double album, that most tired and bloated of rock-excess beasts. At the time, avoidance of all rock-star gestures had become something of a survival mechanism for the band. They had been touring, more or less continuously, for the past seven years. Six months into the long, punishing tour for OK Computer, Thom Yorke had briefly slipped into catatonia. They were getting more successful, and it felt awful: Watch the 1998 documentary Meeting People Is Easy and youâ€™ll see what rock stardom felt like to Yorkeâ€™s nervous systemâ€”dull, pointless torture, like being detained for eternity by airport security.

When they began the fitful, labored studio sessions that would produce both Kid A and Amnesiac in late 1999 and 2000, Radiohead knew very little about what they wanted, only that they did not want to be â€œrock starsâ€ anymore. Their new music, whatever else it might be, must accomplish that singular objective: All rock-band gestures were to be isolated, rooted out, and erased. They wanted to, as the song title had it, disappear completely.

A Radiohead axiom is that whatever the band set out to do, they usually wind up accomplishing the exact opposite. When they went in to record OK Computer, Thom Yorke declared confidently that they were about to make their first â€œpositiveâ€ record. And when they released Kid Aâ€”the album meant to chart a new course away from the rock-star treadmillâ€”it became their first-ever album to simultaneously top the U.S. and UK charts. Even more than â€œCreep,â€ which had only blown up Stateside, Kid A was now their big hit. Eight months later, Amnesiac would reach No. 2. They had gone as far away from guitar-based rock music as they knew how to go, and at the end of it, not only were Radiohead still a rock band, they were a generational one. All roads led back to the arena stage, even their escape route.

In the last five or so years, the band seems to have come to terms with its statusâ€”Selway and Ed Oâ€™Brien graciously accepted the bandâ€™s nomination into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2019. In 2017, they entered their commemorative re-release phase with OK Computer OKNOTOK 1997 2017, which collected the bandâ€™s foundational third album along with its ephemera. Now, they have finally released that long-avoided double album: Kid A Mnesia, which unites the two studio albums, along with whatever worthy B-sides, alternate versions, and outtakes they can find. 

Like many of their recent gesturesâ€”putting their music on Spotify for fans, years after Yorke memorably dubbed the streaming service â€œthe last desperate fartâ€ in the music industryâ€™s â€œdying corpseâ€; releasing hours of their demos for OK Computer after someone hacked their MiniDiscs from the sessionsâ€”it feels like an act of both generosity and capitulation. They have long since stopped fighting, but these albums capture the band when the stakes felt mortal; in recording these albums, they were fighting for their lives.

During the recording sessions, the band was frequently aimless, frustrated, certain only that they were accomplishing very little. On the online journal he maintained on Radioheadâ€™s website during the recording sessions, Oâ€™Brien worried publicly that the band was steering itself toward oblivion. â€œItâ€™s taken us seven years to get this sort of freedom, and itâ€™s what we always wanted,â€ he wrote. â€œBut it could be so easy to fuck it all up.â€ At times, it seems like every one of them was casting about in different directions, returning with half-cooked pieces of music that nobody else quite knew what to do with. They didnâ€™t know what kind of band they were supposed to become, but they all knew they were tired of the band they were currently in. None of them had one clear, resounding idea for a new direction.

One of the earliest songs they struggled with was â€œIn Limbo,â€ which layers guitar triplets over straight 4/4 drums, both of which slid off the surface of the underlying 6/4 meter. Rhythmically, it created a featureless expanse with no distinguishing marks, and the songâ€™s pulse resembled ocean waves more than any sort of backbeat. Perhaps in a nod to the songâ€™s maze-like rhythm, perhaps in acknowledgment of the quicksand they felt underneath, they called the demo â€œLost at Sea.â€

Meanwhile, Jonny Greenwood was fooling around with modular synthesizers, playing patches of radio static and snatches of electronic music records over rudimentary drum machine patterns, searching for a moment of inspiration. Yorke listened to it patiently, and found only 40 seconds of usable materialâ€”four refracted synth chords from the American composer Paul Lanskyâ€™s computer piece â€œMild Un Liese.â€ The seeds of â€œIdiotequeâ€ were planted.

In all this seeming directionlessness, Radiohead were zeroing in on the most primal essence of their artâ€”sound. Critics at the time knocked Kid A and Amnesiac for seeming half-formed, or sketch-like, but the de-emphasis on things like bridges and middle-eights seemed strategic. The members were seeking textures and tones, spaces expansive and inviting enough that they might stay awhile. In doing so, they reinvented the timbral palette for a rock band.

It was on Kid A and Amnesiac that they became in love with almost recognizable sounds. What was born out of a desire to eraseâ€”and Yorke used this word more than once, suggesting a vigorous desire, naming his solo album after this impulseâ€”became an opportunity to transfigure. The standard rock instruments became the ghostsâ€”nothing in Kid A sounds so otherworldly as the guitars, or Yorkeâ€™s voice. On â€œMorning Bell,â€ Greenwood scraped the strings with a coin to produce keyboard-like sounds.

The disembodied guitar sounds mingled eerily with the ondes Martenot, an instrument Jonny Greenwood mastered after becoming obsessed with the music of French composer Olivier Messiaen. Messiaen employed the ondes Martenot in his celebrated large-scale 1948 work TurangalÃ®la-Symphonie, which generated ecstatic, alien textures from the full orchestra and the early electronic instrumentâ€™s disembodied whine. The ondes Martenot is everywhere on these two albumsâ€”whining alongside the string section in â€œHow to Disappear Completely,â€ doubling the guitar and vocals on â€œOptimistic.â€ It is deployed as a forbidding chill whenever the textures threaten to get too familiar. Likewise, itâ€™s the non-rock instruments that are allowed to breathe, to exist in a recognizable shape as themselvesâ€”a harp glissandi, for instance, or a harmonium, both on â€œMotion Picture Soundtrack,â€ or the wailing New Orleans brass band on â€œLife in a Glass House.â€ These are the warmest textures on albums that defined digital-age paranoia, and they predate electricity completely.

Kid A was the first Radiohead album released in the harsh light of the Napster era, the dawn of musicâ€™s digital age. Because of that, the songs that would come to comprise Amnesiac were already pretty familiar to Radiohead fans who had been trolling P2P servers for new material. Live and demo versions of â€œDollars and Cents,â€ â€œYou and Whose Army?â€ and â€œPyramid Songâ€ were freely traded over Napster, as were a few of the outtakes that didnâ€™t make either album.

This means that none of the bonus material on Kid Amnesiae, the third â€œbonusâ€ disc accompanying the two studio albums, has the same revelatory quality as the inclusions on OK Computer OKNOTOK 1997 2017. The tracklist is padded out slightly with the isolated string tracks for â€œPyramid Songâ€ and â€œHow to Disappear Completely,â€ as well as a murmured two-minute take on â€œMorning Bellâ€ that sounds like a rehearsal for the version that appeared on Amnesiac. There is no â€œI Promise,â€ no â€œLift,â€ no bolt-from-the-blue alternate history that redefines our understanding of the band that wrote the album material. â€œFollow Me Around,â€ which was billed as the big inclusion on this re-release and the â€œholy grailâ€ for Radiohead fans, is a song that most Radiohead hardcore faithful know extremely wellâ€”it was included in a pivotal scene of Meeting People Is Easy.

Another â€œlostâ€ Radiohead song from these sessions, â€œFog,â€ is a little more intriguing. It was one of those nakedly vulnerable ballads that slipped out of Yorke from time to time, seemingly against his will. The grief-haunted lyrics mingled tenderness and dreadâ€”a child, possibly dead, runs forever up and down a hallway, while a luminous fog belches up from the sewers.

They first premiered it at a concert in Israel, where it was known as â€œAlligators in New York Sewers,â€ in July 2000. The live version is a simple, arresting two-minute piano ballad. The original studio version, which found its way into the world as one of the B-sides to the â€œKnives Outâ€ single, preserved this intimacy, but was marred by a slightly out-of-time tambourine and an uncertain-sounding guitar part. The version they include here isnâ€™t as good as either, with overly bright synth patches and a non-committal vocal take. It underscores the trouble that Radiohead have often had with their tender songs. If there is anything comical about the band, it is their distrust of their own instincts to write beautiful songs, and the agony and prolonged discomfort it seems to provoke in them.

If not for this slightly adolescent distrust of prettiness, however, Kid A might never have been born. â€œIt annoys me how pretty my voice is,â€ Yorke famously griped, and the last 20 years of their music can sometimes be seen as a battle between Yorkeâ€™s uglier impulses squaring off against the choirboy lilt of the instrument heâ€™s stuck with.

Yorkeâ€™s impulse to deform himself on record, however, led to moments of wild creativity. On Amnesiacâ€™s â€œPulk/Pull Revolving Doors,â€ seven years before Lil Wayneâ€™s â€œLollipop,â€ he intentionally mangled his voice with Auto-Tune. As an entire generation of hip-hop performers would go on to do, Yorke mumbled into the machine, allowing the pitch-corrector to randomly assign a key and a melody to his words.

Perhaps no single song encapsulates this mix of aimlessness and invention, the will toward prettiness and the losing war against it, as neatly as â€œLike Spinning Plates.â€ In the studio, they were grimacing their way through another demoâ€”the chord progressions were somehow insulting, too obvious. Thom Yorke, always quick with a withering aside for their own material, dubbed it â€œdodgy Kraftwerk.â€

They couldnâ€™t stop messing with it, however. No idea the band generated, no matter how wispy or maddeningly incomplete, seemed to stay away forever. (Yorke apparently wrote the bassline for â€œThe National Anthemâ€ when he was 16, and it sounds like it.) Their song fragments were like sick dogs that wouldnâ€™t stop limping after their masters. So there was Greenwood, messing around with the latest playback of that pretty ballad. Out of boredom, a fit of pique, whatever, he played it backwards.

Yorke, who was nearby, was transfixed. He crossed the room and demanded to hear it again. The track, played backwards, sounded like it was sucking nearby debris inward and pulling everything down with it. Yorke sat down and wrote a new song on top of his upside-down old one. But the backwards/forwards vortex seemed to have inspired a fever. So he sang his own lyrics backwards, on purpose, live. Then he reversed them so we heard them forwardsâ€”a subliminal message, just like the hysterical censors told us there would be when we played our records backward. But there it was, floating on the surface like a plastic bottle on the ocean.

That original upside-down song was a pretty ballad called â€œI Will,â€ which they would go on to rework, yet another time, and release for 2003â€™s Hail to the Thief. Radiohead fans have long tried to sync up the two versions themselves, re-reversing â€œLike Spinning Platesâ€ and laying the vocal take from â€œI Willâ€ atop it to recreate that â€œdodgy Kraftwerkâ€ demo that is lost to history.

Kid Amnesiae does not include that original â€œI Willâ€ demo, which, given the juvenilia and ephemera the band has allowed to see the light of day by now, suggests just how much Yorke must still hate it. The â€œLike Spinning Platesâ€ version on the bonus disc layers the grand piano arpeggios familiar from the version on I Might Be Wrong: Live Recordings atop the backmasked effects of the studio version. Notably, Yorke adds a verse that brings his desire for escape at the time into urgent focus: â€œWhy us? Why not someone else?/The cameras are turning off.â€ Like Bob Dylan post-motorcycle crash, doing everything he could to discourage the press and his fanâ€™s interest only to increase his enigmatic appeal, Yorke struggled against the straitjacket of his bandâ€™s grandness only to feel it pull tighter.

Decades later, the grandness of those sounds is what lingers. This is Radioheadâ€™s ultimate gift as a rock bandâ€”the transmutation of sound into sensation, the way an unnerving bit of audio can play upon our nerve endings, up-end us ever so slightly. The searching language of the chorus to â€œLike Spinning Platesâ€ (â€œThis just feels likeâ€¦Spinning platesâ€) nailed the curious, uneasy feeling that sound can give us, and the way those feelings translate into our other senses. It was the indelible sounds they made on Kid A and Amnesiac, more than any of the albumâ€™s digital age paranoia or its baleful view of the future, that comprise the bandâ€™s enduring legacy. Those sounds break free of anything you might want to attach to them.

entries.notes: It has nearly become a clichÃ© unto itself for so many albums released in 2021 and 2022: an accomplished work of art that perfectly articulates themes of isolation and desperation and fatalism, only for the artists to reveal that the songs that express these ideas most acutely were written before the pandemic. â€œIt was already sort of all in the world,â€ Arcade Fireâ€™s Win Butler tells Apple Musicâ€™s Zane Lowe. â€œIn order to write music, you have to have this antenna up that kind of picks up little signals from the future and signals from the past. And so I think a lot of times we're just getting these like aftershocks of things that are about to happen.â€ WE is 10 tracks, but really more like five songs, taking into account various parts and chapters that give the album its epic scope, capturing the joy-in-the-face-of-peril spirit of their beloved 2004 debut Funeral, only with the peril a bit heightened. The songs that Butler and his wife RÃ©gine Chassagne started in their backyard New Orleans studio prior to March 2020 form a narrative that opens in a state of despair and winds up in an unlikely place of hope and optimism, with all the exuberance that marks the bandâ€™s most memorable songs. Like all Arcade Fire albums, WE is a family affair, featuring not just Butler, Chassagne and Butlerâ€™s younger brother Willâ€”who has since left the group, amicablyâ€”but Butlerâ€™s mom, a harpist, as well as guest vocals from Peter Gabriel. Read on as Butler expounds on a few key moments from WE. â€œEnd of the Empire I-IIIâ€ â€œIt's easy to interpret everything as being about the present, and I think there's an element of that, but I think you're trying to pick up on smoke signals. To me, the end of the empire isn't about now, it's about the future. It's about what's coming. I'm still waiting to wake up and check my phone and see the stock market has finally crashed. I mean, it's just an inevitability. This stuff is so cyclical, and it's like we're just printing money and pretending everything's okay. My grandfather lived through the Depression and was a musician in World War II and lived through some pretty intense stuff, and so I think this generation is up to the task as well. We have an eight-year-old, and the tools that he has compared to the tools that I had at that age are incredible.â€ â€œEnd of the Empire IV (Sagittarius A)â€ â€œâ€˜End of the Empireâ€™ is four parts; we had the first three parts and it was already six and a half minutes. For some reason I just knew that there was a fourth part to it, and I had this index card that said, â€˜Sagittarius Aâ€™, which is a black hole in the middle of our solar system. I just had the card on my wall and I would just walk by it. As soon as I was vaccinated and was able to travel, I went with my son to go visit my parents because I hadn't seen them in a long time. I went back to their house in Maine and I brought my 4-track and I put it in the basement of their house and ran a bunch of cables up to the top floor. I felt like I was 15. It was exactly like the shit I was doing when I was 15. I was like, 'Mom, I'm working on this song.' We would play 'Sagittarius A' together. There were a couple other songs that I did these 4-track recordings of playing it with her, and it sort of helped me to work through it and to just figure out what it is.â€ â€œThe Lightning IIâ€ â€œWhat was in my head when I was singing that song was all the Haitians at the border trying to get into the US who had taken a boat from Haiti to Brazil and then walked or taken a train all the way to the Mexican border. Just to find a better life for your familyâ€”imagine what it would take, the bravery. The governor of Texas can honestly...I don't hate a lot of people, but I hate that motherfucker. I don't even believe in hell, but if there's a hell, that motherfucker's going there. Just to meet people with the absolute absence of compassion, these fake fucking Christians. That's not necessarily what the song's about, but that was what was in my head: What does it mean to not quit and to reach the end and then to be turned back, and you still can't quit because you still have your family, so then you get sent back to where you started and you still can't give up because it's still your life and it's still your family and you're still fighting for survival.â€ â€œUnconditional I (Lookout Kid)â€ â€œI was really just thinking about my son and the world that he's facing and how I was a very depressed kid, particularly in high school. I was trying to imagine the way that I'm wired, just chemically, having to deal with that now, not to mention 10 years from now, whenever the fuck he's going to be dealing with it. He's going to need to have a thick skin and to just really be able to take a hit and have some fortitude. And basically just the idea of unconditional love, which is this impossible thing to achieve. But we do it naturally, somehow. And it's something that I think we naturally have with our kids, but I think it's something that we're supposed to have for people that we're not related to as well.â€ â€œWEâ€ â€œI think the journey of the record, the first half is: Imagine this character's like, 'Get me the F out of here, get me off this planet, get me out of my own skin, get me away from myself. I don't want to be here.' It's anxiety and it's depression and it's heaviness, it's the weight of the world. And he looks at this black hole like, 'Well, maybe if I could get through that black hole, that would be far enough away.' And when he gets there, he finds that it's himself and it's everyone he ever loved and the lives of his ancestors. There's nothing to escape, because it's all the same thing anyway. Stories and films are always building towards this big conclusion and then the credits roll. And to me, the sentiment is, 'Let's just fucking do it again, with all of itâ€”all the pain, all the loneliness, all the sadness, all the heartbreak. I just want to do it over and over again. Just run it back.â€
entries.title: WE

entries.notes: â€œThis album is all about contrasts,â€ Wevalâ€™s Harm Coolen tells Apple Music. â€œItâ€™s mixing in-your-face, heavy dance music with a joyful hopefulness to make you move.â€ Since forming in 2012, Dutch duo Harm Coolen and Merijn Scholte Albers have been crafting melodically intricate electronic tracks with an underlying acoustic warmth. Theirs is a sound full of earworming melodies and luscious arrangements, producing 2016â€™s self-titled debut album and The Weight in 2019. On their latest release, Remember, they pay homage to their decade in music by piecing together fragments of long-standing unreleased songs with fresh, emphatic production. The result is 11 infectiously energetic tracks, from the soaring vocal hooks of â€œNever Stay for Loveâ€ to the earthy funk of â€œEverything Went Wellâ€ and the distorted rhythms of â€œLosing Daysâ€. â€œItâ€™s a propulsive record but one with a positive feeling,â€ Coolen says. â€œItâ€™s made from the longing to play loud and to let people have fun with the music.â€ Read on for Coolen and Albersâ€™ in-depth thoughts on the album, track by track. â€œRememberâ€ Harm Coolen: â€œâ€˜Rememberâ€™ is one of the final tracks we made for the record. We had been working on the album for three and a half years already but we were still searching for new ideas to help round out its contrasts.â€ Merijn Scholte Albers: â€œWe were on the road in LA and stopped into the studio to jam with our friend, producer Daniel Lynas. It was meant to just be a hang but then we came up with the stems for â€˜Rememberâ€™. It had a perfect, positive feeling and, once we got back home, we built the vocal line and knew it would be the ideal opener.â€ â€œEverything Went Wellâ€ HC: â€œOver the summer, we spent a week in Germany with a group of other artist friendsâ€”this was one of the tracks we wrote there. Iâ€™d just gotten back from a one-off therapy session using psychedelics, and I had an amazing experience. Itâ€™s not something I usually do but the lyrics were influenced by that unique moment, since the first sentences that came out of my mouth were about how you feel when everything goes well. Itâ€™s an uplifting song about looking back with gratitude.â€ â€œLosing Daysâ€ MSA: â€œThis was one of the first tracks we wrote for the album, encapsulating that feeling of the two worlds of distortion and hopeful melodies combining. The beat is really heavy, like it might blow up your speakers, but the chords are so soothing.â€ HC: â€œThis track started the whole concept of the record. Itâ€™s meant to be played with the volume loud and blazing.â€ â€œWhere It All Leadsâ€ HC: â€œWe had the elements of the track that would go on to become â€˜Where It All Leadsâ€™ for quite some time but we didnâ€™t know how to fully piece it together. We didnâ€™t want to overload it, so we focused on the groove and its harshness, which gave new context to the sweet vocal lines on top.â€ MSA: â€œThis has a similar concept to â€˜Losing Daysâ€™, starting with a heavy beat and a compressed, gritty sound then layering on a hopeful melody.â€ â€œDonâ€™t Lose Timeâ€ MSA: â€œThe final 20 seconds of â€˜Donâ€™t Lose Timeâ€™ is a snippet of the first demo we made of the track. That used to be a five-minute song that we were very happy with, but it didnâ€™t quite fit with the sound of the new record.â€ HC: â€œIt was almost too sentimental, so we shifted it into a rave direction and really embraced our dance music influences. We knew we had gotten it right because we just wanted to dance in the studio when we came up with it!â€ â€œNever Stay for Loveâ€ (feat. Eefje de Visser) HC: â€œEefje was one of the artists staying in the house we rented in Germany, and we asked her to feature on another tune, â€˜Is That How You Feel Itâ€™. We jammed for a while over that instrumental, and she did an incredible job. So much so that when we isolated the vocal track and worked on it further, it became an entirely new song, which is â€˜Never Stay for Loveâ€™.â€ MSA: â€œThat reworking is something we do quite often now. Itâ€™s a fun way to surprise yourself by switching vocals from different chord progressions.â€ â€œDay After Dayâ€ MSA: â€œThis is another fragment of an old ideaâ€”a song called â€˜Daysâ€™ from 2016. We had tried to finish it for years but we always failed. We loved the basic idea but didnâ€™t know how to fill in the other elements until I pitched the chords down one day and it became an entirely new thing. It has this driving, big-beat feel, which is exactly how we wanted the whole record to be. The song is like a train, it just keeps on going.â€ â€œChanged for the Betterâ€ HC: â€œâ€˜Changed for the Betterâ€™ came out of our longing to play live again during the pandemic. We wanted to make a tune that we could play in front of a crowd once things reopened, something where the vocals are clear and punchy and that incorporates dance elements to get people moving.â€ MSA: â€œIt was the perfect single for us to release as it embodies the new direction weâ€™re exploring. Itâ€™s in-your-face, fun and full of distorted 808 kick drums.â€ â€œI Saw Youâ€ HC: â€œThis was another late addition to the album. Since so many of the other tracks are driving and more intense, we needed a breather and something to showcase a more uplifting side to the darker elements. Even though â€˜I Saw Youâ€™ is upbeat and almost drum â€™nâ€™ bass tempo, it embodies that lightness we were looking for in its melodies.â€ â€œIs That How You Feel Itâ€ HC: â€œEefjeâ€™s initial vocal take for this track ended up becoming the basis for â€˜Never Stay for Loveâ€™, so we were then left with a gap where we needed new lyrics and vocals. I was playing around and recording some lines and ended up slowing down the track while jamming. It suddenly made my vocal take on a great vibrato and soulful feel. Itâ€™s not our typical sound but it just fits perfectly here.â€ â€œForeverâ€ HC: â€œâ€˜Foreverâ€™ is another example of us stitching together pieces of old tracks to make something new. The beat on the song is around three years old, while the vocal was taken from another demo. We added a rave-y, acid synth line to a 120 BPM dancey feel and hopeful lyrics on being thankful for everything that has come before. As soon as we made it, we knew it was the only way to end the album.â€
entries.title: Remember

entries.notes: Mike Hadreasâ€™ music as Perfume Genius has always walked an interesting line between experimentalism and accessibilityâ€”pop for listeners more interested in â€œpopâ€ as a concept than a reality. Written as a companion to a dance piece by choreographer Kate Wallich, Ugly Season effectively inverts the balance, situating Hadreasâ€™ hallmarksâ€”his romanticism, his expressivity, his startling, sometimes violent sense of dramaâ€”in the context of something that plays more like a symphony or soundtrack than a set of discrete songs. The title is a feint, of course: This is extremely beautiful music even in its dissonance, from the Philip Glass-like grid of â€œTeethâ€ and the spiderweb instrumental of â€œScherzoâ€ to the industrial roar of â€œHellbentâ€. And just in case, he gives you something called â€œPop Songâ€â€”which isnâ€™t one, of course.

entries.notes: Letâ€˜s start with that speech. In September 2022, as Taylor Swift accepted Songwriter-Artist of the Decade honours at the Nashville Songwriter Awards, the headline was that Swift had unveiled an admittedly â€œdorkyâ€ system sheâ€™d developed for organising her own songs. Quill Pen, Fountain Pen, Glitter Gel Pen: three categories of lyrics, three imagined tools with which she wrote them, one pretty ingenious way to invite obsessive fans to lovingly obsess all the more. And yet, perhaps the real takeaway was the manner in which she spoke about her craft that night, some 20 years after writing her first song at the age of 12. â€œI love doing this thing we are fortunate enough to call a job,â€ she said to a room of her peers. â€œWriting songs is my lifeâ€™s work and my hobby and my never-ending thrill. A song can defy logic or time. A good song transports you to your truest feelings and translates those feelings for you. A good song stays with you even when people or feelings donâ€™t.â€ On Midnights, her tenth LP and fourth in as many yearsâ€”if you donâ€™t count the two sheâ€™s just re-recorded and buttressed with dozens of additional tracksâ€”Swift sounds like sheâ€™s really enjoying her work, playing with language like kids do with gum, thrilling to the texture of every turn of phrase, the charge in every melody and satisfying rhyme. Alongside long-time collaborator Jack Antonoff, sheâ€™s set out here to tell â€œthe stories of 13 sleepless nights scattered throughout [her] lifeâ€, as she phrased it in a message to Apple Music subscribers. Itâ€™s a concept that naturally calls for a nocturnal palette: slower tempos, hushed atmosphere, negative space like night sky. The sound is fully modern (synths youâ€™d want to eat or sleep in, low end that sits comfortably on your chest), while the aesthetic (soft focus, wood panelling, tracklist on the cover) is decidedly mid-century, much like the Mad Men-inspired title of its brooding opener, â€œLavender Hazeâ€â€”a song about finding refuge in the glow of intimacy. â€œTalk your talk and go viral,â€ she sings, in reference to the maelstrom of outside interest in her six-year relationship with actor Joe Alwyn. â€œI just want this love spiral.â€ (A big shout to Antonoff for those spongy backup vocals, btw.) In large part, Midnights is a record of interiors, Swift letting us glimpse the chaos inside her head (â€œAnti-Heroâ€, wall-to-wall zingers) and the stillness of her relationship (â€œSweet Nothingâ€, co-written by Alwyn under his William Bowery pseudonym). For â€œSnow on the Beachâ€, she teams up with Lana Del Reyâ€”an artist whose instinct for mood and theatrical framing seems to have influenced Swiftâ€™s recent catalogueâ€”recalling the magic of an impossible night over a backdrop of pizzicato violin, sleigh bells and dreamy Mellotron, like the earliest hours of Christmas morning. â€œIâ€™ve never seen someone lit from within,â€ Swift sings. â€œBlurring out my periphery.â€ But then thereâ€™s â€œBejeweledâ€, a late, 1989-like highlight on which she announces to an unappreciative partner, a few seconds in: â€œAnd by the way, Iâ€™m going out tonight.â€ And then out Swift goes, striding through the centre of the song like she would the room: â€œI can still make the whole place shimmer,â€ she sings, relishing that last word. â€œAnd when I meet the band, they ask, â€˜Do you have a man?â€™/I could still say, â€˜I donâ€™t remember.â€™â€ There are traces of melancholy layered in (see: â€œsapphire tears on my faceâ€), but the song feels like a triumph, the sort of unabashed, extroverted fun that would have probably seemed out of place in the lockdown indie of 2020â€™s folklore and evermore. But here, side by side with songs and scenes of such writerly indulgence, itâ€™s right at homeâ€”more proof that the terms â€œsinger-songwriterâ€ and â€œuniversal pop starâ€ arenâ€™t mutually exclusive ideas. â€œWhatâ€™s a girl gonna do?â€ Swift asks at its climax. â€œA diamondâ€™s gotta shine.â€ This special expanded version of Midnights includes seven additional songs.
entries.title: Midnights (3am Edition)

entries.notes:
The album of our Denia holiday trip in April 2022. 

â€œI literally donâ€™t take breaks,â€ ROSALÃA tells Apple Music. â€œI feel like, to work at a certain level, to get a certain result, you really need to sacrifice.â€ Judging by MOTOMAMI, her long-anticipated follow-up to 2018â€™s award-winning and critically acclaimed EL MAL QUERER, the mononymous Spanish singer clearly put in the work. â€œI almost feel like I disappear because I needed to,â€ she says of maintaining her process in the face of increased popularity and attention. â€œI needed to focus and put all my energy and get to the centre to create.â€ At the same time, she found herself drawing energy from bustling locales like Los Angeles, Miami and New York, all of which she credits with influencing the new album.
 
Beyond any particular source of inspiration that may have driven the creation of MOTOMAMI, ROSALÃAâ€™s come-up has been nothing short of inspiring. Her transition from critically acclaimed flamenco upstart to internationally renowned starâ€”marked by creative collaborations with global tastemakers like Bad Bunny, Billie Eilish and Oneohtrix Point Never, to name a fewâ€”has prompted an artistic metamorphosis. Her ability to navigate and dominate such a wide array of musical styles only raised expectations for her third full-length, but she resisted the idea of rushing things. â€œI didnâ€™t want to make an album just because now itâ€™s time to make an album,â€ she says, citing that several months were spent on mixing and visuals alone. â€œI donâ€™t work like thatâ€.
 
Some three years after EL MAL QUERER, ROSALÃAâ€™s return feels even more revolutionary than that radical breakout release. From the noisy-yet-referential leftfield reggaetÃ³n of â€œSAOKOâ€ to the austere and Yeezus-reminiscent thump of â€œCHICKEN TERIYAKIâ€, MOTOMAMI makes the artistâ€™s femme-forward modus operandi all the more clear. The point of view presented is sharp and political, but also permissive of playfulness and wit, a humanising mix that makes the album her most personal yet. â€œI was like, I really want to find a way to allow my sense of humour to be present,â€ she says. â€œItâ€™s almost like you try to do, like, a self-portrait of a moment of who you are, how you feel, the way you think."
 
Things get deeper and more unexpected with the devilish-yet-austere electronic punk funk of the title track and the feverish â€œBIZCOCHITOâ€. But there are even more twists and turns within, like â€œHENTAIâ€, a bilingual torch song that charms and enraptures before giving way to machine-gun percussion. Add to that â€œLA FAMAâ€, her mystifying team-up with The Weeknd that fuses tropical Latin rhythms with avant-garde minimalism, and you end up with one of the most unique artistic statements of the decade so far.
entries.title: MOTOMAMI

Thereâ€™s a gnarly guitar solo that sheâ€™s become known for at her many award-show performances, references to eating in fine-dining establishments in Paris, and a pretty piano outro. entries.notes: Having collaborated as the London-based Portico Quartet for more than a decade, drummer Duncan Bellamy and saxophonist Jack Wyllie know how to maximise their time and effort. Their sessions for the 2021 album Monument were productive enough to have generated this compelling follow-up EP. Of the four contrasting songs, the title track is the most rhythmically intense, with long manipulated soprano sax sounds floating over Bellamyâ€™s fast broken-beat patterns. On the opening â€œCaptured Timeâ€, Wyllie gets an almost trumpetlike tone from the soprano as string textures and rhythmic agitation swell around him. â€œProcessionâ€ begins in a piano-centred stillness, with breath elements and drones setting up a doleful, slowly pulsing elegy on tenor sax. â€œYouthâ€, also with Wyllie on tenor, has fat, sustaining synth-bass tones undergirding a reverberant and impassioned melody. Aesthetically, Next Stop is one with Monument, though it expands the scope of that previous achievement.
entries.title: Next Stop

entries.notes: In 2017, Ctrlâ€”a 14-track project rife with songs about love, sex, self-doubt and heartbreakâ€”became one of the most influential albums in R&B. Ctrl was the soundtrack for many people in their twenties, highlighting the growing pains of young adulthood. SZAâ€™s vulnerability and raw honesty, coupled with ultra-relatable lyrics full of diary-like ruminations and conversations from friend group chats, are what made her debut so impactful. Where Ctrl reflected SZAâ€™s journey towards finding self-love and acceptance, her long-awaited sophomore LP SOS finds the St. Louis-born singer-songwriter dealing with some of the same topics of love and relationships from a more self-assured place. She ditches the uncertainties of her romantic entanglements to save herselfâ€”most of the time. On the soulful and gritty album opener â€œSOSâ€, SZA reintroduces herself and says precisely whatâ€™s on her mind after a night of crying over a lost relationship: â€œI talk bullshit a lot/No more fuck shit, Iâ€™m done,â€ she swaggers. This isnâ€™t the only song that shows her weariness towards relationships that no longer serve her; see also â€œSmoking on My Ex Packâ€ and â€œFarâ€. She finds the confidence to know that she doesnâ€™t need to depend on a man to find happiness on â€œConceitedâ€ and â€œForgivelessâ€. However, not every song on the project is about moving on and leaving her past relationships behind her; SZA still has a penchant for making wrong decisions that may not end well for her (â€œToo Lateâ€, â€œF2Fâ€) and questions her worth in some instances (â€œSpecialâ€). The album sketches the ebbs and flows of emotions, with strength in one moment but deep regret and sadness the next. Thereâ€™s growth between her debut and sophomore album, not just lyrically but sonically as well, blending a mix of her beloved lo-fi beats and sharing space with grunge- and punk-inspired songs without any of it sounding out of place. On the Phoebe Bridgers collaboration â€œGhost in the Machineâ€, the duo take a deeper look at the realities of stardom, looking for a bit of humanity within their day-to-day interactions. The track is not only progressive in its use of strings and acoustic guitars but haunting in its vocal performance. Throughout the journey of SOS, there are moments of clarity and tenderness where SZA goes through the discomfort of healing while trying to find the deeper meaning within the trials and tribulations she endures. She embraces this new level of confidence in her life, where she isnâ€™t looking for anyone to save her from the depth of her emotions but instead is at peace with where sheâ€™s at in life.
entries.title: SOS

entries.notes: Part of the appeal of Londoner Tom Skinnerâ€™s first release under his own name is that it sounds perpetually familiar but canâ€™t be traced to a single source. Over the course of 27 minutes and with the unusual quintet of drums, bass, two cellos and two saxophones, he compresses â€™70s-style cosmic jazz (â€œBisharaâ€), noir soundtrack music (â€œRed 2â€), abstract blues (â€œThe Day After Tomorrowâ€) and sparkling post-bop (â€œQuiet As Itâ€™s Keptâ€) into pieces small enough to digest easily but dense enough to get across the essence of their respective reference pointsâ€”a feat not just of composition but editing, which, in Skinnerâ€™s own words, owed more to the chopping and looping of disco and house DJs than anything else. But to the modern jazz fans who landed here because of Skinnerâ€™s affiliation with Sons of Kemet or the International Anthem label, know that Voices of Bishara isnâ€™t a beat tape or collage project, and to the Radiohead fans curious about Thom Yorke and Jonny Greenwoodâ€™s collaborator in The Smile, know that, like great Radiohead, what makes Skinnerâ€™s process here interesting is how little you can hear its seams.
entries.title: Voices of Bishara - EP

entries.notes: The nearly six-year period Kelela Mizanekristos took between 2017â€™s Take Me Apart and 2023â€™s Raven wasnâ€™t just a break; it was a reckoning. Like a lot of Black Americans, sheâ€™d watched the protests following George Floydâ€™s murder with outrage and cautious curiosity as to whether the winds of social change might actually shift. She read, she watched, she researched; she digested the pressures of creative perfectionism and tireless productivity not as correlatives of an artistic mind but of capitalism and white supremacy, whose consecration of the risk-free bottom line suddenly felt like the arbitrary and invasive force it is. And suddenly, she realised she wasnâ€™t alone. â€œInternally, Iâ€™ve always wished the world would change around me,â€ Kelela tells Apple Music. â€œI felt during the uprising and the [protests of the early 2020s] that thereâ€™s been an external shift. We all have more permission to say, â€˜I donâ€™t like that.â€™â€ Executive-produced by longtime collaborator Asmara (Asma Maroof of Nguzunguzu), 2023â€™s Raven is both an extension of her earlier work and an expansion of it. The hybrids of progressive dance and â€™90s-style R&B that made Take Me Apart and Cut 4 Me compelling are still there (â€œContactâ€, â€œMissed Callâ€, both co-produced by LSDXOXO and Bambii), as is her gift for making the ethereal feel embodied and deeply physical (â€œEnough for Loveâ€). And for all her respect for the modalities of Black American pop music, you can hear the musical curiosity and experiential outliersâ€”as someone who grew up singing jazz standards and played in a punk bandâ€”that led her to stretch the paradigms of it, too. But the albumâ€™s heart lies in songs like â€œHolierâ€ and â€œRavenâ€, whose narratives of redemption and self-sufficiency jump the track from personal reflections to metaphors for the struggle with patriarchy and racism more broadly. â€œIâ€™ve been pretty comfortable to talk about the nitty-gritty of relationships,â€ she says. â€œBut this album contains a few songs that are overtly political, that feel more literally like no, you will not.â€ Oppression comes in many forms, but they all work the same way; Raven imagines a flight out.
entries.title: Raven

â€œWhen itâ€™s just us two, itâ€™s really easy to make music,â€ JD BECK tells Apple Music. â€œWe play around, and the tracks come pouring out.â€ Instrumental prodigies DOMi & JD BECK certainly have a telepathic connection when it comes to creativity. First meeting in 2018 at the NAMM trade show in Southern California, where the two teenagers were individually invited to perform as part of a larger ensemble, Texas-born drummer BECK formed an instant connection with French keyboardist and Berklee student DOMi Louna (born Domitille Degalle). The pair soon began writing fast-paced, note-packed jams to upload to their Instagram, and by 2020, they had caught the attention of multi-instrumentalist Anderson .Paak. Swiftly signing them to his APESHIT label, he challenged the duo to release an updated body of work as a debut. â€œHe basically told us we could do better than the albumâ€™s worth of material we already had,â€ BECK says. â€œSo, we put together a wish list of collaborators and got to work.â€ The result is NOT TiGHT, a 15-track jazz-fusion odyssey of head-nodding hip-hop, psychedelic vocoder experiments and rhythmic freakouts. â€œWe just wanted to surprise ourselves with this album,â€ DOMi says. â€œThis music is an expression of ourselves at our core.â€ Here, DOMi & JD BECK offer their thoughts on each of the albumâ€™s tracks. â€œLOUNAâ€™S iNTROâ€ DOMi Louna: â€œWe thought the album needed book-ending to help bring the listener in and then back out of the tracks. We already had the outro, â€œTHANK Uâ€, so we wrote these chords and added synth patches before sending it to violin, double bass, viola, cello and harp players all around the world. It was like a mini online orchestra opening the album for us.â€ â€œWHATUPâ€ DL: â€œWeâ€™ve had these chords since 2018, as they were part of a track that was going to be the intro for our original album. We kept playing around with it when we were locked down together during the pandemic, and after deconstructing it a few times, we decided to make a new tune. We added a drum solo section, and so now the record has two intros before we get into â€˜SMiLEâ€™.â€ â€œSMiLEâ€ JD BECK: â€œI sing dumb little melodies a lot, and when I was in the bathroom on my phone one day in 2018, the melody just came to me. I put it together in my head and shouted to DOMi to quickly set it to some chords.â€ â€œBOWLiNGâ€ (feat. Thundercat) JDB: â€œWe met Thundercat around the same time as meeting each other. Whenever we were in LA, we would go and stay with him and take over his house. We always write a lot with him when weâ€™re thereâ€”we must have 50 song ideas together already. Back in 2018, weâ€™d all go bowling a lot, as itâ€™s his favourite thing to do, and so we wrote this song about hanging out in the bowling alley.â€ â€œNOT TiGHTâ€ (feat. Thundercat) JDB: â€œItâ€™s probably the closest representation of our soundâ€”just singing random melodic lines to crazy chord combinations. In 2019, we played it for Thundercat, and he loved it so much that he wanted to be on it. He became the first instrumentalist to collaborate with us, and it was incredible to have him soloing on the track with DOMi.â€ â€œTWO SHRiMPSâ€ (feat. Mac DeMarco) DL: â€œWe wrote the instrumental for this track while we were on tour in 2019. JD had a little drum machine, which he made a loop on, and then I added the keyboard parts and put it in a 9/8 time signature. We met Mac the same day we met Anderson .Paak in 2019, and by 2020, we were spending a lot of time at Macâ€™s house. We played him this instrumental, and he started singing along to it, just listing random sandwich names. The track was originally called â€˜Sandwiches of Americaâ€™. We ended up re-recording new lyrics with him, but thankfully itâ€™s still food-related.â€ â€œU DONâ€™T HAVE TO ROB MEâ€ JDB: â€œIâ€™ve been playing gigs by myself since I was 11, and I got used to the element of danger, being in cities late at night. When DOMi and I started going out in LA, you could feel when there was danger, like one day we were in the parking lot of the bowling alley at 1 am, and this dude asked us for a cigarette, and it really felt like he might pull a knife on us too. It made us think about how we never have cashâ€”only cards that we can cancel easilyâ€”so why even go through that trouble of robbing us?â€ â€œMOONâ€ (feat. Herbie Hancock) JDB: â€œAndy made us write down all our goals for the record, and among them was a list of people weâ€™d love to work with. Herbie was at the top of those names. One of Andyâ€™s managers had a connect with Herbie, and he called us one day to say that Herbie had watched our videos on YouTube and was down to collaborate.â€ DL: â€œWe were shitting our pants, as we knew we now had to come up with the best song weâ€™d ever written. Sunlight is some of our favourite stuff that Herbie has done with the vocoder, and so we wrote â€˜MOONâ€™ to that same vibe. Luckily, we got him on piano, too, and when we recorded it together in 2021, we got to hang out with him, which was amazing.â€ â€œDUKEâ€ JDB: â€œThis track is a George Duke reference. We had been hanging out a lot with Earl Sweatshirt and his producer Black Noise, and they inspired us to put three of our loops together into one track and then record it as a new song. The record is full of crazy songs, and we needed something to chill after Herbieâ€”a track that has a natural feel.â€ â€œTAKE A CHANCEâ€ (feat. Anderson .Paak) DL: â€œWe really wanted a feature from Anderson, as weâ€™re huge fans of his, and so we had to come up with something unique and very pretty for him to sing and play on. JD wrote this hook, and when we played it to Andy, he just started rapping over the verses, and then we all sang on the chorus. The whole track was a bunch of surprises and sections put together, since Andy can fit over pretty much anything.â€ â€œSPACE MOUNTAiNâ€ JDB: â€œWhen we first got to LA, I couldnâ€™t get into any clubs, so the only thing we ended up doing, apart from making music, was going to Disneyland. We went on the ride Space Mountain a lot, and it felt like the perfect title for this crazy tune. The first section is a loop we wrote in 2019, where I recorded the drums through an intense compressor, and then the second half used to be part of the original intro to our first album.â€ â€œPiLOTâ€ (feat. Anderson .Paak, Busta Rhymes & Snoop Dogg) DL: â€œWe made this beat in 2020, before we signed with Anderson. We used to send him clips of what we were making, and the day after we sent him this, he emailed it back with him and Busta on it, which was amazing. Once we signed, we had Snoop Dogg on our dream list of collabs, and we thought he would be perfect for â€˜PiLOTâ€™. He was down for it, so we went to Snoopâ€™s studio for six hours one day and recorded it all super smooth. It was very cool to see him and Andy interact and write to our loop.â€ â€œWHOAâ€ (feat. Kurt Rosenwinkel) JDB: â€œDOMi wrote the first part of this tune when she was 12. It was on a random Sibelius session that she played by accident, and I loved it. I knew we had to do a song with it, and Kurt felt like the perfect fit. We met him through the drummer Louis Cole when we were in New York in 2019. A week after he had the track, he sent it back with him soloing from beginning to end. It was perfect.â€ â€œSNiFFâ€ DL: â€œThe original title for this was â€˜You Can Sniff My Buttâ€™. JD wrote it in 2018, all in one go in front of meâ€”and itâ€™s one of my favourite things heâ€™s ever made. We played it at every show as a closer and people loved its pace, so it felt like a good idea to close the record with it too. It was one of the earliest songs we came up with together.â€ â€œTHANK Uâ€ JDB: â€œThis used to be a crazy loop in a 13 time signature, which was called â€˜Dermatologistâ€™ because DOMi had just learned what that word was. We wrote it in an Airbnb somewhere in 2018 and then, when we came back to it a few years later for this record, we realised it was perfect to send to the mini-orchestra who played on the intro. It rounds out the album really well.â€
entries.title: NOT TiGHT

entries.notes: Alongside Moor Motherâ€™s 2021 album, Black Encyclopedia of the Air, Jazz Codes explores the question of how accessible a generally inaccessible artist can get without sacrificing the density of their ideas. It isnâ€™t to say itâ€™s easy music (45 tightly collaged minutes of spoken word, free jazz, electronic loops and fragmentary hip-hop)â€”only that it makes space for the listener in ways she hasnâ€™t always in the past. Given the albumâ€™s subject matterâ€”jazz history, the nature and place of Black artâ€”itâ€™s easy to hear the shift as one from personal expression to stewardship and communication: She wants you to understand where sheâ€™s coming from as a gesture of respect to those who came before, whether Woody Shaw (â€œWOODY SHAWâ€), Mary Lou Williams (â€œODE TO MARYâ€) or Joe McPhee (â€œJOE MCPHEE NATION TIMEâ€). Her fellow travellersâ€”multi-hyphenate Black artists like AKAI SOLO and Melanie Charlesâ€”show you she isnâ€™t alone. And while the difficulty lingers, it gets explicit purpose, courtesy of professor, artist and activist Thomas Stanley on the outro: â€œUltimately, perhaps, it is good that people abandoned jazz/Replaced it with musical products better-suited to capitalismâ€™s designs/Now jazz jumps up like Lazarus if we allow it, to rediscover itself as a living music.â€
entries.title: Jazz Codes

entries.notes:
Duncan Bellamy and Jack Wyllie had a more productive lockdown than most in 2020. The drummer and saxophonist pair, who make up the London-based jazz and electronic group Portico Quartet, recorded two albums in only a matter of months. The first, Terrain, arrived in May 2021 and is a three-track, minimalist exploration of melodic loops and textural atmospheres. It is followed by Monument, a concise encapsulation of the Portico Quartet sound. Where Terrain dug into lengthy meditative compositions, Monument traverses everything from the driving groove of â€œImpressionsâ€ to the krautrock-referencing â€œUltravioletâ€ and the strings-laden, cinematic melodies of â€œOn the Lightâ€. â€œThere isnâ€™t much wastage in Monument,â€ saxophonist Wyllie tells Apple Music. â€œIt feels like this sculptural, composed exploration of our sound and evolution over the years.â€ Read on for his thoughts on the album, track by track.
â€œOpeningâ€ â€œOur process generally works with us individually building ideas over the course of a month and then in the following month we work together to make them into tunes. This track began with an idea that Duncan had and that I added some sax and synth to, as well as recorded strings. We did a lot of studio work on it afterwards by running it back through delays to give it a sense of space and ambience.â€
â€œImpressionsâ€ â€œThis is a recognisably Portico Quartet tune, featuring the hang drum, which is a key part of the identity of the band. It's similar to the track â€˜Ruinsâ€™ from our third album, but this is more up front and direct. There's a nice contrast between the rhythmic groove that is quite big and then the sax, which is played very gently. There's a load of vocal samples that we sang on too in the background. All of that helps make up its ambient textures.â€
â€œUltravioletâ€ â€œThis is contrastingly quite different from our earlier music. It's got a krautrock groove to it, as well as that pitched saxophone at the start and the Prophet synth line that Duncan's playing. At this point in the record, we felt like you need to have a bit of propulsion, since you've come out of the intro into something quite up front and now you want to keep on driving through.â€
â€œEver Presentâ€ â€œDuncan wrote the piano part, and I liked the simplicity of it. We put it back through some modulated reverb to give it a woozy effect, and then my saxophone melody references our earlier work with its melodic economy. Duncan's playing bass on it as wellâ€”itâ€™s quite busy underneath the melody, but it fits together nicely.â€
â€œGatewayâ€ â€œWe didn't have any interludes on the album at first, but after we sent it in to the record label, they said it felt slightly too full-on and needed a bit of space to breathe. We had already written this hang drum melody and the one on â€˜Portalâ€™, which we then slid into the track listing. It gives the album a different pace and allowed it to be an easier listen.â€
â€œMonumentâ€ â€œThis started with a vocal loop, in a similar feel to an earlier track of ours called â€˜Endlessâ€™. I added a very simple melodic sax sound to the loop that is then quite heavily manipulated through effects pedals. The whole song is supposed to feel like a journey, where the listener is taken through these different sonic worlds and ends up in an entirely new space.â€
â€œA.O.Eâ€ â€œThe connection between the tracks and their titles is sometimes so abstract for usâ€”we just go with whatever feels like it works. We spend so long doing them; it could take three months to write the album and three months to do the sequencing and titles. This stands for â€˜Age of Enlightenmentâ€™, since Duncan and I were both reading an article about it at the time. It's one of my favourite tunes, since I really like how it cuts between these two sections, switching from electronic drums to acoustic drums and then the soaring sax and cello melody.â€
â€œWarm Dataâ€ â€œAfter we've separately worked with each other's ideas, we usually go to a recording studio and turn them into pieces of music by re-recording everything. With â€˜Warm Dataâ€™, we jammed most of it in a studio that had a Steinway piano. We improvised along to a groove that Duncan had already written, and then after we'd recorded it, we chopped it up and made it more coherent.â€
â€œPortalâ€ â€œWe probably could have turned â€˜Gatewayâ€™ and â€˜Portalâ€™ into more fleshed-out tunes of their own, but they fit on this album perfectly as interludes. They are both hang drum melodies processed through reverb and delay. They're functional tracks, but they are also essential to the listening experience of the record as a whole.â€
â€œOn the Lightâ€ â€œThis is classic Portico territory. Duncan initially wrote the drum and bass grooves and then I built the melodies on top. It's a really nice way to finish the record, since the strings come in at the end and elevate it into a cinematic feel. It was lovely to have the strings players Simmy Singh and Francesca Ter-Berg in the studio with us, helping with the arrangements. It's a celebratory way to end the album.â€
entries.title: Monument

entries.notes: Brittney Parksâ€™ Athena was one of the more interesting albums of 2019. Natural Brown Prom Queen is better. Not only does Parksâ€”aka the LA-based singer, songwriter and violinist Sudan Archivesâ€”sound more idiosyncratic, but sheâ€™s able to wield her idiosyncrasies with more power and purpose. Itâ€™s catchy but not exactly pop (â€œHome Makerâ€), embodied but not exactly R&B (â€œCiaraâ€), weird without ever being confrontational (â€œItâ€™s Already Doneâ€), and it rides the line between live sound and electronic manipulation like it didnâ€™t exist. She wants to practice self-care (â€œSelfish Soulâ€), but she also just wants to â€œhave my titties outâ€ (â€œNBPQ [Topless]â€), and over the course of 55 minutes, she makes you wonder if those arenâ€™t at least sometimes the same thing. And the albumâ€™s sheer variety isnâ€™t so much an expression of what Parks wants to try as the multitudes she already contains.
entries.title: Natural Brown Prom Queen

DJ/producer Teneil Throssell calls her debut album under the alias HAAi â€œa hyperactive journey that feels like a real reflection of who I am.â€ While that description rings true in some of her frantic breakbeats and other concussive blasts, Throssell also excels at downtempo softness and many subtle textures in between those poles. Formerly the guitarist/vocalist for Sydney, Australia, shoegaze trio Dark Bells, she relocated to London and made a name for herself as a DJ thanks to meticulous crate-digging and trippy flourishes she adds to her sets. Both qualities shine on this album, with lead single â€œBodies of Waterâ€ memorably contrasting Throssellâ€™s slow, dreamy vocals with crackling techno motifs. Baby, Weâ€™re Ascending also boasts high-profile collaborators, from ambient keyboardist/composer Jon Hopkins on the radiant title track to Hot Chipâ€™s Alexis Taylor on the string-swept â€œBiggest Mood Everâ€. Meanwhile, spoken-word poet Kai-Isaiah Jamal and singer Obi Franky hold hypnotic sway over assorted slippery contours on â€œHuman Soundâ€.
entries.title: Baby, We're Ascending

entries.notes:
Absurdly impressive album from this Welshman. Took him 10 years according to the reviews, while in the meantime working on album for FKA twigs and the likes.
This album is innovative in so many ways; the use of electronics in an almost classical music kind of way. Famous number are of cours Joy Squad (already discovered in mixes from Jamie XX and others) and Black Rainbow but all tracks on this album have their own beauty.

From Pitchfork:
â€œArriving a full 10 years after his debut single, Welsh producer Lewis Robertsâ€™ first album is a bravura display of brain-bending editing thatâ€™s more concerned with big feelings.â€

Another review:
â€œWelsh producer Lewis Roberts â€“ aka Koreless â€“ released his debut single a decade ago. There have been a couple more singles and even a couple of EPs since â€“ but this is his debut full-length album. A lot of time has been taken refining his sound, as when he arrived on the scene, the result is a project that has its own distinct sound but takes from many forms, not just dub/dance/ambient/techno/house worlds but also contemporary classical.

They say you canâ€™t be all things to all people but I wonder if Agor is an argument very nearly against that â€“ thereâ€™s all sorts here for sure. Opener, Yonder, is barely ever with us, some ambient thumps signaling an arrival. But when it folds over into Black Rainbow we have a kind of clipped techno, that has no actual driving pulse but is all forward momentum. Itâ€™s like Oneohtrix Point Never and John Hopkins wrestling over control of how best to steer and shape an Omni Trio remix. And thatâ€™s a place Iâ€™m very happy to be.

But then another result. Primes is barely a minute long and seems to exist to palette-cleanse as much as anything.

Across the last decade Roberts has earned income and honed skills producing for acts on the pop part of the dance spectrum or at the dance end of the pop spectrum, or however you might say it, people like FKA Twiggs â€“ itâ€™s not just been an earner, itâ€™s been how he has shaped his sound and ideas. Though thereâ€™s no pop remnants here â€“ instead we get â€œserious composerâ€ mode after our intro notes.

White Picket Fence features a wordless soprano voice fitting in and around the debris of a broken techno track. Itâ€™s exhilarating, and again the music rolls over into Act(s), a soft comedown ahead of the next new wave of music â€“ the more playful Joy Squad. Guest vocals are chopped and diced and sprinkled across this song and also Frozen and Shellshock before the very soundtrack-y Hance, our final reset before this brief albumâ€™s longest track, a closing piece of cut-up collage called Strangers.
Itâ€™s sound-art but thereâ€™s always the feeling of forward movement. Itâ€™s dance music but no one would ever actually â€˜danceâ€™ to it. Itâ€™s as serious as Michael Nyman or Philip Glass or Steve Reich but more likely to be embraced by fans of Aphex Twin and Daniel Lopatin and Jenny Hval. I think itâ€™s mesmeric, absolutely wonderful.â€
entries.title: Agor
