entries.notes: Long before he made his name at jazzâ€™s vanguard, editing together off-the-cuff live sessions like a hip-hop beatmaker, drummer and producer, Makaya McCraven set out to create a comprehensive record of his collaborative processâ€”a testament to the intuition of improvisation. Its sessions recorded over the course of seven years, between multiple projects and releases, In These Times is McCravenâ€™s sixth album as a bandleader, and it showcases the virtuosic instrumentalists he has spent his career building an almost telepathic bond withâ€”bassist Junius Paul and guitarist Jeff Parker among them. Itâ€™s also the warmest and most enveloping album heâ€™s produced to date. Frenetic beat-splicing might underpin the polyrhythms of tracks such as â€œSeventh Stringâ€ and â€œThis Place That Placeâ€, but the soft melodies played by Parker and harpist Brandee Younger always permeateâ€”a reminder of the clarity of the moment of creation, rather than its post-production manipulation. Indeed, In These Times is a reflection of the past decade of McCravenâ€™s instrumental expertise, but itâ€™s also a powerful reminder of the freedom inherent in this time, in the here and now of making music together, when the artist lets go and surrounds us with the ineffable beauty of collective creation.
entries.title: In These Times

entries.notes: In early 2021, Tom and Ed Russell were working on a mix for the iconic London club fabric. They knew they wanted a particular tune included, but simply couldnâ€™t find the track anywhere or remember its name. Faced with a deadline and an endless dig through disc logs, the pair changed their approach: They would themselves write the song they could hear. The track became June 2021 single â€œSo U Knoâ€â€”an insidious, addictive banger thatâ€™s a cornerstone of the Russellsâ€™ debut album as Overmono. Itâ€™s an anecdote that reveals a great deal about the brothersâ€™ practical mindset and prodigious abilities. Veterans of the UK dance scene (Tom, the elder Russell, released techno as Truss, while Ed put out drum â€™nâ€™ bass as Tessela), the Welsh-raised producers combine for something special here. Good Lies is an extraordinary electronic record: a genre-defying set glistening with purpose, poise and dance-floor delirium. â€œThe main anchor for the album isnâ€™t genre-based, itâ€™s an emotional place,â€ Ed tells Apple Music. â€œItâ€™s a particular emotional sense that we try and achieve with a lot of our musicâ€”depending on what mood youâ€™re in on that day, you could interpret that state in a few different ways.â€ Tom is able to pinpoint the origins to that â€œemotional ambiguityâ€. â€œI think our formative experiences of partying in the Welsh countryside had a massive impact on us,â€ he says. â€œWhen you have the sun going down and the sun coming up, and those emotions of somewhere between euphoria, slight sadness that the nightâ€™s coming an end but a real sense of optimism that youâ€™re going into a new day. These sorts of weird crossover points are what we try and find in how we put our music together.â€ Read on for the brothersâ€™ track-by-track guide. â€œFeelings Plainâ€ Ed Russell: â€œIt was originally going to close the album. We wanted to see if we could make a sort of plainsong piece of musicâ€”13th-century church music, where someone would be singing one note over and over and then someone else joins in, and everyoneâ€™s singing these cyclical things. But when it all comes together, they start cycling differently and you get this big wash of voices. But we wanted to try and do a sort of R&B take on plainsongâ€”it was one of the songs that had a more conceptual start to it.â€ Tom Russell: â€œIt was the furthest weâ€™d gotten in terms of direct new avenues that we might explore. Itâ€™s a bold statement of intent to start.â€ â€œArla Fearnâ€ ER: â€œWhen did you first write this bassline, Tom?â€ TR: â€œAbout 1976. No, I think it was about 15 years ago.â€ ER: â€œI would tell Tom itâ€™s the best thing heâ€™d ever written. Itâ€™s got so much mood and character and just sounds so satisfying to me.â€ TR: â€œI know Ed meant it as a compliment but I kept on taking it as a bit of a diss really. But I finally gave in.â€ ER: â€œWe spent ages processing the drums and then Tom sampled the Geovarn vocal and came up with the insane outro. The track is at 135 BPM, and by the end itâ€™s at 170 BPM, but you never really notice itâ€™s changedâ€”it just flips the vocal into a different spot. We really wanted the album to be a place where tracks would often morph into something completely different. That itâ€™s bubbling over with ideas.â€ â€œGood Liesâ€ ER: â€œWe went through a phase of trying not to sample every Smerz song because they just had so many good hooks. Theyâ€™re incredible at writing these top lines that sound straight off early-2000s garage records, but not in a pastiche way. We had the vocal from [2018 Smerz track] â€œNo harmâ€ and spent a lot of time chopping it into the phrasing we wanted and creating a hook out of this little section that had jumped out at us. The demo for the instrumental then came together in a day, but there was an 18-month, almost two-year period from writing the demo to coming back and starting to really chip away at it.â€ â€œGood Lies (Outro)â€ TR: â€œWhen we were writing the â€˜Good Liesâ€™ instrumental, we thought weâ€™d see if we could flip it and turn the vibe on its head into something moodier. Itâ€™s always going back to that ambiguity with us. Thereâ€™s something of that in the Good Lies title. What constitutes a good lie?â€ â€œWalk Thru Waterâ€ (feat. St. Panther) TR: â€œEd was at my studio in February [2022], and we were battening down the hatches for Storm Eunice.â€ ER: â€œIt was this quite nice feeling of, â€˜All right, thereâ€™s a storm coming, weâ€™ve got loads of snacks and a few drinks, the place to ourselves, and we canâ€™t go anywhere.â€™ Tom had written these really beautiful chords and Iâ€™d kept saying I wanted to do something with them. We got really stoned while the rain was coming down, listening to these chords, and we came across the St. Panther vocal.â€ TR: â€œI then started doing the beat on the Pulsarâ€”which is a drum machine thatâ€™s quite difficult to tame but on certain things it just works beautifully.â€ â€œCold Bloodedâ€ TR: â€œThis started out as something quite different. It dawned on us that weâ€™d written this massive IDM tune.â€ ER: â€œIt was a bit too nice, wasnâ€™t it?â€ TR: â€œIt was this late-â€™90s breakdance thingâ€”not really the vibe we should be going for.â€ ER: â€œI had this Kindora sample that Iâ€™d wanted to use for ages, and then Tom sent me this slowed-down version of â€˜Cold Bloodedâ€™ with the new drums and I realised itâ€™d be fucking killer. It then became a month of last-minute adjustments, which we sometimes get ourselves into a bit of a hole with. Tweaking everything until the last.â€ â€œSkulledâ€ ER: â€œWe had the Kelly Erez sample put away into our sample folder. And then we built a drum machineâ€”a copy of a â€™70s drum machine called the Syncussion, made by Pearl, the drum kit manufacturer. It [the Syncussion] was meant to sound like a normal drum kit, and it sounds so far away from real drums itâ€™s insane. We spent a couple of weeks trying to make our version sound like weâ€™d soldered it not quite right. It has this weird, sort of dry, alien, â€™80s vibe to it. Like with all our stuff, itâ€™s processed so heavily.â€ TR: â€œEd has come up with this mad compression chain, which you can basically put any sort of drums into and you get this massive wall of noise.â€ ER: â€œI said earlier the best thing Tom has written was the bassline on â€˜Arla Fearnâ€™, but Iâ€™ve changed my mind now: Itâ€™s the piano outro to â€˜Skulledâ€™. We both loved the idea of the song ending like a classic balladâ€”a CÃ©line Dion tune.â€ â€œSugarushhhâ€ TR: â€œWe liked the idea of trying to shoehorn in a screaming 303 to the album somewhere.â€ ER: â€œTomâ€™s good at doing these quite irregular things that you donâ€™t immediately notice. This, if you actually count it out, is in some weird time signature and itâ€™s cycling every nine bars. It was also really important that we had this abrasive, aggressive 303 line being offset completely with a really beautiful vocal.â€ â€œCalonâ€ ER: â€œTom played me the first iteration of this in the back of a van on the way to a festival in Minehead. Weâ€™ve sampled Joe Trufant a few times before and we liked the idea of there being a few familiar voices on the album.â€ TR: â€œWe then hired a studio in Ibiza and Ed had the idea of making the beat much slower. It became this big, slowed-down house tuneâ€”it dropped to something like 110 BPM.â€ ER: â€œWe were in a US club sound-checking and played through some tunes from the album. Hearing it on the club system we were like, â€˜Fuck me!â€™ Itâ€™s this sneaky banger.â€ â€œIs Uâ€ ER: â€œWeâ€™ve both been massive Tirzah fans since the start, and one day the â€˜All I want is youâ€™ line from â€˜Gladlyâ€™ just jumped out of the speaker at us. We then spent ages trying to make the beat on this mono machine we have, which has all these really shit â€™80s drum samples. We just mangled them until we had the beat, and then chopped up the vocal to get what we felt was a really strong and more confrontational delivery. Tom then put these lush chords in the breakdown and it opens the track up, like the sun coming out from behind a cloud.â€ TR: â€œItâ€™s amazing when a track starts to take on a life of its own. Playing this out and seeing the reaction gives me goosebumps every time.â€ â€œVermonlyâ€ ER: â€œA lot of our tracks will be written on just one piece of gear and we see what you can do with it. I had bought Tom a synth for his birthday, but when I gave it to him he said he wasnâ€™t going to be in the studio for a few days, so I asked if I could take the synth I had just given him. I sent him a really rough 16-bar loop with the main melodic ideas, and he did the rest, really.â€ TR: â€œTracks like this are really important to us. They might get lost on an EP. Itâ€™s not always about writing dance-floor bangers.â€ â€œSo U Knoâ€ ER: â€œWe were doing this mix for fabric and we both knew we wanted a very particular tune in the mix but couldnâ€™t find it. So we basically just thought, â€˜Fuck it, itâ€™ll be quicker to write something ourselves.â€™ I had a chopped-up vocal and a rough beat going, played it to Tom, who went straight over to a Jupiter-6 synth and immediately played the bassline before doing the same with the chords.â€ â€œCalling Outâ€ TR: â€œEd had suggested to try and sample something by slowthai and I managed to find this little [section] I really liked from quite an obscure track called â€˜Dead Leavesâ€™. I loved the line â€˜Iâ€™m like the sun, I rise up and then gone.â€™ Then we combined it with a CASISDEAD and dâ€™Eon sample and it really started to make sense. I have a tendency to overcomplicate things, but Ed is often able to say, â€˜We donâ€™t need thatâ€™, or â€˜Change a snare from there to thereâ€™. A tiny idea or decision can make such a huge difference.â€ ER: â€œI remember when Tom sent me the chords for the end and I felt like it reminded me of old Radioheadâ€”the perfect way to close the album.â€

entries.notes: From Pitchfork: â€œMore often than not, Menneskekollektivetâ€™s inherently unfinished quality makes it feel naturalistic, deeply human. If Menneskekollektivet is about the sensuality of meandering through oneâ€™s artistic process, then â€œReal Life,â€ is the recordâ€™s most fully realized, gorgeous cut. entries.notes: The caveat with mentioning the 30 years of history John McEntire and Sam Prekop shared before making Sons Of is that the album doesnâ€™t exactly sound like anything theyâ€™ve done before. McEntire is the drummer of the adventurous, anything-but-rock band Tortoise and the Prekop-fronted Sea and Cake; Prekop is a singer-songwriter who rebutted the harshness of â€™90s indie rock with music influenced by lounge jazz and bossa nova. Sons Of, by contrast, is made up of four lengthy synth improvisations combining early house, indie pop and the spacey, ruminative side of IDM. The connective tissue is in the approach, which is somehow adventurous but gentle, experimental but restrained. And while everything here has narrative momentum, their shared language is thick enough that they sound better the longer they go (the sunglasses-indoors sci-fi of â€œAscending by Nightâ€ and the 24-minute â€œA Yellow Robeâ€).

entries.notes: Thereâ€™s a haunting intensity and rare poetic beauty about Ryuichi Sakamotoâ€™s blend of ambient sounds, stripped down to the bare essentials of melody and rhythm. And for all its simplicity, this is an album that is profoundly moving. His dozen pieces, created spontaneously in March 2021 during the early stages of convalescence from major cancer surgery, speak of lifeâ€™s fragility and of musicâ€™s power to comfort, console, even to heal. It feels almost intrusive at first to listen to what originated as private musical thoughts, conceived on synthesiser and piano out of an innate need for the presence of pure, unadorned sounds. Sakamotoâ€™s choice of 12 favourite sketches, each named for its date of composition, charts the stages of his recovery, from pieces infused with his laboured breathing to a sublime final sequence of impressionistic miniatures.

â€œIf I ever win a Grammy, Iâ€™m gonna thank him,â€ Queens-born vocalist, producer and multi-disciplinary artist Yaya Bey tells Apple Music about one of the many songs on Remember Your North Star inspired by an unnamed ex-lover. He was a music industry player and that relationship, which lasted some three years, revealed many things to Beyâ€”not just about the industry itself, but about who she is and what she values. â€œIt was like, â€˜Well, where am I going? Where am I headed and what should I remember?â€™ And I guess in trying to move towards loveâ€”love for self, love romantically, platonicallyâ€”Iâ€™m remembering that thatâ€™s where Iâ€™m going. Thatâ€™s my North Star.â€ While that relationship opened her eyes to some of the industryâ€™sâ€”and men at largeâ€™sâ€”more sordid practices, Bey managed to keep her joy intact, delivering a robust collection of music that spans Billie Holiday-inspired jazz crooning, lovers rock reggae and the bubbling form of South African house, amapiano. Within these spoonfuls of sugar, Bey supplies medicine aplenty, lambasting the intrinsically toxic systems that would, at one time, have her questioning her own self-worth. â€œTo be a woman in this male-dominated industry means you get judged and valued by things that really donâ€™t matter,â€ she says. â€œBut I canâ€™t have apprehension about what I do with my music because itâ€™s the only place I have a voice. Being a Black woman, an up-and-coming artist, and especially in my thirties, the only place I have a voice is in my music. I canâ€™t be silent there. Iâ€™ll just disappear.â€ Below, Bey takes us through some of the key tracks on Remember Your North Star, a project that casts her more visible than ever. â€œIntroâ€ â€œSo, [talk show host] Wendy Williams had said some shit about [vegan lifestyle influencer] Tabitha Brown on her show. And then Tabitha Brown retaliated in this way that insinuated Wendy Williams doesnâ€™t know love or doesnâ€™t have anyone to love her. And then someone on Black Twitter tweeted that even though Tabitha Brown didnâ€™t say very much, we all knew it was an insult because we all kind of know Black women have a wound around not being loved and not knowing love. And that got me to thinking about how Black women respond to that. Thereâ€™s the â€˜city girlâ€™ approach, which is like, â€˜Fuck love, just provide for me financiallyâ€™â€”and all of it is defense mechanismsâ€”because a lot of times weâ€™re afraid to ask for the things that we want, or we assume that we canâ€™t get the things that we want, emotionally. Iâ€™m saying, â€˜N****s going to n***a, so you might as well get paid.â€™ Thatâ€™s just my take on not feeling secure that men will show up in a way that is supportive of my emotional needs.â€ â€œbig daddy yaâ€ â€œI was having this realisation that most all of my problems can somehow be tied to either racism, patriarchy or capitalismâ€”literally everything in my life thatâ€™s going wrong. And as it pertains to patriarchy, misogyny and all that shit, itâ€™s always just fucking men at the root of my problems. Even when itâ€™s a woman, itâ€™s still some woman enacting patriarchy, enacting misogyny. What I learned about the male ego is just to laugh at it because itâ€™s utterly ridiculous. It isnâ€™t built on supporting the collective, uplifting the collective. Itâ€™s built on scarcity and thatâ€™s why itâ€™s so fragile. And so, â€˜big daddy yaâ€™ is just me mocking men.â€ â€œnobody knowsâ€ â€œI had just signed to Ninja Tune, and they sent me to D.C. to start the album. It was one of the first songs that I wrote. I had been going back and forth with this guy for three years, and we werenâ€™t in contact at the time. And he was bouncing back and forth between me and this other woman. I was really fucked up because I had lost my job. Like, the song starts off, â€˜I ainâ€™t paid my rent in three monthsâ€™â€”that was very true for me. And this guy, the last time I saw him, he was rubbing it in my face that [his other woman] is a doctor and Iâ€™m unemployed. I have to work so hard under the system of capitalism to be worthy. I canâ€™t just wake up in the morning and be worthy. I have to have all of these things to be worthy of love, to be worthy of a roof over my head. Me just being me is not enough for this worldâ€”I think itâ€™s a song that means the most to me on the album because I was at my lowest point, but I was still fighting for myself.â€ â€œalrightâ€ â€œI was listening to a lot of Frankie Beverly & Maze, and what I like about Frankie Beverly & Maze is that they make music to uplift the spirit. I knew I needed live musicians because a lot of the album was made on a 404 or from sliced samples. Itâ€™s all digital. [My friend] Temi introduced me to [co-producer] Aja Grant, and it was easy. It was a jam session sort of thing. I just hummed out the melody lines and they picked it up, and then added to it and extended it.â€ â€œmeet me in brooklynâ€ â€œMy family is from Barbados. I always say that Iâ€™m an African American of Western Indian descent. I grew up deeply in both cultures. So, I felt like I needed to put some of that on the album because itâ€™s part of who I am. And the album, overall, is about me dealing with and navigating misogyny externally and internally, and even internalised misogyny through my romantic dealings. And some of romance is about fun, like when you first meet someone at a partyâ€”like, the first time I ever danced with a boy was at a reggae party. So, itâ€™s in my DNA, and culturally and socially growing up in New York, and I wanted to include that sound.â€ â€œpour upâ€ (feat. DJ Nativesun) â€œMy friend Chris is an amazing DJ, and he plays a lot of house and dance, and I was working on a song with another artist at a session in D.C. at this big house that had all these little studio rooms. Chris comes into the session, and he has a track. At first, I was afraid because itâ€™s amapiano. But when I think about the music thatâ€™s coming out of Africa, thatâ€™s dancehall, thatâ€™s soca, itâ€™s house musicâ€”and I think, once we get past the whole diaspora wars thing, all of us fighting for the scraps, weâ€™re all Africans at the very bottom of this capitalist, imperialist food chain. Because you canâ€™t talk about Fela without talking about James Brown without talking about [Wizkidâ€™s] Made in Lagosâ€”that was an Afrobeats album because it was made by an African from Nigeria, but if we take that away, that was a dancehall record. At first, I was afraid that I would experience some backlash, but when I thought about it, Iâ€™m like amapiano is house music, and Iâ€™m allowed to be a part of the conversation.â€ â€œrepriseâ€ â€œSometimes relationships that you go through are a catalyst for you to get to know yourself more, or for you to really see where youâ€™re playing yourself, where youâ€™re doubting yourself, where you are not showing up for yourself. Itâ€™s really about how I had a lack of self-worth, and I was afraid to see myself as capable. And I had this other song where I was, like, tearing his ass a new one. But it was coming from a place that was more about bashing him than it was about uplifting me. And it isnâ€™t really my desire to bash anyone. So, I didnâ€™t put the song out and, instead, I wrote â€˜repriseâ€™, which is more reflecting on how I got to where I am, and the things that Iâ€™ve seen. It gave me a space to even have compassion for him because heâ€™s somebody with his own trauma and insecurities that are informing the way heâ€™s moving through the world.â€ â€œrolling stonerâ€ â€œI probably smoke the heaviest when Iâ€™m going through shit. Two months before the pandemic started, I was working 13-hour shifts in a homeless shelter, seeing crazy shit. Iâ€™m riddled with guilt because Iâ€™m working there, and I feel like Iâ€™m a part of the problem. Even though Iâ€™m just an art teacher there, itâ€™s still like I shouldnâ€™t be here because this is hella problematic. I come home, I smoke my life away, I make music, I go to sleep for two hours. I do it again. I mean, I had smoked before then, but that was my introduction to, â€˜Now Iâ€™m a pothead.â€™â€ â€œiâ€™m certain sheâ€™s thereâ€ â€œSo, my parents were teenage parents. My mom, she didnâ€™t raise me. She came from different circumstances. Her family was not as supportive. Her mom died. Her dad was just really disappointed that she had a baby so young. And my dad, on the other hand, he just had more support, more help raising me. Either people donâ€™t ever talk about my mom at all, like sheâ€™s this thing that never happened, or they have terrible things to say about her. Which, as a child, it fucked with my own self-image, to have this mom that is a pariah, I guess. So, as I got older, I realised that some of that is misogyny. And I just wanted to address that.â€ â€œstreet fighter bluesâ€œ â€œâ€˜Street fighter bluesâ€™ was the starting point of the album. I had someone else that I was supposed to work with, and the session was a nightmare. I ended up snatching my equipment out the wall and leaving. But then, I called my friend Nate Jarvis, who is a longtime collaborator, and once I got in the right environment, it was easy. I was listening to a lot of Billie Holiday and Sarah Vaughan, which is what informed the vocals. And then, I went on the 404 and sampled my voice, busted out a drum pattern and it was over with.â€ â€œmama loves her sonâ€ â€œA long, long time ago, I had this conversation with my friend, and she was like her motherâ€”always kind of taught her not to trust women. And weâ€™re taught not to trust women and not to trust ourselves because we see other women as competition for male validation. Itâ€™s not even just romantic male validation, itâ€™s just love from men, acknowledgement from menâ€”in the workplace, in friendships, in social settings, on social media, in relationships, in every power dynamic in marginalised groups. I needed a way to address the way that women act out misogyny.â€ â€œblessingsâ€ â€œI wrote â€˜blessingsâ€™ when I was in D.C. Itâ€™s one of the first songs I wrote. At the time, I was not talking to the same person Iâ€™ve been talking about. We were not on speaking terms. I guess I was going through breakup blues. I felt like I wasnâ€™t enough for that person, and I was figuring out how to be enough for myself. But at the same time, I was in D.C. A label had paid for me to go out there and make an album. I was too sad to get out of bed, but if I could just get out of this funk and realise thereâ€™s blessings around me, I could find a way to be present for them. And wherever you are, a person needs that. And life goes on, with time, you know?â€
entries.title: Remember Your North Star

entries.notes: Unique, strong and sexyâ€”thatâ€™s how BeyoncÃ© wants you to feel while listening to RENAISSANCE. Crafted during the grips of the pandemic, her seventh solo album is a celebration of freedom and a complete immersion into house and dance that serves as the perfect sound bed for themes of liberation, release, self-assuredness and unfiltered confidence across its 16 tracks. RENAISSANCE is playful and energetic in a way that captures that Friday-night, just-got-paid, anything-can-happen feeling, underscored by reiterated appeals to unyoke yourself from the weight of othersâ€™ expectations and revel in the totality of who you are. From the classic four-on-the-floor house moods of the Robin S.- and Big Freedia-sampling lead single â€œBREAK MY SOULâ€ to the Afro-tech of the Grace Jones- and Tems-assisted â€œMOVEâ€ and the funky, rollerskating disco feeling of â€œCUFF ITâ€, this is a massive yet elegantly composed buffet of sound, richly packed with anthemic morsels that pull you in. There are soft moments here, too: â€œI know you canâ€™t help but to be yourself around me,â€ she coos on â€œPLASTIC OFF THE SOFAâ€, the kind of warm, whispers-in-the-ear love song youâ€™d expect to hear at a summer cookoutâ€”complete with an intricate interplay between vocals and guitar that gives BeyoncÃ© a chance to showcase some incredible vocal dexterity. â€œCHURCH GIRLâ€ fuses R&B, gospel and hip-hop to tell a survivorâ€™s story: â€œI'm finally on the other side/I finally found the extra smiles/Swimming through the oceans of tears we cried.â€ An explicit celebration of Blackness, â€œCOZYâ€ is the mantra of a woman who has nothing to prove to anyoneâ€”â€œComfortable in my skin/Cozy with who I am,â€ â€ BeyoncÃ© muses on the chorus. And on â€œPURE/HONEYâ€, BeyoncÃ© immerses herself in ballroom culture, incorporating drag performance chants and a Kevin Aviance sample on the first half that give way to the disco-drenched second half, cementing the song as an immediate dance-floor favourite. Itâ€™s the perfect lead-in to the album closer â€œSUMMER RENAISSANCEâ€, which propels the dreamy escapist disco of Donna Summerâ€™s â€œI Feel Loveâ€ even further into the future.
entries.title: RENAISSANCE

entries.notes:
Like Lâ€™Rain, Fatigue is marbled with personal recordings: Dishes being washed in the sink beneath a piano melody on â€œNeed Be,â€ a voicemail from her mother buried in â€œBlame Me.â€ The clips imbue the music with fleeting traces of closeness and familiarity. Cheek approaches them from a distance, recontextualizing some of the most heartfelt or difficult moments of her life in song. The mercurial, six-minute highlight â€œFind Itâ€ begins downcast, with a metronomic synth loop and the repeated mantra, â€œMake a way out of no way.â€ Screams echo through the sluggish beat as coming through a wall; the dust settles on an organist and singer performing the gospel song â€œI Wonâ€™t Complain,â€ recorded at the funeral of a family friend. Cheek intones over it until the song crests in a rapturous, overwhelming finale, with no less than 13 musicians contributing to the commotion. Itâ€™s easily the most poignant song she has ever made, a deeply felt, Biblically minded portrait of forging a path out of darkness. Yet the journey has room for lightness and humor, too, like the â€œoopsâ€ that slips into the end of â€œWalk Throughâ€ or the wacky vocal affect of a former roommate on â€œLove Her.â€ On the brief â€œBlack Clapâ€ and the rhythmic, low-lit â€œSuck Teeth,â€ Cheek incorporates the percussive sounds of a handclap game she made up with multi-instrumentalist Ben Chapoteau-Katz, a way to pay tribute to the joyful sound of childhood hand games played by Black girls.

Cheek upends expectations in more direct pop and dance traditions, too. On â€œTwo Face,â€ a roving piano line and stuttering samples melt into a soulful, psychedelic throb as she ruminates on a failed friendship. â€œI canâ€™t build no new nothing no new life no new nothing for me,â€ she trills in a singsong cadence, the words bouncing over oscillated coos. The lyrics on the tense â€œKill Selfâ€ are even more unforgiving: â€œDid you see me chew myself out?â€ she asks, voice rippling in a cascade over shuffling percussion. â€œHear the gnawing?â€ At once the albumâ€™s darkest and most propulsive moment, â€œKill Selfâ€ eventually assumes a seething dancefloor pulse, bending skillfully toward structure without abandoning Cheekâ€™s wandering impulses.

Fatigue ends with the beatific â€œTake Two,â€ a spare reconfiguration of â€œBatâ€ from Lâ€™Rain. She repurposes the song in a similar way to her field recordings, as raw material to mold into an unfamiliar shape. Stripped bare of percussion and transformed into an airy, droning spiritual, Cheekâ€™s voice unfurls in billowy, Auto-Tuned tones as she repeats the words, â€œI am not prepared for what is going to happen to me.â€ In her skyward voice, the sentiment is more life-affirming than terrifying, suggestive of infinite possibilities. There is no fixed road toward healing, Fatigue reassures us; there is only the way forward.
entries.title: Fatigue

When Fred again.. began work on Actual Life 2 (February 22 - October 15 2021), the BRIT Award-winning producer saw it as a way to close the book on the most traumatic period of his life. Still processing the grief of losing a loved one, he imagined that making his second solo album would be a way to get through and move on. Instead, he learned that life doesnâ€™t work that way. Grief has long legs. â€œI was like, â€˜Yeah, OK, this is going to be the journey through grief, from it being there and unbearable to it all being solved,â€ Fred Gibson, the man behind the handle, tells Apple Music. â€œBy the end, I was like, â€˜This is an ever-going thing, and this is just one chapter of it.â€™â€ Following up on his debut, Actual Life (April 14 - December 17 2020), released in April 2021, itâ€™s a soulful and emotional dance record. Blending euphoric bangers and atmospheric electronica, it confirms the producer whoâ€™s collaborated with Headie One, Stormzy, Romy, Ed Sheeran and FKA Twigs as an exhilarating artist in his own right.
Like its predecessor, Actual Life 2 (February 22 - October 15 2021) uses snippets and samples from real-life events and conversations as the foundation for intricate soundscapes. â€œAs soon as I make a song, I start dragging in shit from my iPhone, a bunch of voice notes that Iâ€™ve recorded from around the world,â€ says Gibson. â€œI just love the way that feels, so much more than opening up some dry synth and playing some notes.â€ Gibson says Actual Life is an ongoing project, each LP a snapshot of his life in that particular era. â€œIâ€™m going to do this forever now. Itâ€™ll be like chapters. Iâ€™m obsessed with it.â€ Let Fred again.. guide you through this phase, track by track.
â€œFebruary 2nd 2021â€ â€œItâ€™s the first sample I found. Itâ€™s picking up from where the last album ended, beginning to try and move on from a thing. It felt very clearly like it needed to be at the beginning.â€
â€œCatrin (The City)â€ â€œI thought this lyric was just really beautiful and very much resonated with me. I adore London, and I always have, and I always will. I make most of my music just out in the city, just on benches or in museums. My real brother on this record felt like the city. It just felt very clear and honest to me that this was how the album needed to begin. I only sing four lines in this tune, but theyâ€™re like flashbacks. I see them as being montage flashbacks at different moments from last year. And then it moves forward again.â€
â€œRoze (Forgive)â€ â€œThis is a sample Iâ€™d found on Instagramâ€”someone in his bedroom singing this song. To me the feeling of it was itâ€™s still not moving forward, itâ€™s still reflecting on the past. But it was at least a step in there being a nostalgia over itâ€”it wasnâ€™t present tense. It was like, â€˜This is whatâ€™s happenedâ€™. The main breakthrough on that was finding the thing of doing it with the strings. Iâ€™m going to record a version of it actually with a string orchestra, which will be fun.â€
â€œGigi (What You Went Through)â€ â€œThis is [London singer-songwriter] Gigi Moss, a sample of her singing at a pub. Sometimes itâ€™s very much as simple as just stumbling across someone saying what Iâ€™d want to say and then Iâ€™ll be like, â€˜OK, thank you for holding my hand through that. You need to carry on helping me, and I can sample it so I can sing around it.â€™ I find it hard to go from a white, blank page to singing it myself off of nothing. But if thereâ€™s someone else there singing it with me, I see it as a safety blanket.â€
â€œKahan (Last Year)â€ [feat. Kodak Black] â€œFor a while, there was a version of this where I wanted it to feel like I was out of my mind, chaotic and claustrophobic. Then my brother, who I work with on lots of music, was like, â€˜What if you make the opposite interpretation, just a piano?â€™ As soon as it was on piano, it was able to breathe. And then I was like, â€˜OK, I would want to sing on this now. I need to tell my part of the story.â€™ It becomes more of a duet. The whole record is very much in memory mode of the previous year, and I think this song summarises that.â€
â€œTate (How I Feel)â€ â€œThe lyric is saying, â€˜I donâ€™t know how I feelâ€™â€”just that over and over again. The music sounds more positive, which I think was just how I was feeling. I couldnâ€™t work out if it was a good or a bad thing. I think, in hindsight, it was just a pending thing. I thought I was through it. I was like, â€˜Weâ€™re getting to the good bit and to a good state of mindâ€™. But that was definitely, definitely not the case.â€
â€œHannah (The Sun)â€ â€œItâ€™s in the same portion of time [of â€˜Tate (How I Feel)â€™], of that feeling of thinking the sunâ€™s coming through, thereâ€™s an optimism here. It was short-lived but real. I like things when the answer isnâ€™t, â€˜Yeah, and then that was that and thatâ€™s it, doneâ€™. I like it more when itâ€™s like, â€˜It really felt like it was that, but it was a total fallacy, and you were totally wrong two weeks later.â€™ Iâ€™m into that side of it; it feels more human.â€
â€œCarlos (Interlude)â€ â€œCarlos is the OG. Heâ€™s the first person I met that I sampled. And I adore him and feel forever indebted to him. Iâ€™m going to try and track him down at the beginning of next year when Iâ€™m in America. Every album will sample Carlos somewhere. I like the challenge of finding new ways of using this little, 14-second video I have with Carlos. Iâ€™ve made 20 songs out of it.â€
â€œFaisal (Envelops Me)â€ â€œThis is probably the song that means the most to me on the record. The verse is very much about the traumas of the year before, but I think the chorus is representing a hug of the beautiful people I have around me. I think I was coming out of the short-lived sun moment and realising that this would be a lifelong thing. I think traumas and grief, it gets less frenetic and thereâ€”but then it just becomes part of you. It doesnâ€™t just disappear. It just becomes you. And thatâ€™s not a bad thing; itâ€™s just a true thing. I was making peace with the fact that there would be no leaving this behind.â€
â€œTayla (Every Night)â€ â€œI love this sample. Itâ€™s of this amazing singer called Tayla Parx. Itâ€™s a song that we actually wrote together a time ago, but it was a balladâ€”itâ€™s a song Iâ€™ve made quite a few versions of. This one felt right for this moment in this record. Before it picked up, I wanted it to have this stiller, more washed, padded moment of just a few lyrics before it starts to get some momentum.â€
â€œTanya (Maybe Life)â€ â€œThis is the beginning of a form of optimism. I like it sounding like all these loads of different voices, loads of different chops, loads of different people around you trying to help in different ways. Thereâ€™s a chop of Tanya going, â€˜Maybe life ainâ€™t as bad as it seems.â€™ Thereâ€™s a chop of Romy from The xx going, â€˜You can lean on me, you can lean on me.â€™ Thereâ€™s a chop of a whole host of other stuff, and they were representing the different people around me and the different approaches thatâ€”theyâ€™re all love, but just the different aspects of the people around me.â€
â€œMarco (And Everyone)â€ â€œI love making these reprise songs that summarise all the samples that youâ€™ve heard in the record. On the last record, the reprise song was over this washy pad, and it was very ambient and still, so I was like, â€˜OK, letâ€™s try doing that same thing of finding a song that can incorporate everything youâ€™ve heard, but in the opposite way of a super-driving beat.â€™ Also, I was like, â€˜Weâ€™re picking up now; I want to be building a momentum.â€™â€
â€œBillie (Loving Arms)â€ â€œThis is the real climax of the feeling of letting people help you, the most visceral incarnation of that. It feels like a pinger to meâ€”just a proper, undiluted serotonin hit of falling into someone else. After a year of that whole aspect of things being gone, I think those things are even sweeter. This song felt like the pinnacle of allowing people in.â€
â€œBillie (Interlude)â€ â€œI knew that the record had to end with â€˜Mollieâ€™ because I was absolutely adamant it didnâ€™t end with â€˜Loving Armsâ€™. It was so insincere for it to end on â€˜Loving Armsâ€™ because that so isnâ€™t the truth of the end of the journeyâ€”not that there is an end. I wanted to end â€˜Loving Armsâ€™ in a way that it could get into â€˜Mollieâ€™ without it being too rogue. It needed to just pause for a second to allow it the space to breathe so it could go into that last song.â€
â€œMollie (Hear Your Name)â€ â€œIf â€˜Loving Armsâ€™ is the Saturday night, the reality is much more of a Sunday afternoon. That â€˜Loving Armsâ€™ serotonin hit isnâ€™t a sustainable state of mind. Itâ€™s more like â€˜Mollieâ€™â€”â€˜OK, actually we are more here, and this is our cruise pace and thatâ€™s OK, and weâ€™re going to try and marathon this out as opposed to some little sprint of a gassed-up pingerâ€™s life.â€™â€
â€œ15th October 2021â€ â€œThis is literally just me, very ill in my bed, finishing the record. Itâ€™s just a message to someone, a little minute of stillness after â€˜Mollieâ€™.â€
entries.title: Actual Life 2 (February 2 - October 15 2021)

The artist meditates on grief through intricate blips and beats.

From Pitchfork:

Liv.eâ€™s brilliant second album bends her expressive R&B into fearsome new shapes, acknowledging all the nuance and pain on the long journey to personal truth.

Couldnâ€™t Wait to Tell You, Liv.eâ€™s debut LP, flipped through the pages of her diary quickly enough to animate her scattered musings on young romance while preserving each entryâ€™s distinct perspective. Its allure rested on Liv.eâ€™s charismatic storytelling, in her belief that â€œeverybody got a love storyâ€ and her ability to play every role in those tales herself. Aggressively non-linear and rich in lo-fi charm, Couldnâ€™t Wait to Tell You kept the proceedings light and easy. Even in the albumâ€™s darkest moments, Liv.e never felt more than 30 seconds away from a cathartic breakthrough, rescued by a tempo shift, a false ending, or the affirming words of a guest feature. She tore through dreamy realizations like outfits ripped off a garment rack, theorizing that a change of heart could be as easy as a change of costume.

Girl in the Half Pearl cuts to the scene after the diary slams shut, when your face crashes into the pillow before a long and sleepless night. In place of Couldnâ€™t Wait to Tell Youâ€™s rose-tinted psychedelia, Liv.e builds a mirror, surgically examining the ugliest parts of her subconscious and clawing toward her worst impulses and most frightening thoughts. Healing is a minefield of doubt and confusion, crossed only by necessity. Liv.e doesnâ€™t waste time idealizing the process. â€œWhen I looked inside my brain, there were all these webs of pain,â€ she groans on opener â€œGardetto.,â€ somersaulting over a wave of pitch-shifted oh nos. She strains like a petulant child, burnt out before the work even begins: â€œI just wanna play with my toys/Iâ€™m too young for the worldâ€™s big problems.â€ Girl in the Half Pearl delves into the rich tension between deciding to change and taking the first step, dwelling in both the pain and promise of learning things about yourself that you sometimes wish you could forget. Itâ€™s a mesmerizing documentation of Liv.eâ€™s ongoing rebirth that dares you to keep your eyes open during the scary parts.

Liv.e heads a formidable ensemble of producers in soundtracking Girl in the Half Pearlâ€™s compounding existential crises, eliciting career-high performances from accomplices new and old. Frequent Remi Wolf collaborator Solomonophonic and West Coast new age keyboardist John Carroll Kirby pull out all the stops for the fluorescent â€œWild Animals,â€ wrapping its knowing eye roll to conniving men in trickling piano and the evergreen warmth of a brushed drum backbeat. Ever-reliable L.A. lysergist Mndsgn carves out a sizable chunk of real estate across the record, but lends a particularly inspired hand to â€œFind Out.â€ He digs deep in the crates, unearthing a jazzy, snare-less loop that thumps like an aching heartbeat, giving Liv.eâ€™s decision to trade loveâ€™s rollercoaster for â€œprecious time aloneâ€ the perfect dose of last-kiss sweetness. She walks away, a trilling synthesizer swirls in the mix, and the gut-wrenching resolve of her parting words (â€œI guess weâ€™ll find outâ€¦the hard wayâ€) cuts like a knife.

But true to the recordâ€™s â€œknow thyselfâ€ thesis, Liv.e tackles the bulk of the production solo, rediscovering herself through electronica and noise, and dousing her R&B foundations in a stunning coat of fresh paint. The most satisfying moments push her to undertake fearsome experiments with her voice. She crashes into the breakbeats of â€œGhostâ€ with a metallic howl, roaring with frustration as she bitterly acknowledges her need for securityâ€”and recalls how it was denied to her in the past. â€œI know I said I donâ€™t need the help/Just wanna get back home,â€ she cries, and the syllables begin to catch in her throat before suddenly vanishing, swallowed by grief. On â€œClowns,â€ Liv.e lures you into the tense moment before the emotional dam between two people bursts. At the breaking point, teasing percussion and sickly sweet strings erupt into gory pyrotechnics. â€œCanâ€™t be clowns for this long, so baby what do we make it?â€ she screams, her words sparking against the blown-out crash of the drums.

For years, Liv.e has found a home among some of Black musicâ€™s most critically lauded experimentalists like Earl Sweatshirt, Pink Siifu, and Black Noi$e. If you come to Girl in the Half Pearl looking to find a soothing voice in the wilderness, you will instead find a complex maze of battered beats and warped shouts. The gripping soundscape doesnâ€™t allow you to watch its protagonistâ€™s transformation from the safety of the back rowâ€”it shoves you through the screen. If Liv.eâ€™s going to â€œbreak the mirror 90 timesâ€ because she canâ€™t stand to see herself, youâ€™re going to help her sweep up the glass.

When Liv.e announced Girl in the Half Pearl, she described it as a send-off for â€œpeople pleasingâ€ behavior, and the album succeeds precisely because it feels so authentic and uncompromising: designed to serve only the needs of its creator. In burying the tender apology of â€œSnowing!â€ under a blanket of static, in applying a different vocal style and post-production technique to each vocal line of â€œSix Weeks,â€ in refusing to condense the long struggle of finding yourself into a catchy chorus, Liv.e affects an irresistibly magnetic anti-charm. She leads by example, by meeting herself in the present and holding her own gaze. Girl in the Half Pearl doesnâ€™t fixate on the light at the end of the tunnel. It chisels into the rock slowly, humming along to the sound of each strike.
entries.title: Girl In The Half Pearl

entries.notes: â€œâ€˜Do the wrong thingâ€™ is my thing,â€ TJ â€œLil Silvaâ€ Carter tells Apple Music. â€œBecause everyone thinks, â€˜Oh, we've got to use this bassline, or do that sound.â€™ But actually, we should all strive to be in the now. What feels good, right now?â€ More than a decade on from his teen emergence in the UKâ€™s Funky House scene, Lil Silvaâ€™s genre-bending odyssey lands here: a debut LP hosting a vigorous bout between ego and self-doubt. â€œIt's all self work,â€ he says. "But thatâ€™s important, because how much time do you want to invest in yourself? What do you want to unlock in your brain that you havenâ€™t? How much are you worth?" These questions arose for the producer, singer, songwriter and DJ throughout the course of deep meditation and Theta healing (an energy healing technique and spiritual philosophy), and lay central to his ongoing exploration of the self. Yesterday Is Heavy crafts a moving elegy that explores feelings of alienation (â€œBackwardsâ€), raw emotion (â€œAnother Sketchâ€) and disjointedness (â€œStillâ€) experienced throughout lockdown, and remedied in rich, experimental textures that draw on the sincerity of Silvaâ€™s bluesy vocals and arrangement style, plus some eclectic collaborations (including standout moments with Sampha and Little Dragon). â€œIâ€™ve always been skeptical about being genre specific,â€ he says. "Iâ€™ve always known that Lil Silva is going to be a sound. Yes, Iâ€™ve been influenced by Timberland, Pharrell, and even the early grime era of Davince, Plastician, Jon E Cash, Wiley. All have defining sounds. But I wasnâ€™t listening to music for about two years when making this album. I was only going back in my archive, and bringing out what hadnâ€™t seen the light of day.â€ Here, Lil Silva talks us through the 12 expansive tracks of his debut album, track by track. â€œAnother Sketchâ€ â€œIâ€™m constantly inspired by the changing state of water. The idea that something can be, in real time, one thing, in the past something else, and in the future have a different existence, state or body. This song is about heritage, and moments in time, whether thatâ€™s in the past, present or future. So itâ€™s about family, also.â€ â€œBe Coolâ€ (with Little Dragon) â€œI started writing this song with [producer and multi-instrumentalist] Mansur Brown. Heâ€™s dangerous to be in a studio with because in between trying to finish a song, he'll play something crazy, I think we made five songs that day. His [guitar] playing is insane, and the way he's got his pedal game is a joke. He was playing this groove, and I done this whole beat around it. And after I wrote this song, I sent it over and [Little Dragonâ€™s] Yukimi [Nagano] loved it. It really related to her, and she also added in a few things. Iâ€™d done some remix work with Little Dragon before, but weâ€™d been itching to get a song of our own together.â€ â€œVera (Judah Speaks)â€ â€œThis track picks up from the tempo of the intro. I started with the drums off the top, working with [producer] Duncan Laurence, we did â€œDeja Vuâ€ [on 2016 EP Jimi] together, and working with peope that I consider family on this album just felt right. We created this orchestral feel and had strings played by [composer and arranger] Sally Herbert. Iâ€™ve always known Iâ€™d have some strings on my albumâ€”and that goes back to my early tracks like [2008 single] â€œSeasonsâ€, with the brass influence, Iâ€™m just pulling from that.â€ â€œLeave Itâ€ (with Charlotte Day Wilson) â€œThis is a message about celebrating whatâ€™s right in front of you. Thereâ€™s no need to worry, or at least donâ€™t worry for too long. The clouds of doubts that hover over, in life, and sometimes in love feel like youâ€™ll never move out of. But, however grey and however challenging, thereâ€™s a way to get through it. Itâ€™s too easy to get caught up in everything around you. â€œSeptemberâ€ â€œThere was a lot raw emotion in this. I was definitely feeling a lot of grit in that day, and it all came out in â€˜Septemberâ€™. I was with James Vincent McMorrow and Benji B, and weâ€™d clipped through this sample, and Benji played it for me at the perfect time. I was like: â€˜Wow, I've never really put samples on my song before like this.â€™ So, it was paying homage to it I guess. James is dope, really dynamic, and always comes up with these crazy interesting melody trips. And Benji has done a lot. Heâ€™s the perfect guy to have in the room, for his energy, and knowledge of music, to radio, and fashion. It wouldn't have felt right if I didn't have the [club brand] Deviation family in-and-out of this, to bounce the energy off, because my music's gone from the club to here, and he's been a massive part of that.â€ â€œTo The Floorâ€ (with BADBADNOTGOOD) â€œIt's in the title, man. Just get to it, basically. With BADBADNOTGOOD, we had this unconventional arrangement and it was about just pocketing those grooves, and the funk. This was one of the five, myself and Mansur had done, but I was like, man, this could definitely have an extra bit of funkâ€”there's a groove that could be interesting here. So I played the idea to BADBADNOTGOOD, and they came through with: drums, guitar, and even some flutes!â€ â€œBackwardsâ€ (with Sampha) â€œThis song touches on the feeling of alienation and constantly venting in the matrix you find yourself in, whatever that may be. Restricted and feeling guilty to move forward, constantly going backwards mentally; I guess the song is about being in a never ending cycle and the heaviness that can bring.â€ â€œWhat If? (with Skiifall)â€ â€œI really channeled inspiration from our roots on this record. You can hear the reggae, bashment and grime influence weave in and out. This track is about the course we find ourselves on, without even thinking. Itâ€™s about the huge role that love and family plays in our lives, but staying grounded and never forgetting what got us here.â€ â€œColoursâ€ â€œI was coming into the studio shoot for about four or five days, I kept singing, â€˜There's colours, colorus, coloursâ€™â€¦ it's like, why is this bugging me? It's every day, saying the same thing. It just kept trickling through my brain. And I made that into this beautiful soul thing, and eventually I switched it up. This bassline you could say comes from grimeâ€”but grime is in me. I used to be in [Bedford grime collective] Macabre Unit back in the day.â€ â€œAbout Usâ€ (with Elmiene) â€œIt was good for me to get back into my archive, it was like a massive soundboard for myself with sounds and work I could take. Across this process when I would have a block, I would just dig in my archive, as you would, it's almost like I'm going to remix one of my tracks that no one knows about this. It's all there.â€ â€œStillâ€ (with Sampha & Ghetts) â€œWe were all in the room jamming for around 30 minutes. And as Iâ€™ve dissected this beatâ€”everyone behind me, they all loved this bassline. But I didn't like it. Just how familiar, or how close to familiar it was, so I flipped it and found the right bass. Then Sampha dropped the first line, and I knew he had to repeat it. It's so honest, man, it's just like, â€˜Fuck, I still got all this shit to doâ€™. And he just kept on flowing. And that was the thing: If it feels good to me now, we're going to do it now. This shit was lighting me up. Because if it's not lighting you up, why are you doing it?â€ â€œEnds Nowâ€ (with serpentwithfeet) â€œSo weâ€™re back to Mansurâ€™s crazy licks. I breathed a vocal on this, and asked Serpentâ€™ to try some vocals on it, and he fell in love. He just got it. Then he's taking my lyrics and putting them in places to sustain his vocal in moments, and pocket it differently. Heâ€™s also not trying to do the conventional thing, itâ€™s all about what feels good.â€
entries.title: Yesterday Is Heavy

entries.notes: If The Smile ever seemed like a surprisingly upbeat name for a band containing two members of Radiohead (Thom Yorke and Jonny Greenwood, joined by Sons of Kemet drummer Tom Skinner), the trio used their debut gig to offer some clarification. Performing as part of Glastonbury Festivalâ€™s Live at Worthy Farm livestream in May 2021, Yorke announced, â€œWe are called The Smile: not The Smile as in â€˜Aaah!â€™â€”more the smile of the guy who lies to you every day.â€ To grasp the mood of their debut album, itâ€™s instructive to go even deeper into a name that borrows the title of a 1970 Ted Hughes poem. In Hughesâ€™ impressionist verse, some elemental forceâ€”compassion, humanity, love maybeâ€”rises up to resist the deception and chicanery behind such disarming grins. And as much as the 13 songs on A Light for Attracting Attention sense crisis and dystopia looming, they also crackle with hope and insurrection. The pulsing electronics of opener â€œThe Sameâ€ suggest the racing hearts and throbbing temples of our age of acute anxiety, and Yorkeâ€™s words feel like a call for unity and mobilisation: â€œWe donâ€™t need to fight/Look towards the light/Grab it in with both hands/What you know is right.â€ Perennially contemplating the dynamics of power and thought, he surveys a world where â€œdevastation has comeâ€ (â€œSpeech Bubblesâ€) under the rule of â€œelected billionairesâ€ (â€œThe Oppositeâ€), but itâ€™s one where protest, however extreme, can still birth change (â€œThe Smokeâ€). Amid scathing guitars and outbursts of free jazz, his invective zooms in on abuses of power (â€œYou Will Never Work in Television Againâ€) before shaming inertia and blame-shifters on the scurrying beats and descending melodies of â€œA Hairdryerâ€. These arenâ€™t exactly new themes for Yorke and itâ€™s not a record that sits at an extreme outpost of Radioheadâ€™s extended universe. Emboldened by Skinnerâ€™s fluid, intrepid rhythms, A Light for Attracting Attention draws frequently on various periods of Yorke and Greenwoodâ€™s past work. The emotional eloquence of Greenwoodâ€™s soundtrack projects resurfaces on â€œSpeech Bubblesâ€ and â€œPana-Visionâ€, while Yorkeâ€™s fascination with digital reveries continues to be explored on â€œOpen the Floodgatesâ€ and â€œThe Sameâ€. Elegantly cloaked in strings, â€œFree in the Knowledgeâ€ is a beautiful acoustic-guitar ballad in the lineage of Radioheadâ€™s â€œFake Plastic Treesâ€ and the original live version of â€œTrue Love Waitsâ€. Of course, lesser-trodden ground is visited, too: most intriguingly, math-rock (â€œThin Thingâ€) and folk songs fit for a â€™70s sci-fi drama (â€œWaving a White Flagâ€). The album closes with â€œSkrting on the Surfaceâ€, a song first aired at a 2009 show Yorke played with Atoms for Peace. With Greenwoodâ€™s guitar arpeggios and Yorkeâ€™s aching falsetto, it calls back even further to The Bendsâ€™ finale, â€œStreet Spirit (Fade Out)â€. However, its message about the fragility of existenceâ€”â€œWhen we realise we have only to die, then weâ€™re out of here/Weâ€™re just skirting on the surfaceâ€â€”remains sharply resonant.
entries.title: A Light for Attracting Attention

entries.notes: Lana Del Rey has mastered the art of carefully constructed, high-concept alt-pop records that bask inâ€”and steadily amplifyâ€”her own mythology; with each album we become more enamoured by, and yet less sure of, who she is. This is, of course, part of her magic and the source of much of her artistic power. Her records bid you to worry less about parsing fact from fiction and, instead, free-fall into her theatrical aestheticâ€”a mix of gloomy Americana, Laurel Canyon nostalgia and Hollywood noir that was once dismissed as calculation and is now revered as performance art. Up until now, these slippery, surrealist albums have made it difficult to separate artist from art. But on her introspective ninth album, something seems to shift: She appears to let us in a little. She appears to let down her guard. The opening track is called â€œThe Grantsâ€â€”a nod to her actual family name. Through unusually revealing, stream-of-conscious songs that feel like the most poetic voice notes youâ€™ve ever heard, she chastises her siblings, wonders about marriage and imagines what might come with motherhood and midlife. â€œDo you want children?/Do you wanna marry me?â€ she sings on â€œSweetâ€. â€œDo you wanna run marathons in Long Beach by the sea?â€ This is relatively new lyrical territory for Del Rey, who has generally tended to steer around personal details, and the songs themselves feel looser and more off-the-cuff (they were mostly produced with long-time collaborator Jack Antonoff). It could be that Lana has finally decided to start peeling back a few layers, but for an artist whose entire catalogue is rooted in clever imagery, itâ€™s best to leave room for imagination. The only clue might be in the albumâ€™s single piece of promo, a now-infamous billboard in Tulsa, Oklahoma, her ex-boyfriendâ€™s hometown. She settled the point fairly quickly on Instagram. â€œItâ€™s personal,â€ she wrote.

entries.notes: The piano is at the heart of Nils Frahmâ€™s music. The Berlin musicianâ€™s earliest releases were solo piano affairs. On 2011â€™s Felt, he applied preparations to hammers and strings; in 2015, he founded Piano Day, a celebration of the instrument. But on Music for Animals, which follows 2021â€™s solo piano record Old Friends New Friends, Frahm closes the cover on his keyboard and, instead, busies himself with his studio full of vintage and analogue synthesisers. Begun during the first year of the pandemic, when the world pressed pause on daily life, it basks in an almost reverent sense of calm. Chords unfurl patiently against a backdrop of velvety reverb. There are few distractions and little harmonic developmentâ€”just abiding quiet and sparkling focus. The pinging arpeggios of â€œSheep in Black and Whiteâ€ recall the clockworks of Frahmâ€™s live shows rendered in slow motion and zero gravity; the languid â€œDo Dreamâ€ drapes a wheezing pump organ in negative space. Three hours long and soft as a whisper, Music for Animals is a breathtakingly beautiful ode to stillness and solitude.
entries.title: Music for Animals

entries.title: We Will Always Love You

entries.notes: Like a lot of music made in the early 2020s, the electronic pop producer and dance music experimenter Kathy Yaeji Leeâ€™s colourful, searching first official album was born in part out of the forced reckonings of the pandemic. â€œThe promptâ€”which is what started the storyâ€”was my anger,â€ Yaeji tells Apple Music. â€œIâ€™m stuck in my room. I have no distractions. Thoughts, memories, things I havenâ€™t processed because I would distract myself usuallyâ€”they started to come up. And for the first time, from all of thatâ€”from remembering childhood, from what was happening around us politically, sociallyâ€”I felt deep anger, and I had no idea what to do with it. So I said, 'I have to make something. I have to write.'â€ But part of what makes the album interesting is Leeâ€™s ability to frame that anger with sounds that feel inviting, even celebratoryâ€”a contrast that has the meditative effect of diffusing emotions even as she expresses them; or, put another way, to demonstrate curiosity about them instead of just venting them, whether itâ€™s the panic of cyclic thinking (â€œFor Grantedâ€, â€œDone [Letâ€™s Get It]â€) or the discomfort of self-alienation (â€œPassed Me Byâ€). â€œWhen I write, itâ€™s to understand what happened better, to understand myself better,â€ she says. â€œAnd for that reason, in the moment, Iâ€™m not clocking whatâ€™s happening or exactly what it is Iâ€™m writing about. But then, after Iâ€™m done writing it, after I play it for a friend, after it comes out into the worldâ€”sometimes thatâ€™s when I realise or fully process the thing I was trying to figure out.â€ The feelings of With a Hammer are hot, but the musicâ€”spacious, patient, round, guided by Leeâ€™s naturally diminutive voiceâ€”is cool. The project also offered Lee opportunities to discover new creative approaches. The flute that opens â€œSubmerge FMâ€, for example, was one of many samples Lee collected from sessions with friends before sheâ€™d even started writing the album in earnest but whose role didnâ€™t become clear until much later. â€œI just sat with this loop on forever and then I started improvising on my synth, and it became almost like this conversation or call-and-response. And thatâ€™s what started the first track on the albumâ€”me just having a conversation with Gabby [Gabrielle Garo].â€ (Similar conversations appear with a trumpet on â€œIâ€™ll Remember for Me, Iâ€™ll Remember for Youâ€ and fractured percussion on â€œWith a Hammerâ€.) She also managed to further explore not just her identity as a speaker of Korean and English, but the way both languages can dovetail with the abstractions of musical expression. â€œWhen I was writing â€˜Passed Me Byâ€™, the main chorus of it isnâ€™t even made up of lyrics, itâ€™s just sound,â€ she says. â€œAnd the combination of the bass and the [â€™90s-style] synthâ€¦made me feel like Iâ€™m expressing a feeling I havenâ€™t been able to say in words before.â€
entries.title: With A Hammer

entries.notes: NO THANK YOUâ€”the follow-up to 2021â€™s Mercury Prize-winning Sometimes I Might Be Introvertâ€”emphatically deepens Little Simzâ€™s connection with producer Inflo, and provides further confirmation of the Islington rapperâ€™s generational abilities. The initials of the title of her soul-searching fourth LP spelled out her first name, and the name of its surprise follow-up also hints at a purposeful double meaning. Perhaps a kindly expression of gratitude for the flowers given since SIMBIâ€™s success? More likely an act of defiance. Either way, within this trademark ambiguity Simz gets her shine on across 10 sumptuous tracks. BRIT Awards Producer Of The Year 2022 Dean Josiah Coverâ€”aka Infloâ€”taps into the rich, bluesy elements of his enigmatic Sault music for urgent dispatches from Simbi Ajikawo. Itâ€™s a rich sonic seam: A returning undercurrent of gospel-rooted R&B reinforces lines with spiritual resonance. From tone-setting opener â€œAngelâ€ (dedicated to the model Harry Uzoka, who died in January 2018), soft choral flourishes and dreamy Cleo Sol vocals help Simz pick up where she left off in 2021. â€œRevoke access, Iâ€™m running it back, yes/Missing opportunities, I wish I was that pressed.â€ Building on a deep-rooted synergy, Simz and Inflo go the whole length on the gut feeling that has made their partnership so prolific. For Simz, an artist whoâ€™s always operated to her own set of standards, an equally clear-sighted collaborator (Inflo is also across the keys, chords and strings) finds her at her most compassionate and precise, tackling family trauma and the emotional isolation of success. Within the streams of sharp, self-analysing rhymes, scattered samples and prolonged orchestral sectionsâ€”â€œSidewaysâ€ and â€œControlâ€â€”lies the sound of a winning combo firmly in the groove. As Simz continues to soar, sheâ€™s evidently still clearing house. By facing down the dark reaches of the mind and the tests of her daily environment, emotional and soulful highs and lows are wonderfully bared across her tightest lyrical offering to date.
entries.title: NO THANK YOU

entries.notes: Young Fathers occupy a unique place in British music. The Mercury Prize-winning trio are as adept at envelope-pushing sonic experimentalism and opaque lyrical impressionism as they are at soulful pop hooks and festival-primed chorusesâ€”frequently, in the space of the same song. Coming off the back of an extended hiatus following 2018â€™s acclaimed Cocoa Sugar, the Edinburgh threesome entered their basement studio with no grand plan for their fourth studio album other than to reconnect to the creative process, and each other. Little was explicitly discussed. Instead, Alloysious Massaquoi, Kayus Bankole and Graham â€œGâ€ Hastingsâ€”all friends since their school daysâ€”intuitively reacted to a lyric, a piece of music or a beat that one of them had conceived to create multifaceted pieces of work that, for all their complexities and contradictions, hit home with soul-lifting, often spiritual, directness. Through the joyous clatter of opener â€œRiceâ€, the electro-glam battle cry â€œI Sawâ€, the epic â€œTell Somebodyâ€ and the shape-shifting sonic explosion of closer â€œBe Your Ladyâ€, Young Fathers express every peak and trough of the human condition within often-dense tapestries of sounds and words. â€œEach song serves an integral purpose to create something that feels cohesive,â€ says Bankole. â€œYou can find joy in silence, you can find happiness in pain. You can find all these intricate feelings and diverse feelings that reflect reality in the best possible way within these songs.â€ Across 10 dazzling tracks, Heavy Heavy has all that and more, making it the bandâ€™s most fully realised and affecting work to date. Let Massaquoi and Bankole guide you through it, track by track. â€œRiceâ€ Alloysious Massaquoi: â€œWhat weâ€™re great at doing is attaching ourselves to what the feeling of the track is and then building from that, so the lyrics start to come from that point of view. [On â€˜Riceâ€™] that feeling of it being joyous was what we were connecting to. It was the feeling of fresh morning air. Youâ€™re on a journey, youâ€™re moving towards something, it feels like youâ€™re coming home to find it again. For me, it was finding that feeling of, â€˜OK, I love music again,â€™ because during COVID it felt redundant to me. What mattered to me was looking after my family.â€ â€œI Sawâ€ AM: â€œWeâ€™d been talking about Brexit, colonialism, about forgetting the contributions of other countries and nations so that was in the air. And when we attached ourselves to the feeling of the song, it had that call-to-arms feeling to it, itâ€™s like a march.â€ Kayus Bankole: â€œIt touches on Brexit, but it also touches on how effective turning a blind eye can be, that idea that thereâ€™s nothing really you can do. Itâ€™s a call to arms, but thereâ€™s also this massive question mark. I get super-buzzed by leaving question marks so you can engage in some form of conversation afterwards.â€ â€œDrumâ€ AM: â€œItâ€™s got that sort of gospel spiritual aspect to it. Thereâ€™s an intensity in that. Itâ€™s almost like a sermon is happening.â€ KB: â€œThe intensity of it is like a possession. A good, spiritual thing. For me, speaking in my native tongue [Yoruba] is like channelling a part of me that the Western world canâ€™t express. I sometimes feel like the English language fails me, and in the Western world not a lot of people speak my language or understand what Iâ€™m saying, so itâ€™s connecting to my true self and expressing myself in a true way.â€ â€œTell Somebodyâ€ AM: â€œIt was so big, so epic that we just needed to be direct. The lyrics had to be relatable. Itâ€™s about having that balance. You have to really boil it down and think, â€˜What is it Iâ€™m trying to say here?â€™ You have 20 lines and you cut it down to just five and thatâ€™s what makes it powerful. I think it might mean something different to everyone in the group, but I know what it means to me, through my experiences, and thatâ€™s what I was channelling. The more you lean into yourself, the more relatable it is.â€ â€œGeronimoâ€ AM: â€œItâ€™s talking about relationships: â€˜Being a son, brother, uncle, father figure/I gotta survive and provide/My mama said, â€œYouâ€™ll never ever please your woman/But youâ€™ll have a good time trying.â€â€™ Itâ€™s relatable again, but then you have this nihilistic cynicism from Graham: â€˜Nobody goes anywhere really/Dressed up just to go in the dirt.â€™ Itâ€™s a bit nihilistic, but given the reality of the world and how things are, I think you need the balance of those things. Jump on, jump off. Itâ€™s like: decide. Youâ€™re either hot or youâ€™re cold. Donâ€™t be lukewarm. You either go for it or you donâ€™t. Then encapsulating all that within Geronimo, this Native American hero.â€ â€œShoot Me Downâ€ AM: â€œâ€˜Shoot Me Downâ€™ is definitely steeped in humanity. Youâ€™ve got everything in there. Youâ€™ve got the insecurities, the cynicism, youâ€™ve got the joy, the pain, the indifference. Youâ€™ve got all those things churning around in this cauldron. Thereâ€™s a level of regret in there as well. Again, when you lean into yourself, it becomes more relatable to everybody else.â€ â€œUlulationâ€ KB: â€œItâ€™s the first time weâ€™ve ever used anyone else on a track. A really close friend of mine, who I call a sister, called me while we were making â€˜Uluationâ€™: â€˜I need a place to stay, Iâ€™m having a difficult time with my husband, Iâ€™m really angry at himâ€¦â€™ I said if you need a place to chill just come down to the studio and listen to us while we work but you mustnâ€™t say a word because weâ€™re working. Weâ€™re working on the track and she started humming in the background. Alloy picked up on it and was like, â€˜Give her a mic!â€™ Sheâ€™s singing about gratitude. In the midst of feeling very angry, feeling like shit and that lifeâ€™s not fair, she still had that emotion that she can practise gratitude. I think thatâ€™s a beautiful contrast of emotions.â€ â€œSink Or Swimâ€ AM: â€œIt says a similar thing to what weâ€™re saying on â€˜Geronimoâ€™ but with more panache. The music has that feeling of a carousel, youâ€™re jumping on and jumping off. If you watch Steve McQueenâ€™s Small Axe [film anthology], in Lovers Rock, when theyâ€™re in the house party before the fire startsâ€”this fits perfectly to that. Itâ€™s that intensity, the sweat and the smoke, but with these direct lines thrown in: â€˜Oh baby, wonâ€™t you let me in?â€™ and â€˜Donâ€™t always have to be so deepâ€™. Sometimes you need a bit of directness, you need to call a spade a spade.â€ â€œHoly Molyâ€ AM: â€œItâ€™s a contrast between light and dark. Youâ€™re forcing two things that donâ€™t make sense together. You have a pop song and some weird beat, and youâ€™re forcing them to have this conversation, to do something, and then â€˜Holy Molyâ€™ comes out of that. Itâ€™s two different worlds coming together and what cements it is the lyrics.â€ â€œBe Your Ladyâ€ KB: â€œItâ€™s the perfect loop back to the first track so you could stay in the loop of the album for decades, centuries and millenniums and just bask in these intricate parts. â€˜Be Your Ladyâ€™ is a nice wave goodbye, but itâ€™s also radical as fuck. That last line â€˜Can I take 10 poundsâ€™ worth of loving out of the bank please?â€™ Iâ€™m repeating it and Iâ€™m switching the accents of it as well because I switch accents in conversation. I sometimes speak like someone whoâ€™s from Washington, D.C. [where Bankole has previously lived], or someone whoâ€™s lived in the Southside of Edinburgh, and I sometimes speak like someone whoâ€™s from Lagos in Nigeria.â€ AM: â€œI wasnâ€™t convinced about that track initially. I was like, â€˜What the fuck is this?â€™â€ KB: â€œThatâ€™s good, though. Thatâ€™s the feeling that you want. Thatâ€™s why I feel itâ€™s radical. Itâ€™s something that only we can do, it comes together and it feels right.â€

entries.notes:
With an audience comes expectationsâ€”and Snail Mailâ€™s Lindsey Jordan became acutely aware of both following the warm response to her 2018 debut LP Lush, released when she was only 18. â€œI was 100% terrified,â€ she tells Apple Music. â€œItâ€™s so confusing to get any kind of reaction to your work. And I think it kept me from writing for at least a year, just because I was scared. I make music because I love it, so it was really all about connecting withâ€”for lack of a better analogyâ€”my child self.â€
Making that connection was that much easier when Jordan found herself living with her parents again in suburban Maryland for five months, after the pandemic took hold in 2020. Thatâ€™s where much of Valentine began to take shape, Jordan working alone in her childhood bedroom, free of distractions. Though bigger and bolder and more adventurous than its predecessor, the album is still deeply personalâ€”indie rock thatâ€™s laced with reflections on time spent in and out of love and rehab. â€œWhether the actual time there was for better or for worse, it got good art out of me,â€ she says of being back home. â€œI just felt like I was just doing it for fun again, like when I was working on Lush, coming home from high school every day and writing for a while. I guess just sitting on that same carpet was pretty liberating for me.â€ Here, she guides us through the entire album, track by track.
â€œValentineâ€ â€œI was shopping around ideas for the record long before there was one, just wanting to put a title to the thing to maybe give it a startâ€”like if there's just an overarching vibe, then I can start to make things. It's such a heartbreaking thing, referring to someone as your valentine in a love-lost type of way, because I just think there's nothing more tender and innocent. I just think the hurt there is pretty relatable, and when I came up with â€˜darling, valentineâ€™, it kicked me in the guts in a way that felt right for the entire thing. I just knew immediately that the record was going to be called Valentine.â€
â€œBen Franklinâ€ â€œI've always been extremely self-assured, confident and independentâ€”especially doing this job at such a young age. And rehab just kicks that out of you in a way. You kind of have to get in touch with values in a way that is shocking. Even just in the pandemic I was like, â€˜Okay, so now I need to be good at being a normal person, too.â€™ And that's different, and thatâ€™s not something I was so self-assured in. It was a big decision to want to just go and clean up, so that I could work again. I'm not cocky anymore. I'm dealing with what I left behind. Itâ€™s like, boom: real adulthood.â€
â€œHeadlockâ€ â€œâ€˜Headlockâ€™ isnâ€™t about losing someone so much as it is about really losing myself in a relationship. I worked on that one at my parents' houseâ€”all the synth lines I did in my room on my Minilogue, and I wrote all the lyrics sitting right there at my desk, just sort of dipping my toes into the deep darkness. With that line â€˜Thought I'd see her when I died,â€™ I'm saying that the end goal of dying in this case would be to be reunited with this lost love. It came from a real dark spot that I was in.â€
â€œLight Blueâ€ â€œI wrote it for a girlfriend. It feels like I was young at the timeâ€”I was 19â€”and even though it wasn't that long ago, in a way it was. I guess I meant it to be a gesture, but also kind of a declaration. I don't remember it being a particular communicative relationship but it was fiery and I think that was my way of communicating my feelings at the timeâ€”and I think that comes through.â€
â€œForever (Sailing)â€ â€œThat song was initially constructed from a sample of a song, â€˜You and Iâ€™ by Madleen Kane. I heard it forever ago and I was just really movedâ€”it has some magic that feels like I really feel. And I had never really dabbled in sampling, but I just couldn't stop thinking about being involved with the song somehow, selfishly. So I brought it to the studio in North Carolina and we isolated the sample and slowed it down. It's kind of a deep cut in a way, and random that I heard it. I don't know that much about disco at all.â€
â€œMadonnaâ€ â€œI was raised Catholic and went to Sunday school. I was in the church band. And the song is about putting someone on a pedestal and worshiping them and how that just doesn't translate into anything but resentment and anger once you kind of step away from it. Using religious metaphors and my knowledge from that time of my life felt exciting and genuine. I have a deep fear of being blasphemousâ€”I don't want to disappoint my mom.â€
â€œc. Et Al.â€ â€œI spent a lot of time writing it in the van, actually, on tour. I had a little portable amp that hooks up to headphones and I would just play it in there because I don't like to come up with lyrics around other people. It's complex, because Iâ€™d be sitting in the van for eight hours a day or something.â€
â€œGloryâ€ â€œVery angry and upset vibes. And it's similar thematically to â€˜Madonnaâ€™, goes within the same grieving process and theme of anger. It's disenchanted as fuck. Itâ€™s like no matter how angry I am and no matter how much I try to make this something where I'm in control and I'm the one making demands, at the end of the day I still would do anything for the subject of the song. No matter how in control I feel, I don't even feel like I belong to myself because I'm so entwined in this person's life.â€
â€œAutomateâ€ â€œI think that there comes a time whenâ€”through experience and through fucking up and learning about my needs and myselfâ€”love becomes less of a fantasy and less of a game. Thereâ€™s so much that needs to exist for love to be healthy, and once you realise that relationships are more than what you imagined them to be as a teenager and as a kid, it just becomes a lot more loaded. Like love, real love, is unconditional in a perfect world, and it's loving somebody beyond the good stuff. Being in love with someone is taking them where they're at and having them take you where you're at, and that's the brutal truth being uncovered in that song: Itâ€™s not all about passion and fire.â€
â€œMiaâ€ â€œâ€˜Miaâ€™ is the only song with a full orchestra on it and the whole shebang. Originally, we sent the song to an arranger and they sent back some ideas. I wasn't crazy about the arrangement, so I played some of the arrangement myself on a synth and sent it back and was like, â€˜Can I hear this?â€™ That synth line that got translated into an orchestral moment is one of my favourite parts of the songâ€”it was super collaborative.â€

entries.notes: The most jarring part about listening to the London band black midi isnâ€™t how much musical ground they coverâ€”post-punk, progressive rock, breakneck jazz, cabaretâ€”but the fact that they cover it all at once. A quasi-concept album that seems to have something to do with war (â€œWelcome to Hellâ€, â€œ27 Questionsâ€), or at least the violence men do more generally (â€œSugar/Tzuâ€, â€œDangerous Liaisonsâ€), Hellfire isnâ€™t an easy listen. But itâ€™s funny (main character: Tristan Bongo), beautiful, at least in a garish, misanthropic way (the Neil Diamond bombast of â€œThe Defenceâ€), and so obviously playful in its intelligence that you just want to let it run over you. The first listen feels like being yelled at in a language you donâ€™t understand. By the third, youâ€™ll be yelling with them.
