entries.notes:
From Pitchfork:

â€œRachika Nayar doesnâ€™t just spew out a little fog before her live show, she stretches the venueâ€™s fire code to its limit. Before the guitarist walks onstage, the entire performance space is clouded, red exit signs barely visible, until you can barely see your hand in front of your face. The effect on the audience is immediate: Conversations dull to a whisper and friends drift carefully towards each other to reunite before the music starts, tiptoeing across a shadowy maze of bodies as they take on a heightened awareness of their own.

Itâ€™s the perfect environment to experience Nayarâ€™s music. Interviewed on the heels of her 2021 debut, Our Hands Against the Dusk, she championed the â€œtotally obliteratingâ€ power of a raveâ€™s atmosphere, and spoke of her desire to create a similar environment, ones that â€œsimultaneously takes you out of yourself, and submerges you deep within yourself.â€ Our Hands did this by constructing misty ambient labyrinths out of processed guitar, revealing Nayarâ€™s ability to sculpt the instrumentâ€™s earthy twang into unpredictable alien timbres and shift them back to familiar shapes at a momentâ€™s notice. When Nayar debuted tracks from her astonishing second album, Heaven Come Crashing, at the Brooklyn venue Public Records, strobes flashed violently and unexpected floods of drums crashed into the crowd. Egos melted away as the crowd breathed in a wave of ecstatic release.

Heaven Come Crashing injects the ambient wash of Nayarâ€™s past work with flashes of dancefloor emotionality, striking a balance between reflective contemplation and the ego-melting thrills of a warehouse party. On the stunning title track, she traces the arc of her musical transformation in miniature. Slices of granulated guitar gently refract into the frame, and for a few seconds, the song could be a holdover from the swooning sentimentality of Our Hands. But she soldiers on, backed by unearthly guest vocals from fellow guitarist and songwriter Maria BC that swell from airy wisps into a supercharged choir. Suddenly, a trap door unhinges and youâ€™re ripped into a punishingly beautiful beat drop. Itâ€™s a scene of catharsis surrounded by a squealing guitar solo and the cascading cymbal crashes of a drumâ€™nâ€™bass beat. â€œHeaven Come Crashingâ€ lifts you up with shameless melodrama and pure affirmation: It was all worth it.

Nayar deploys these moments of tension and release with the sixth sense of a veteran after-hours DJ, keenly aware that floor-filling emotional highs are earned through careful pacing. â€œTetramorph,â€ the albumâ€™s longest and most satisfying song, weaves through a series of false stops and starts that perfectly read the pulse of the crowd. Chattering hi-hats come in at full volume, emerging from pin-drop silence in a quick hit of stimulation. They fizzle out but the effects cling to your body, propping you up as you navigate a maze of buzzing drones that build into a waltzing post-rock climax. The effect is startling, but as Nayar rocks out in the coda, you easily recall every part of the meticulously arranged journey, awe-struck at how seamlessly she blended it all together.

Other tracks use compositional sleight-of-hand to leave you dangling off the edge of a cliff, ending on deliciously maddening chords that make you lean into the speaker, trying to manifest a neat resolution by sheer force of imagination. â€œThe Price of Serenityâ€ rides dueling motifsâ€”a steadily rising clean piano arpeggio and a squelching synthesizer leadâ€”to a crunchy four-on-the-floor stomp, disguising a jarring left turn into oblivion with a pulse-pounding bass drum stutter. In a show of supreme confidence, she resurrects the formula on the next track, â€œOur Wretched Fate,â€ crashing from nocturnal ecstasy into sober daylight in half the time. Unexpected power surges back into your feet, only for the house lights to come up.

In this metamorphosis from ambient composer to dancefloor mystic, Nayar meets her mirror image in UK producer Loraine James. Where Nayar has folded her impressionistic collages into body-breaking narrative arcs, James has done the opposite, smoothing out the gritty IDM of 2021â€™s Reflection to reemerge this year with ambient side-project Whatever the Weather. But although they take new form, traces of the past and beloved compositional tools linger. Just as James canâ€™t help but blow the dust off her drum machine, Nayar uses her guitar for soothing interludes that provide a dynamic counterpoint to Heaven Come Crashingâ€™s barn-burning anthems.

Nayarâ€™s new guitar experiments light the path with flickering details. A rhythm that sounds as if it were tapped out on her thigh, off-the-cuff, gives â€œGayatriâ€ a strange kind of propulsion. And the combination of bass synth and the brief glimmer of a corresponding lead line roots the searching motif of â€œDeath & Limerenceâ€ in the assurance of a heaven-bound trajectory. Itâ€™s a dazzling recalibration, lifting Nayar up and over the darkness of her previous work. The answers arenâ€™t quite pieced together, but the questions grow deeper and more satisfying.â€

After seven weeks, number one again as it is such an interesting ambient album.

From spectrumculture.com:

Do you remember a time before mashups? Before Danger Mouse made a name for himself splicing together Jay Zâ€™s The Black Album and the Beatlesâ€™ The White Album, or biomed engineer Gregg Gillis catapulting the genre into a world of nonstop blends of Biggie Smalls and Elton John or Birdman and Temple of the Dog? Before you could, essentially, type two similar songs into YouTube to discover that somebody cooked up the â€œHead Like a Holeâ€/â€Call Me Maybeâ€ mashup you imagined in your head? We wonâ€™t pretend that the Avalanches invented doing this around the dawn of the new millennium â€” to do so would ignore the Negativlands of the world, they of a strong lineage of splicers and visionaries who were doing things the hard way, without the help of Audacity or GarageBand or whatever program they chose to do it in.

And maybe itâ€™s disingenuous to even label Australiaâ€™s the Avalanches a â€œmashup bandâ€ â€” one might argue that what they do is plunderphonics, a term that sounds like your coolest uncle attempting to make up a word for, essentially, the same thing. It doesnâ€™t matter what you call it, though. In a worst-case scenario, you might produce an unlistenable mess of incongruous sounds that youâ€™d never foist on your worst enemy. But in the best-case â€” which is where we find ourselves with Since I Left You â€” youâ€™ll find yourself immersed in a rich, shimmering tapestry of sounds and sensations that leave you wondering, â€œNow, how the fuck did they do that?â€

These questions are the fairest ones to ask of any album this side of Paulâ€™s Boutique. How did the Avalanches do that, and how the fuck did they get away with it? The actual number of samples contained within the hourlong journey of Since I Left You â€” now re-released in a gargantuan 4LP format to celebrate its 20th(!) anniversary â€” is difficult to pin down. While some estimate that the number sits within the 900 range, Robbie Chater (one of the two founding members still with the group to this day) puts it somewhere in the 3,500 range. For those that somehow missed Since I Left You, the fact that thereâ€™s a dispute over whether or not the album only contains 900 samples should give you an idea of the magical beast weâ€™re working with here.

This article/love letter could be double in size if we covered the spiraling galaxy of removals and revisions that have taken place over the years; because the band never really foresaw anyone listening to the album, much less anyone giving it distribution outside of Australia, the matter of clearance becomes murky and impossible. That lack of foresight means that they did a ludicrously bad job of even cataloguing the samples they used and tossed in some biggies just for kicks â€” and as such, some sacrifices to the Clearance Gods had to be made in order to introduce the rest of the world to the record. Itâ€™s entirely possible that youâ€™ve only heard the version of â€œFrontier Psychiatristâ€ with vocals re-recorded in-house, and you may not have heard any clips from the film Midnight Run in the mix.

Underneath the dizzying number of samples and different versions of Since I Left You, though, thereâ€™s this album. It never truly feels like a real â€œalbumâ€ â€” many songs here present themselves more as connective tissue between bigger set pieces. If Since I Left You is the ultimate summer party captured by thousands of sound fragments, these moments are like hallways full of different conversations within the microparties that can bloom in those events. Youâ€™d expect it to feel disjointed, even disorienting, right? But no â€” even when theyâ€™re sampling the shit out of horses neighing, Since I Left You is a fully fleshed-out world, and one that feels staggeringly visual; Wildflower and We Will Always Love You would show the Avalanches expanding their ability to construct remarkably vivid albums that induce temporary synesthesia, urging you to hear the music in colors and shapes and whole vistas, but what becomes clear as time goes on is that they more or less arrived fully capable of performing this magic trick, immediately capable of invoking technicolor worlds you yearn to live in. They donâ€™t even need hits to keep you stoked â€” take a look at the beloved â€œFrontier Psychiatrist,â€ which moves away from the â€œsongâ€ part of the song long before the track itself ends, but totally organically.

Even given 20 years to spend with Since I Left You, itâ€™s hard to put a finger on what it is about these songs that endures like it does. From a certain view, the album can seem like amorphous noise that occasionally coalesces into a real â€œsong.â€ This feels myopic, though. The fact that the album is so easily equated to a party points to the fact that the album doesnâ€™t always feel like it was meant to serve as proper music, but instead, an aural gateway into your most fond memories. Itâ€™s a dreamworld dense with sounds that you feel like you must have heard somewhere, and just when you think youâ€™ve caught it, the sound passes. Every sound in the world might be totally new to you, but when youâ€™re hit with so many different things, it can create a strange phantom nostalgia for a formative experience that you never actually had. Songs like â€œExtra Kingsâ€ donâ€™t need to have cohesive structure for it to do to you what it wants to do â€” the Avalanches are powerful wizards, and they can give you those moments even without it.

Weâ€™d be remiss if we didnâ€™t go into the second half of this set. This massive 4LP reissue devotes two of those LPs to various remixes and (in the case of â€œThank You Caroline,â€ seen in its infancy at the tail end) alternate versions of album tracks. The very nature of the record lends itself to those remixes â€” artists like Stereolab, Black Dice, Deakin, and the late MF Doom tear the songs apart easily, inserting themselves into these worlds effortlessly. Your enjoyment in this aspect may vary: if you come to the Avalanches to spend your time within the world they designed, you may find these remixes unnecessary. After all, doesnâ€™t some of the magic of Since I Left You fade when you subject it to the standards of more typical dance music? Yet, for those willing to see what parts of each song are adopted and repurposed by each songâ€™s rebuilder. This is true of all remixes, but the album is such a treasure trove of sights and sounds, and each remix sneakily represents a love letter from the artist about the moments during that grand party that stuck in their minds the most.

The remixes here run the gamut, like the propulsive, gargantuan Carl Craigâ€™s Paperclip People Remix of â€œA Different Feeling,â€ or Sun Arawâ€™s psychedelic take on â€œClose to You.â€ The most perplexing omission is the eternal barnburner â€œStay Another Season,â€ but we do get Black Diceâ€™s thoroughly Black Dice-y spin on â€œSummer Crane,â€ which sees the band throwing the original into a blender with plenty of classic noise theyâ€™ve had sitting around, and then recording the sound of that blender on Max. This song is destined to be polarizing as hell, but itâ€™s easily the most unique track of the bunch (next to Deakinâ€™s zonked â€œExtra Kings,â€ that is). And then thereâ€™s the two sets of triplets: â€œSince I Left Youâ€ and, most surprisingly, â€œTonight May Have to Last Me All My Lifeâ€ each get a trio of different remixes, allowing us to compare and contrast. Watch as Cornelius steals the vocal hook of â€œSince I Left Youâ€ and lovingly sews it into a shimmering sea of beats, Prince Paul cranks the funkiness and Stereolab reveals how easily the song fits into their French futurist aesthetic. â€œTonight May Have to Last Me All My Life,â€ while existing squarely in the category of songs that feel representative of the space in between bigger set pieces, reveals itself as being highly remixable. Edan and MF Doom both choose to rap over the track, but the Dragged by Leon Vynehall version reconfigures the song into a bona fide dubstep banger worthy of a FactMag mix by Joy Orbison or Four Tet.

Twenty years on, the legacy of the Avalanches is a confusing one full of letdowns (the 16-year wait for its follow up) and triumphs (their follow-ups, Wildflower and We Will Always Love You, each a surprising and distinct masterpiece in their own ways), but as they broaden their scope and creation methods, their talent feels unassailable. The worst thing about their remarkable and unassuming debut is also one of the best things: itâ€™s an album that presents sounds that arenâ€™t always musical or even listenable when not in context, an aspect which then asks you to exist within its curious world instead of simply dipping your toe into certain moments. Since I Left You is still a breath of fresh air after two decades, its heady trajectory providing endless revisits and the constant discovery of new, exciting aspects. Ultimately, labeling the band anything at all is a gross misunderstanding of what makes the Avalanches special in the first place. They were â€” and are â€” just a band transforming the sounds they love into sounds they know weâ€™ll love, and that pursuit exists beyond any boxes we might try to put them in.
entries.title: Since I Left You (20th Anniversary Deluxe Edition)

entries.notes: When Kendrick Lamar popped up on two tracks from Baby Keemâ€™s The Melodic Blue (â€œrange brothersâ€ and â€œfamily tiesâ€), it felt like one of hip-hopâ€™s prophets had descended a mountain to deliver scripture. His verses were stellar, to be sure, but it also just felt like way too much time had passed since weâ€™d heard his voice. Heâ€™d helmed 2018â€™s Black Panther compilation/soundtrack, but his last proper release was 2017â€™s DAMN. That kind of scarcity in hip-hop can only serve to deify an artist as beloved as Lamar. But if the Compton MC is broadcasting anything across his fifth proper album Mr. Morale & The Big Steppers, itâ€™s that heâ€™s only human. The project is split into two parts, each comprising nine songs, all of which serve to illuminate Lamarâ€™s continually evolving world view. Central to Lamarâ€™s thesis is accountability. The MC has painstakingly itemised his shortcomings, assessing his relationships with money (â€œUnited in Griefâ€), white women (â€œWorldwide Steppersâ€), his father (â€œFather Timeâ€), the limits of his loyalty (â€œRich Spiritâ€), love in the context of heteronormative relationships (â€œWe Cry Togetherâ€, â€œPurple Heartsâ€), motivation (â€œCount Me Outâ€), responsibility (â€œCrownâ€), gender (â€œAuntie Diariesâ€) and generational trauma (â€œMother I Soberâ€). Itâ€™s a dense and heavy listen. But just as sure as Kendrick Lamar is human like the rest of us, heâ€™s also a Pulitzer Prize winner, one of the most thoughtful MCs alive and someone whose honesty across Mr. Morale & The Big Steppers could help us understand why any of us are the way we are.
entries.title: Mr. Morale & The Big Steppers

entries.notes: Ever since 2013, when Sons of Kemet saxophonist Shabaka Hutchings first leapt onstage to join synth-and-drums duo Soccer96 in a spontaneous explosion of pure groove, the three musicians have been honing their gale-force attack. Dubbed The Comet Is Coming, the trioâ€”Hutchings, drummer Max Hallett and synth player Dan Leaversâ€”first laid out their double-barrelled jazz-dance fusion on 2016â€™s Channel the Spirits, then gave free rein to more psychedelic urges on 2019â€™s Trust in the Lifeforce of the Deep Mystery and The Afterlife, which followed six months later. With Hyper-Dimensional Expansion Beam, The Comet Is Coming deliver their biggest, most expansive record yet. Part of that might stem from recording at Peter Gabrielâ€™s Real World Studios, where the three musicians tracked four days of improv sessions that Hallett and Leavers subsequently reworked into these 11 powerhouse jams. In contrast to the previous two albumsâ€™ star-gazing tendencies, Hyper-Dimensional Expansion Beam unleashes a focused blast of energy with the opening â€œCODEâ€, with Hutchings meting out stabbing arpeggios over the rhythm sectionâ€™s heads-down stomp. They expand their range with every track. â€œTECHNICOLOURâ€ is a slinky detour into liquid funk, and â€œLUCID DREAMERâ€ drifts on a cloud of ambient soul; album highlight â€œPYRAMIDSâ€ taps the tunnel-vision intensity of early-2000s techno. â€œATOMIC WAVE DANCEâ€ is another big one, with spiky sax riffs set against jagged arpeggios and a driving 4/4 beat, while on â€œAFTERMATHâ€, they pursue krautrock down an almost ambient path. And listeners pining for the last albumsâ€™ offworld vibes will find an escape pod in the form of â€œANGEL OF DARKNESSâ€, an unrestrained journey to their cosmic-jazz limits. The Comet Is Coming have never sounded tighterâ€”or freerâ€”than they do here.
entries.title: Hyper-Dimensional Expansion Beam

entries.notes: When Jessie Ware wrote â€œRemember Where You Areâ€â€”the final song on her career-altering 2020 record Whatâ€™s Your Pleasure?â€”she knew sheâ€™d unlocked the sound of her future. â€œI think I finally understood my place in music,â€ she tells Apple Music. â€œI felt like I was combining all my loves, from musical theatre to soul, groove, dance and funk to R&B and orchestral moments and group vocals. I wanted to do â€˜Remember Where You Areâ€™, but with a big old dance beat.â€ Thatâ€™s more or less what you can expect from That! Feels Good!, on which the London singer-songwriter doubles down on her devotion the dance floor andâ€”after the varnished opulence of Whatâ€™s Your Pleasure?â€”embraces a looser, louder, more live sound. Itâ€™s (almost) all up, with brass and string arrangements, choruses of voices, very winking lyrics and, perhaps most surprisingly, rapping Ã  la Blondie or Tom Tom Club. â€œMy voice was always the thing, which is fabulous,â€ says Ware (who, of course, also belts out plenty of elastic vocals here). â€œBut for me it was like, â€˜Letâ€™s see what else Iâ€™ve got.â€™â€ Made with â€¦Pleasure collaborators James Ford, Clarence Coffee Jr., Shungudzo and Danny Parker, plus UK producer Stuart Price (Madonna, Kylie Minogue, The Killers, Pet Shop Boys), That! Feels Good! was powered by the roaring success of its predecessor. Released during the pandemic, the disco-fuelled Whatâ€™s Your Pleasure? became an antidote for many during lockdown, and earned Ware a British Album of the Year BRIT Award nomination, a support slot on tour with Harry Styles and an army of new fans. All of which gave her the confidence to just keep having fun. â€œI felt like Iâ€™d been granted permission to let loose and show all sides of myself,â€ says Ware. â€œI wanted it to feel free, and I think that was indicative of how I was feeling. This record was about celebration and joy. I wanted it to feel like the sexiest slap around the face.â€ Read on as Ware walks us through That! Feels Good!, one song at a time. â€œThat! Feels Good!â€ â€œI needed it to feel like you landed straight into a groove, which is very different to how I started Whatâ€™s Your Pleasure?. It felt like I was imagining me as Dâ€™Angelo or James Brown. With the spoken thing at the start of this track, Iâ€™d said to [producer] James Ford, â€˜Letâ€™s really enjoy this intro: What do you think about [including] loads of different people so it felt like were in an orgy?â€™ It was about making people feel slightly uncomfortable, particularly British people, and to make you go, â€˜Hang on, what is she about to do?â€™ Those voices are RoÃ­sÃ­n Murphy, Kylie Minogue, Aisling Bea, Jamie Demetriou, Gemma Arterton, benny blanco, my mum [Lennie Ware; Jessieâ€™s co-host on their podcast Table Manners), my [podcast] producer Alice and her husband, who speak French, because they sounded really good, an ex-boyfriend whoâ€™s Spanish and Clara Amfo. We got them all!â€ â€œFree Yourselfâ€ â€œWe nearly didnâ€™t write this song. It was the first day Iâ€™d worked with Stuart [Price], and heâ€™d played this house song but I felt it was a bit too close to Whatâ€™s Your Pleasure?. Respect to Stuart, because he never gives up and said, â€˜Can we just listen to that instrumental again?â€™ We put the vocal down just to see what happened and then Coffee [London-based songwriter and producer Clarence Coffee Jr.] sang, â€˜Free yourselfâ€™â€”and it was really fun. Me and Coffee went and celebrated afterâ€”we had tequila and toasted the song because it felt like it was going to change things.â€ â€œPearlsâ€ â€œIt felt very camp and soulful, immediate, bombastic, glorious and fun. Itâ€™s saying, â€˜Here are some of the ladies Iâ€™m going to be on this record.â€™ The lyric â€˜And I do what I wanna/A perfect prima donnaâ€™ is said with a wink because I know that I can play up to the role of being a pop star when I need to, but I never take myself too seriously. And when I say prima donna, itâ€™s very much playing with the notion of women being thought of a certain way when they have an opinion, but also acknowledging that I am quite perfect at being a bit of a diva. Hopefully I donâ€™t do it for too long!â€ â€œHello Loveâ€ â€œI needed there to be a breather because I didnâ€™t want people to feel exhausted by those first three songs, which are supposed to hit hard and feel like a bang. I hope this song lives on forever, because it feels quintessentially me, but with me having grown with experience in writing. Itâ€™s me tapping into romance and Donny Hathaway and soul music and groove like The Gap Band. Iâ€™m a sucker for a love song, but I wanted to do one that didnâ€™t feel like a ballad per se. I also kind of wanted this to feel like the opportunity for a new first-dance song [at weddings], because I feel like everyoneâ€™s been using â€˜Champagne Kissesâ€™ and â€˜Say You Love Meâ€™, but theyâ€™re both really sad songs so they should just give up on those and do this one.â€ â€œBegin Againâ€ â€œâ€˜Begin Againâ€™ is the pathway from Whatâ€™s Your Pleasure? into That! Feels Good!. Itâ€™s where this album startedâ€”and was written over Zoom between LA and Hackney. The lyric â€˜Why does all the purest love get filtered through machines?â€™ probably came from thatâ€”Iâ€™m sick to death of Zooms! But if you think further into it, itâ€™s about being a prisoner to screens and it becoming so habitual and wanting to escape that, but not being able to. It was very much inspired by Stevie Wonderâ€™s â€˜Another Starâ€™ and Talking Headsâ€™ Stop Making Sense, and bossa nova, Brazilian disco and longing for travel.â€ â€œBeautiful Peopleâ€ â€œI wanted this song to feel like it went from a monologue into a conversation. That there was a bit of a narrative, however fantasy-led that was. You go from talking yourself out of a crap day to going to a club and feeling free and happy. I think thatâ€™s what dance music, particularly going clubbing, can be, and I love that feelingâ€”thereâ€™s nothing greater. But as a mother of three, who also works insanely hard, clubbing isnâ€™t on the agenda every week. This was my way of transporting myself to that place.â€ â€œFreak Me Nowâ€ â€œStuart made this instrumental and he was adamant that we were going to use it. This song has kind of French house nods and I was thinking about how RÃ³isÃ­n Murphy would say something, as well as Mousse T.â€™s â€˜Hornyâ€™ and Gwen McCraeâ€™s â€˜Keep the Fire Burningâ€™. Itâ€™s another commanding song like â€˜Free Yourselfâ€™ and Iâ€™m in the driverâ€™s seatâ€”itâ€™s not requesting, itâ€™s like this personâ€™s going to have to do it. That was a really fun position to be in.â€ â€œShake the Bottleâ€ â€œThis is almost my cabaret song. Itâ€™s highly camp and itâ€™s me as a â€˜madameâ€™ and is just really fun. It was like, â€˜How far can we push this innuendo?â€™ It feels more like a performance piece. I really hope all my queens that lip-sync like this, because I think I made it for lip-syncers. Iâ€™m in awe of the performance and I so respect drag and the creativity and the confidence. I feel so loved and cherished by a beautiful community and theyâ€™re always in my mind, particularly because we have so much fun together. I feel very lucky to have an incredibly strong following from the LGBTQ community. Theyâ€™ve made me a better performer.â€ â€œLightningâ€ â€œI was definitely leaning into a more R&B moment: This pulled from Sade, Madlib, Drake. There needed to be a bit of space on the record to just take a moment, but I also wanted to feel like it could connect with the rest of the album. This is my husbandâ€™s favourite tune: itâ€™s sex, itâ€™s languid, itâ€™s a bit of a breather. Maybe itâ€™s also the end of the night when the party is starting to die out and itâ€™s just you and somebody else. It has a vulnerability.â€ â€œThese Lipsâ€ â€œI wanted it to feel like there was Earth, Wind & Fire on this, or Minnie Riperton. It felt right to finish with this spoken-word thing at the end, which is me trying to do my little Gil Scott-Heron moment. But itâ€™s also got the celebratory and dramatic backing vocals. It felt optimistic, and like the groove carried on, but thereâ€™s also ceremony and dramaâ€”thatâ€™s how I wanted to leave people. It felt like a blissful, sensual ending.â€
entries.title: That! Feels Good!

entries.notes: Where KICK ii delves into the lurching, snapping grooves of reggaetÃ³n, KicK iii applies an even more forceful touch to experimental beats that zigzag between futuristic club rhythms and vintage IDM. The strutting â€œBrujaâ€ fires merciless ballroom salvos over car-crash drums and apocalyptic synth squeal; â€œIncendioâ€ twists Arcaâ€™s perpetually morphing vocals over drums that punch like Brazilian funk carioca or Portuguese batida; and â€œMorboâ€ dissolves into a gooey morass of slow-motion techno. From there, things just get more unpredictable: The shuddering beats of â€œFieraâ€ and â€œRipplesâ€ feel like theyâ€™re coming apart at the seams, while the shimmering melody of â€œSkullqueenâ€ channels mid-â€™90s Aphex Twin, long a latent influence on Arcaâ€™s fractured syncopations. But the storm clouds part for the closing â€œJoyaâ€: Over soft, feathery chimes, she sings sweetly, â€œI want to tell you/You are a jewel among men/I feel so much love.â€ After so much violent turmoil, to let us down so gently feels like an act of kindness.
entries.title: KicK iii

entries.notes:
From Pitchfork:

â€œOn their remarkable third album, the New Orleans band pushes their sound to both its bleakest and its sweetest brinks. Pop, disco, and house all melt into their raucous, revolutionary glam punk.

In a big enough mosh pit, the world jostles loose. You enter the pit as one person, and you leave as someone else. The late queer theorist JosÃ© Esteban MuÃ±oz described this transformation as a portal in his 2009 book Cruising Utopia. â€œI remember the sexually ambiguous punk clubs of my youth where horny drunk punk boys rehearsed their identities, aggressively dancing with one another and later lurching out, intoxicated, to the parking lot together,â€ he wrote. â€œFor many of them, the mosh pit was not simply a closet; it was a utopian subcultural rehearsal space.â€ In the squall of the music, reality starts to split and curl. Through communal, friendly violence, punks build muscle memory of what itâ€™s like to feel unhinged and cared for at the same time. The thrash of bodies clears a channel, however fleeting, into a more survivable life.

Special Interest drill down into that same molten core. Across three ferocious albums, the New Orleans band traces the line where the thirst for a new world meets the rage that torches the old one. Lit up and led by searingly charismatic singer Alli Logout, they call out the stakes of the era as they see them, excoriating gentrifiers, cops, warmongers, and trust-fund art-school kids with keenly tuned sneers. Songs about bracing for revolution brush up against songs about great sex on great drugs. Running on the tireless engine of Ruth Mascelliâ€™s clattering drum machine, they follow in a legacy of queer perturbations from the â€™80s and â€™90s that include Coil, Frankie Knuckles, and the B-52â€™sâ€”all of whom, in their own way, worked with the same mix of political dissatisfaction, biting humor, and erotic fantasy. On their third album, Endure, Special Interest push their sound to both its bleakest and its sweetest brinks. Pop, disco, and house all melt into their reliably raucous glam punk, and questions of communal caretaking press against a grief-riddled apocalyptic outlook. This time around, their thorns drip with honey.

Across Endure, Special Interest embellish the cornerstones they established on 2018â€™s Spiralling and 2020â€™s The Passion Of with gestures that wouldnâ€™t sound out of place on â€™90s radio. The after-dark sounds of house and techno started spilling onto commercial daytime airwaves toward the end of the last millennium, many of them drifting onto the Top 40 from overseas in the pan-flash genre called Eurodance. Logout stretches into certain vocal timbres and minor-key intervals that echo the perfect, ephemeral dance pop of a group like La Bouche, while behind their voice, delicate piano lines fringe the bandâ€™s hard-driving foundation. These shifts clear more air around Special Interestâ€™s sound. While certain moments still feel immediate and unignorable, others seem to waft out from a clubâ€™s open back door, beckoning passersby to come take a closer look.

The albumâ€™s most compelling songs use both strategies in tandem. They invite you to wander in of your own accord, then enclose you inside a fever pitch. On the rollicking dance track â€œ(Hermanâ€™s) House,â€ Special Interest forge an incandescent call to anger out of a surging hook. The song shares its name with a 2012 documentary about the imaginative collaboration between artist Jackie Sumell and activist Herman Wallace, a member of the Black Panther Party who spent 41 years in solitary confinement after serving a life sentence for a murder he denied committing. From his tiny cell, Wallace described his dream house to Sumell, who rendered it via computer graphics and as a tabletop model. In 2013, Wallace finally stepped out of prison, then died of cancer three days later. Sumell made plans to build the house he described to her as a youth community center in New Orleans, but property developers bought the proposed land out from under her.

The story ends bitterly, but Special Interest find solace in the idea of projecting utopia out from hell. â€œBuild it out like Hermanâ€™s house,â€ Logout screams at the chorus over Nathan Cassianiâ€™s jaw-clenched bassline. â€œWeâ€™ll all be Basquiats for five minutes or Hermans for life/So when I say build I mean dream, because thatâ€™s all we got promised,â€ they command in a spoken-word breakdown just before the final refrain. In a recent Quietus interview, Logout illuminated the juxtaposition between the Black queer artist Jean-Michel Basquiat and Wallace: â€œItâ€™s two different sides of what being Black in America is. Youâ€™re either fully idolized and destroyed, or youâ€™re thrown in a cage.â€

Special Interest began writing Endure in the middle of 2020, in the wake of uprisings against police killings that stirred cities around the world. Across the insistent drumbeat spikes of â€œConcerning Peace,â€ the band bemoans the whittling down of those revolutionary impulses into a neoliberal mold of nonviolent personal enrichment: â€œLiberal erasure of militant uprising is a tool of corporate interest and a failure of imagination,â€ goes a call-out line reminiscent of the interjections on System of a Downâ€™s â€œPrison Song.â€ Over Maria Elenaâ€™s frothing, sidelong guitar chords, the bandâ€™s voices come together for the chant-along chorus, where they collectively quote the Black Power activist Stokely Carmichael: â€œWe are not concerned with peace/Peace is not of our concern.â€ Power disguises its own violence as the natural order of things; to call for violence in retaliation clarifies the terms of a smiling oppressor. â€œNo one will ever rest in peace/When their value is less than property,â€ Logout seethes, pillorying commentators who expressed more concern over broken store windows than the lives of Black people killed by police.

Endure howls against a capitalist regime that feeds on the neglect and death of sidelined and exploited human beings, both in the U.S. and globally. This system is fragmented enough to work in the shadows; long threads connect military activity in the Middle East and the gas that seeps out of the pump at the 7-Eleven, but theyâ€™re obscured enough that whoeverâ€™s gripping the handle wonâ€™t typically feel them. On â€œKurdish Radio,â€ Special Interest draw an explicit line between oil lurking under the sands of contested territory and the lives lived in American cities. â€œIs love like Arab oil?/Do we take take take till itâ€™s depleted?â€ Logout sings. Later in the song, they overlay crude oil with blood staining the streets of New Orleans, as if to suggest that connecting local struggle to a global network makes for a start. At the climax of â€œConcerning Peace,â€ Logout calls out the names of metropolises across the world, tethering them together as sites of both historic disinvestment and revolutionary potential.

Amid calls to destroy every kind of cage, Special Interest stay attuned to what might sprout from the ashes. The music video for â€œMidnight Legend,â€ a sweetly melodic dance track whose single version features a verse from Mykki Blanco, follows a group of clubgoers through a messy night out. They flip off a handsy bouncer, ingest a few too many drugs, argue with exasperated bartenders, and get kicked out of the bathroom in the middle of a gay threesome. This club houses little of the utopia the dancefloor can sometimes tease; all night, it plays host to low-grade, aggravating conflict. Then the dancers spill out into the morning light. As passersby hustle their way to work, three of the clubgoers sync up for an impromptu dance routine. The people who have just woken up scowl at those who have been up all night. But the dancers look at each other and beam. Their movements reassure each other that they have each otherâ€™s backs even if no one else does. Under the new sun, they practice another world inside the cracks of this one.

The album rolls to a close with the slow-burning â€œLA Blues,â€ a song that sheds its skin multiple times over the course of its eight minutes. It starts with a handful of neighborhood scenes and a repeated falsetto taunt: â€œIf you donâ€™t like it you can fuck right off/Them boys in blue donâ€™t come around on this block.â€ In the third verse, Logoutâ€™s gaze turns inward. They ruminate on the end of a relationship, approaching a state of tenderness but quickly diverting it with a sarcastic â€œboo hoo,â€ then looping back to the bitterly laughing chorus. But as the song rolls on, as the one-two step of the drumbeat and the guitarâ€™s sour roar refuse to slow or pause, Logout dives deeper. The song boils into a dirge; Logout interrogates God in the wake of an immeasurable loss, their voice strained and cracking. As they hold their grief in its fullness, the song changes again, turning anthem-like, and Logout parts the curtains on a formerly hidden outlook. â€œThe end of the world is just a destination/I had to grow to love/Yes and now I know Iâ€™m not unworthy of love,â€ they conclude, their voice warm and open, defenses scattered on the ground. If this world is barrelling toward a cliff, if thereâ€™s an unavoidable terminus square in our path, maybe we should try to love like we did at the beginning.â€
entries.title: Endure

Any review I read about this new record is top notch. I myself was overwhelmed by Double Negative: still remember walking in Las Vegas on my way to a shopping center having this record on my headphones. 
Their sound is just something else: the distortion combined with the beautiful lyrics. From what I know, this album will only get better with every listening.
entries.title: Hey What

entries.notes: In the context of NilÃ¼fer Yanyaâ€™s second album, the word â€œpainlessâ€ has a few different meanings. â€œI was enjoying the process of making the record, and thinking, â€˜Why do you have to beat yourself up in order to make something?â€™â€ the London singer/guitarist tells Apple Music. â€œObviously, you have to work hard, but often the idea of really struggling is something that people inflict on others, just because it's the idea they sell to them, like, â€˜Oh, you need to go through this.â€™â€ Yanya felt that she hadn't given herself enough time and space to make her 2019 debut, Miss Universeâ€”a record based loosely, and playfully, around the concept of self-help and wellness, and what happens when you get too in your head about things. So, in the thick of the pandemic, she eased into making PAINLESS, writing the songs more collaborativelyâ€”mostly with producer Will Archerâ€”than she had been used to. â€œI kind of felt a bit like, â€˜Am I cheating?â€™ Because you're sharing the work, it feels lighter,â€ she says. "But then because of that, I kind of delved in deeper and it got a bit darker.â€ (The album title actually comes from the â€œshamelessâ€ lyric â€œUntil you fall, it's painless.â€) Those depths can be felt both in Yanya's vocal dynamics and the sense of urgency that underpins much of the album, particularly on opener â€œthe dealerâ€ and â€œstabiliseâ€, the first single. â€œI think the rhythm plays a big part in these songs,â€ Yanya says. â€œYou feel like there needs to be an escape somewhere.â€ Here Yanya talks through PAINLESS, track by track. â€œthe dealerâ€ â€œIt's like when someone's hiding behind their layers, or not being honest, but then also you're not being honest with yourself. My favourite lyric is 'I hope it's just the summertime you grew attached to,' because it's like you're lying to yourself. Youâ€™re not saying, 'Oh, it was this person that made the difference, or it was this person that I miss.' You're just saying, 'I had a great time,' and you're not being honest about why.â€ â€œL/Râ€ â€œ[Producer] Bullion played me this beat, and it had this pitched drum in it. It just made me feel really happy and warm. It had this kind of marching feeling to it, which I really liked. It took us like a year to finish it, but the initial idea came really quickly. I like the almost spoken element to it, because it sounds like you're speaking rather than singing, but then the chorus is very much singingâ€”and it took a while to get that right. It's kind of about so many things. In my notebook at the time, I'd written, 'Do less things'â€”like, less is more. That was my thinking behind the song: trying to enjoy simple things and not overcomplicate things.â€ â€œshamelessâ€ â€œIt's a really intimate song. I felt like it was about someone that's trying to run away from stuff in their life, but they kind of don't have much hope. The vocals are very celestialâ€”not something I really experimented with in the past. At first, I was going to kind of speak the words, but it needed a lighter touch, like something even more delicate.â€ â€œstabiliseâ€ â€œThat was the first one me and Will did together. All the others kind of grew off that song. It's about environments and the way they impact you, and not being able to escape your environment, taking it with you wherever you go. And it kind of becomes your cage or the way you view things. You know when you've been somewhere too long and then it's hard to imagine the world another way? Definitely a very lockdown song.â€ â€œchase meâ€ â€œI really liked the line 'Through corridors your love will chase me,' because it was like the safe feeling you can get when you know you are loved, but you don't necessarily want it. It's almost like an ego song for me. It's very confident.â€ â€œmidnight sunâ€ â€œI was digging into more of an overall feeling and a mood. I feel like it's a song about confidence and finding your own voice in order to speak up, whether that's about your own feelings or bigger issues: â€˜I can't keep my mouth shut this time. I can't keep my head down. I'm not going along with this anymore.â€™â€ â€œtroubleâ€ â€œThat song is so sadâ€”in a beautiful way, if I may say so. It also felt like quite a brave one for me because it's very different. When I was writing, I was like, 'Am I doing a straight-up pop song?' It's not. I think it definitely has that take on it. The vocals needed to be more intimate. Like one voice, and it just all keeps spilling out. It's quite challenging to sing. â€˜Troubleâ€™ is one of those wordsâ€”I think I heard it in a Cat Stevens songâ€”'Trouble, set me free'â€”and I really loved the way it was being referred to almost like a person. In the lyrics here, it's something that's quite persistent and it's not going away. Something's definitely broken that you can't fix.â€ â€œtryâ€ â€œThis one is about getting better, and feeling the need to connect on a deeper level, finding new depths and making new connections, but becoming confused, tired and dejected with the effort it takes.â€ â€œcompanyâ€ â€œIt's about giving up and you're not in a happy place. Originally it started out as, like, you're in a relationship that you are just really not sure about and you're trying to give signs across that you're trying to get rid of someone. But I think the song now is definitely about your inner demons, and they're not really going away.â€ â€œbelong with youâ€ â€œI did this with Jazzi Bobbi, who's in my band. She does more electronic stuff, so that definitely comes into play. I feel like builds are always my favourite things in songs, and at the beginning we actually tried to overcomplicate the song and there was like a whole other section and it changed tempo and it just wasn't working. And I was like, 'We just need to keep building and that's it.' What it's about is like you're tied into something, but you know you're too good for it or you want to leave. I feel like these are all the songs, in a way. Itâ€™s like, escapeâ€”but you can't escape.â€ â€œthe mysticâ€ â€œIt's about watching other people get on with their lives and feeling like you're being left behind. I spend a lot of time doing music, so that's where I put all my energy, and I was like, 'Oh, I thought we were all still doing that.' Other people have got other plans and you're like, 'Oh, you're a grown-up. You're going to move in with your boyfriend,' or, 'Oh, you can drive now.' The verse is really sad, because it's about watching that happen, and feeling very insecure and unconfident.â€ â€œanotherlifeâ€ â€œFor me, this has a completely different energy. It's kind of like you're admitting you're lost now, but in a parallel universe or in the future, you won't always be lost. It's not always bad to be in that kind of lost, super-emotional, flung-out state. I find sometimes when something bad happens and you get really upset, it's kind ofâ€” I don't want to say cleansing, but you see things with this new kind of brilliance and clarity. And that's kind of a beautiful moment.â€
entries.title: PAINLESS

entries.notes: Listen to the fourth album by Scotland-born, LA-based Ross Birchard and youâ€™re liable to feel a little overwhelmed. Sugar rush or religious epiphany? The elation of a good roller coaster or the nausea that sets in when the ride loses control? Birchard likes it all, and by the fistful. Nearly a decade out from his public christening as a producer for Kanye West (â€œMercyâ€, â€œBlood on the Leavesâ€) and half of the jock-jam festival phenomenon TNGHT (with Lunice), heâ€™s become the kind of musician it seems like he wanted to be all along: bright, weird, funky, funny and guided by an optimism so irrepressible you wonder if, deep down, he feels a little sad. â€œStumpâ€ is the most beautiful music that didnâ€™t make Blade Runner. â€œBicstanâ€ is Aphex Twin for a seven-year-oldâ€™s birthday party. He can balance tracks as abstract as â€œKpipeâ€ with ones as direct as â€œ3 Sheets to the Windâ€, and the soulful lag of American rap (â€œRedeemâ€) with the momentum of UK bass (â€œRain Shadowâ€, â€œIs It Supposedâ€), not to mention whatever neon-halo hybrid â€œBeholdâ€ is. This is opera for people raised on anime. And as easy as it is to imagine listening in a big, sweaty room, he knows that most of us will end up taking it in alone on headphonesâ€”and he wants us to have fun.
entries.title: Cry Sugar

entries.notes:
What a remarkable album: 45 minutes using one repeating accord glued together with the sax of Pharoah Sanders, culminating somewhere in the middle in a sound orgy thanks to the London Symphony Orchestra and then fading out once again with the help of Pharoah Sanders. Superb job by Floating Points all over the place.
From Pitchfork: â€œThroughout its emotional 46 minutes, Promises stirs feelings that can be hard to name. The first sound we hear is one that courses through the entire pieceâ€”a brief, seven-note refrain played by what seems to be a harpsichord, sometimes accented by a bell-like tone that could be the celeste. The cluster of sounds begins in silence, and we can hear the creak of wood and some shifting objects in the room where it was recorded, and it repeats every nine seconds for almost the duration of the piece. Itâ€™s a small twinkly loop that brings to mind the feeling of awakening, as if something that was unclear is now understood, there to be rediscovered with each cycle. And that repeating fragment holds the composition together, and every sound exists in relation to it, even if we canâ€™t quite sense how they fit together.â€

entries.notes: Compared to the strutting reggaetÃ³n of KICK ii and the demonic club experiments of KicK iii, kick iiii captures Arca at her most serene. The crooning â€œXenomorphgirlâ€ is a kind of cyborg lullaby; â€œEsunaâ€ curls up like a kitten in the soft swirls of Oliver Coatesâ€™ strings. But serenity is not the same as docility, and kick iiii also features some of Arcaâ€™s most coolly triumphant work to date. On the self-empowerment anthem â€œQueerâ€, Planningtorock testifies to their â€œtears of powerâ€, while on â€œAlien Insideâ€, Garbageâ€™s Shirley Manson solemnly intones the virtues of Arcaâ€™s self-proclaimed â€œmutant faithâ€ over a shimmering shoegaze backdrop. Most affecting of all is Arcaâ€™s own proclamation on â€œLost Woman Foundâ€: â€œIâ€™ve been walking toward the light for years now/And itâ€™s the first time I feel the sunâ€™s warmth on my skin, now that itâ€™s my own/A lost woman, found.â€ The quest for oneâ€™s true identity has long been at the centre of Arcaâ€™s work, and here at the heart of her sprawling, futuristic bildungsroman, she channels years of trauma into something like peace.

entries.notes:
Stunning new album where Four Tet uses many samples of Madlib to compose a delicious mix of beautiful tracks. The first new interesting record of 2021! Fragments of sounds, it is nothing more but every fragment is right on track.

From Pitchfork: â€œSound Ancestors, his new album, is a rare entry in his vast catalog to be billed straightforwardly as a Madlib solo release, not a collaboration with a rapper, or a record by one of several fictitious jazz players and ensembles heâ€™s invented, or an entry in an arcane thematic series. But it, too, is a joint effort, this time with Kieran Hebden, the electronic producer better known as Four Tet, who curated, edited, and arranged its 16 tracks from a body of hundreds of recordings that Madlib sent him over a period of two years. Their process reminds me of 2003â€™s Shades of Blue, which Madlib created by raiding the vaults of Blue Note Records, sometimes chopping the original jazz recordings intricately and sometimes letting them unfold for long stretches without much apparent editing. Now, Madlib is the one opening his archives, and Four Tet is the one listening and assembling.â€
entries.title: Sound Ancestors

entries.notes: Brimming with astrological fervour and unbridled emotionality, Red Moon in Venus finds the Colombian American sensation zeroing in on love. From the proud promises behind â€œEndlesslyâ€ to the sweet little profundities of â€œLove Between...â€, the album plays with genre without losing cohesion or connection. On the guest front, Don Toliver matches her R&B potency amid the polyrhythmic blur of â€œFantasyâ€, while Omar Apollo brings his own certain charm to the sumptuous duet â€œWorth the Waitâ€. Yet most of the album keeps the spotlight rightfully on her, leading to breathtaking moments like â€œI Wish You Rosesâ€ and the Sade-esque â€œBlueâ€. And while Red Moon in Venus returns the artist to a primarily English-language mode, she hasnâ€™t dispatched entirely with the approach taken on 2020â€™s Sin Miedo (del Amor y Otros Demonios) âˆž. She brings bilingual lyricism alongside orchestral accents for â€œComo Te Quiero Yoâ€ and retro grooves for â€œHasta Cuandoâ€.
entries.title: Red Moon In Venus

entries.notes: Black Thought may be best-known as part of The Roots, performing night after late night for Jimmy Fallonâ€™s TV audience, yet the Philadelphia native concurrently boasts a staggering reputation as a stand-alone rapper. Though heâ€™s earned GOAT nods from listeners for earth-shaking features alongside Big Pun, Eminem and Rapsody, his solo catalogue long remained relatively modest in size. Meanwhile, Danger Mouse had a short yet monumental run in the 2000s that made him one of that decadeâ€™s most beloved and respected producers. His discography from that period contains no shortage of microphone dynamos, most notably MF DOOM (as DANGERDOOM) and Goodie Mobâ€™s CeeLo Green (as Gnarls Barkley). Uniting these low-key hip-hop powerhouses is the stuff of hip-hop dreams, the kind of fantasy-league-style draft youâ€™d encounter on rap message boards. Yet Cheat Codes is realâ€”perhaps realer than real. Danger Mouseâ€™s penchant for quirkily cinematic, subtly soulful soundscapes remains from the old days, but the growth from his 2010s work with the likes of composer Daniele Luppi gives â€œAquamarineâ€ and â€œSometimesâ€ undeniable big-screen energy. Black Thought luxuriates over these luxurious beats, his lyrical lexicon put to excellent use over the feverish funk of â€œNo Gold Teethâ€ and the rollicking blues of â€œClose to Famousâ€. As if their team-up wasnâ€™t enough, an intergenerational cabal of rapper guests bless the proceedings. From living legend Raekwon to A$AP Rocky to Conway the Machine, New York artists play a pivotal role here. A lost DOOM verse, apparently from The Mouse and the Mask sessions, makes its way onto the sauntering and sunny â€œBelizeâ€, another gift for the fans.
entries.title: Cheat Codes

entries.notes: Listeners expecting the stylish soul-funk of Saultâ€™s 2020 albums Untitled (Rise) and Untitled (Black Is) might be momentarily thrown by the cosmic choral-and-orchestral suite of Air, but thematically, it fits: Like all their music, Air is, at heart, a study of Black artistic traditions, in this case early-â€™70s Alice Coltrane (â€œSolarâ€), the soulful ambience of Stevie Wonderâ€™s Journey Through the Secret Life of Plants (â€œHeartâ€), even a little of the modern-classical side of artists like Anthony Braxton. And as sci-fi as the sound can seem, the core feeling is one of uplifting Earthâ€”a message confirmed as equally by the skyward arc of the strings as by the prayer-like recitation on â€œTime Is Preciousâ€. Or, as producer Inflo tells Apple Music, not fantasy, but â€œart in realityâ€â€”air.
entries.title: Air

entries.notes:
Pitchfork: 

â€œAfter experiments in free jazz and psychedelia, the UK producer reckons with the rave music of his youth. Itâ€™s a utopian project that melds dance musicâ€™s forms with an organic sensibility.

Drop the needle at any given point on James Holdenâ€™s fourth album, and you might think the music is building toward carefully orchestrated catharsis: the moment when the big melody finally drops in, or the various rhythms cohere into a single body-moving lockstep, and the crowd loses its collective mind. There were plenty of those moments in Holdenâ€™s earlier work, when he was a young DJ making sweeping trance and progressive techno anthems. But time and time again on Imagine This Is a High Dimensional Space of All Possibilities, the climax turns out to be an illusion. A filter sweep reaches its apex to reveal the full glowing resonance of a particular synth, and you realize the pulse of its chord progression has been working at cross purposes with the rest of the track, pulling you away from its patient groove rather than toward it. A strobe-lit rave piano arrives just in time for the drums to drop out entirely. 

Holden has said that the album is his attempt to recreate the sense of hearing, as a teenager, far-off pirate radio broadcasts of early UK dance music, the soundtracks to a woolly and utopian rave scene that had largely dried up by the time he was old enough to make music professionally and had to settle for more slickly commercial sounds. Thematically, this is not so different from the territory where Burial has made his career, summoning the atmospheres of emptied-out warehouse parties and solitary walks home. Rather than mourning a paradise lost, Holden instead focuses on the joy and freedom his younger self imagined those ravers must have been feeling. Every individual sound is as bright and welcoming as can be. Itâ€™s the way that these sounds cohereâ€”or more often, refuse toâ€”that suggests a certain distance. The albumâ€™s new-agey title may provoke eye rolls in some listeners, but the first word poignantly grounds it. If we have to imagine that this is a place where everything is possible, it probably isnâ€™t in reality. 

By the time of Holdenâ€™s first album, 2006â€™s The Idiots Are Winning, he was already dislodging himself from the club; his third, 2017â€™s The Animal Spirits, looked like a final break, with Holden leading a full live band on excursions into free jazz and Terry Riley-ish minimalism. His full-lengths have also reflected a growing interest in oblique, free-flowing rhythms, seemingly inspired by the unpredictable complexity of the natural world rather than the mechanistic precision of much dance music. While High Dimensional Space on one level represents a return to the timbres of clubland, it retains this organic sensibility. Acoustic instruments like saxophone and tabla punctuate â€œCommon Landâ€ and â€œContains Multitudes,â€ respectively. The latter also plays with your expectation that the sounds of electronic dance music will stick to their own narrowly defined bands of the frequency range and roles in the larger arrangement. One particular keyboard ostinato begins in the middle, and traverses down to sub-bass depths and up to piercing heights over the course of the track. Listening closely is like watching a time lapse of a treeâ€™s roots bursting through the sidewalk. 

The quality of the rhythms across the album, each developing concurrently at its own pace rather than in strict alignment, mirrors the fragmentary timelines of nature as well. â€œTrust Your Feetâ€ comes tantalizingly close to ecstatic release, its arpeggios percolating onward past the juncture where they might have locked in with the other instruments to deliver a satisfying payoff. Witnessing waterfalls and sunsets, thereâ€™s no single perfect moment when all the elements come together and make their mysterious relationships clear; this music works similarly, absorbing you in the whole of its trajectory rather than any specific waypoint. 

The lack of definitive resolutions can make the album at times difficult to really love, rather than just appreciate or admire, despite the musicâ€™s unflagging optimism. The rare moments when everything does come together are the ones that move me the most: the tumbling snare drum and burbling modular synth of â€œContinuous Revolution,â€ rushing together toward a horizon we never quite glimpse; the droning violins and unexpectedly funky bass guitar of â€œWorlds Collide, Mountains Form,â€ which sound a bit like what might happen if the ancient architects of Stonehenge decided to form a jam band. In between these set pieces, the full enjoyment of Imagine This Is a High Dimensional Space of All Possibilities requires some imagination of your own, a sort of listening past the vaporous surface of the music. Like teenage Holden at the radio, you may sense a magical world there, just beyond what you can hear. â€œ
entries.title: Imagine This Is a High Dimensional Space of All Possibilities

070 Shake sounds like sheâ€™s in pain across You Canâ€™t Kill Me. If love was an inspiration for the Jersey-hailing G.O.O.D. Music signee's follow-up to 2020â€™s Modus Vivendi, it is only to the extent that it has wounded her, caused her to wound someone else or forced her to treat wounds of her own. The project is heavy and operatic (production credits list Dave Sitek, johan lenox and Dave Hamelin, among others), and Shake sings frequently about relationships past (â€œWebâ€, â€œStayâ€, â€œMedicineâ€, â€œSe Fue La Luzâ€), present (â€œBlue Velvetâ€, â€œCocoonâ€, â€œWine & Spiritsâ€) and, in one instanceâ€”hopefullyâ€”future (â€œInvitedâ€). Whatâ€™s clearer than anything else across You Canâ€™t Kill Me is that 070 Shake knows how to turn her pain into art. Or maybe itâ€™s more like she tells us on â€œWine & Spiritsâ€, that â€œLife is about balance, war and harmony/Canâ€™t have one without the other.â€

entries.notes:
During the disorienting first few months of the pandemic, Simon Green hit a creative block. The British electronic musician, better known as Bonobo, felt trapped and isolated working out of his home in east Los Angeles, starved for live music and human interaction. â€œI desperately needed to get into a different headspace,â€ he tells Apple Music. â€œReally, I needed to get out of the house.â€ Green began taking solo camping trips into the areaâ€™s remote mountains and deserts in an effort to get his creative juices flowing. â€œExploring California was a great way of breaking the monotony of being indoors all day,â€ he says. â€œDuring this time of zero stimulation, I felt like I had to make it for myself.â€ Fragments, his moody seventh album, born from these adventures, is a tribute to the West Coastâ€™s wide-open spaces. A laidback mix of mesmerising techno, orchestral instrumentation and hushed R&B balladry, the project is as sprawling, peaceful and varied as the landscape itself. Here, he takes us inside the making of each track.
â€œPolyghostâ€ (feat. Miguel Atwood-Ferguson) â€œThis began as a long, drawn-out, seven-minute techno track that didnâ€™t make the final cut. But it was built on top of two important thematic elements: harp, which is played by Lara Somogyi, who I recorded and then sampled, and strings, which are played by Miguel Atwood-Ferguson. In the end, I decided to keep just those two parts because they weave throughout the rest of the record and drew everything together. The minute I did that, it became the obvious opener.â€
â€œShadowsâ€ (feat. Jordan Rakei) â€œBack in 2019, before I even started assembling this album, I was working on a track that felt like a reference to guys like Theo Parrish and Moodymannâ€”that swingy, old-school Detroit sound. I had been listening to that Andrew Ashong song â€˜Flowersâ€™ and felt like, with a vocalist, this could be in that same area. I reached out to Jordan, who helped me work out the structureâ€”a bit of tension and releaseâ€”and it wound up being one of the first tracks I had in place for this project. Iâ€™ve been sitting on it for almost three years.â€
â€œRosewoodâ€ â€œA good ways into making this album, I started to feel like I had the record but I didnâ€™t have a proper single. So I went through my iPhone notes and voice memos and found a little piano loop that jumped out at me. I pulled it into Ableton and put a little kick drum under it and immediately felt like it could be the seeds of something. For the hook, I found this R&B a cappella on YouTube that had this little lyric of â€˜I won't leave you.â€™ And I knew that was it.â€
â€œOtomoâ€ (feat. Oâ€™Flynn) â€œThis features an archived folk recording of a Bulgarian bagpipe choir that, to me, feels like a huge sample. Itâ€™s this big, droning, ethereal, cathedral-y thing, and I hadnâ€™t heard anything like it before. I felt like it deserved to have some big moments around it, so I reached out to my friend O'Flynn, who does that so wellâ€”switching between tuneful melodies and percussive muscle. He wound up building an entire section for it, without even me prompting him, and it was perfect. Itâ€™s definitely the track thatâ€™s going to get played out in the club.â€
â€œTidesâ€ (feat. Jamila Woods) â€œIâ€™d been talking to Jamila and a few other vocalists about doing some collaborations, but nobody was feeling particularly motivatedâ€”it was too early into the pandemic. But then, in 2021, people came to life. Jamila texted me that she was going into the studio to record something, and it wound up being a demo thatâ€™s on the record. Hearing it really kick-started my creative energy. I remember when she first sent it to me, I was heading out for the night and was like, â€˜I'm going to wait to listen to this until I get home, when I can really give it my full attention.' When I got back, I'd had a couple glasses of wine, so I was in the perfect state. I hit play, and I was just...overcome. I almost cried. It was like suddenly there was an emotional centrepiece to the record. It changed everything.â€
â€œElysianâ€ â€œThis one is named after Elysian Park, which is very close to where I live in LA. Because it was the pandemic and most things were closed, I spent a lot of time in the park, going for walks, cycling up to Angels Point and so on. As this song came together, I listened to it while walking around in Elysian, so the tribute felt appropriate. Itâ€™s the midway point of the record, and felt like a good place to have a nice acoustic interlude. A moment of pause.â€
â€œCloserâ€ â€œI was digging around in my archives and stumbled upon an old session recording with Andreya Triana, a singer-songwriter who Iâ€™d worked with back in 2009. I produced her debut album, Lost Where I Belong, in my apartment in London. I pulled some vocals from this one track â€˜Far Closerâ€™, and it worked really well. I hit her up and was like, â€˜Hey! Remember this vocal? I've started sampling it again on this other thing.â€™ She got a kick out of it.â€ 
â€œAge of Phaseâ€ â€œThroughout this whole process, I was playing a lot with modular synths. It was a way of keeping the process exciting, to learn how to use different technology. â€˜Age of Phaseâ€™ is basically exclusively modular synths, apart from the vocals, and that was a new thing for me. I wanted to create all these interweaving melodies and vocals and have everything reach this chaotic peak, before diving down into something really lush. I'm going to try to deconstruct it for the live show and see how far I can push that idea.â€
â€œFrom Youâ€ (feat. Joji) â€œThis one seems like itâ€™s a bit of a curveball for some people. Maybe myself as well. But I was trying to do something that sounded a bit more like contemporary hip-hop and R&B. I was listening to Kehlani, SZA, slowthai, even some James Blake, and was really inspired by that blended sound. I'd always wanted to work with Joji, because I think he's a really interesting musician, and when the parts all came together I was like, â€˜Wow, okay, this is kind of a pop song. And I'm kind of into that.â€™â€
â€œCounterpartâ€ â€œThis song came together early on and was exactly the mix of sounds I was looking forâ€”a little bit techno, but quite melodic, with lots of modular synths. It was so fun to make that I was sad when I finished it, so now Iâ€™m working on a live version as well. I think itâ€™s going to have multiple lives.â€
â€œSapienâ€ â€œThis is my throwback to early-'90s raveâ€”artists like Mike Paradinas, Rephlex and Future Sound of London, that era of melodic, ravey breakbeats. I sent the piano part into a modular so I could get all those choppy synth parts that are actually from a Rhodes piano, and then I went apeshit on drum programming at the end as a way to hearken back to that era of frenetic drum breaks. Itâ€™s one of the more abrasive moments on the record, which I really like.â€
â€œDay by Dayâ€ (feat. Kadhja Bonet) â€œThis is a straight R&B jam, really. I had spoken to Kadhja for ages and we'd sent demos back and forth. And the thing I like about this one is that it references earlier stuff of mine. It feels like it could be from the Black Sands era, which makes me feel like Iâ€™ve come full circle. I also like that it has a sense of optimism as the album closer, serving as a reminder that everythingâ€™s going to be all right.â€
entries.title: Fragments

entries.notes: Composed during the darkest days of the pandemic, this beautiful album reunites Dutch composer Joep Beving with his cherished Schimmel upright piano and offers up beauty and peace in a destabilised world. Hermetism is inspired by ancient philosophical ideas of nature and the universe. No track rises far above a whisper, yet they are all compelling in their expressive power. Beving journeys through an array of influences, from the timelessness of Bach (â€œAccent Graveâ€, â€œLast Danceâ€) and Eastern modal inflection (â€œDervishâ€) to the haunting simplicity of 19th-century French composer Erik Satie (â€œLe fee verteâ€). In the childlike, Chopin-inspired waltz â€œParis sâ€™enflammeâ€, Beving pays a heartfelt tribute to the French capital, while the final track, â€œRosesâ€, takes the role of a calming, hypnotic postlude.
entries.title: Hermetism
