entries.notes: On his milestone 10th album, pianist, composer, improviser and healer Nduduzo Makhathini distils a decadeâ€™s worth of creative output into an offering that reflects upon both his and his forebearerâ€™s footsteps. â€œThis whole journey started in 2012, when I went to studio to record my debut album,â€ he tells Apple Music. â€œThis is me summarising my journey. This is the moment for a birdâ€™s-eye view of the recurring themes and dialoguing thatâ€™s been taking place.â€ In the Spirit of Ntu muses on various ideasâ€”from a range of disciplinesâ€”that collectively shape us. â€œAn underpinning concept of ubuntu is that everything that lives carries vital force, and this vital force is what counts as â€˜Ntuâ€™,â€ Makhatini explains. â€œIâ€™ve found that the hinge that connects all African art, music, religions, worldviews and histories is this notion of Ntu. This is the part the colonial system was not able to erase. This album is an intervention to hold on to the things that refused to be removed.â€ Crafted by a talented young lineup, these 10 tracks situate Makhathiniâ€™s ideas in the realm of sound. â€œI was grappling with what it means to locate the sonic inside of these conversations,â€ he says. â€œYou exist in the context of the whole, and that became the underpinning conceptual view towards the bandstandâ€”all the musicians are younger than me, to build continuity within that shared â€˜insidenessâ€™ of this cultural sphere.â€ Here, Makhathini breaks down key tracks from the album. â€œUnonkanyambaâ€ â€œWhen I was growing up, there was this myth that if there were heavy quakes, Inkanyamba [the serpent] was emerging from beneath the earth. When it emerges, thereâ€™s no way you can survive, and we were told we couldnâ€™t see it cause weâ€™d die immediately. As a kid, Iâ€™d internalised this as a masculine energy. Here, I use the idea of â€˜Unoâ€™ as pointing towards a different polarity. What if these energies were feminine? Anything that has to do with water, we consult Nomkhubulwaneâ€”thatâ€™s a deity or divinity for rain. Thereâ€™s a sense in which the arising of Unonkanymaba could be seen as a metaphor for all the things that could possibly emerge from beneath the earth.â€ â€œMamaâ€ (feat. Omagugu) â€œThis whole album is underpinned by Ntu configured as essence, and essence as a space of origin. Thereâ€™s always this feminine energy surrounding the womb and water. â€˜Mamaâ€™ is a human manifestation of what Unonkanyamba would mean at a cosmic level. My wife, Omagugu, composed [this song] for my mother-in-law, who got sick and passed away. Itâ€™s paying tribute to a mother in a spiritual formâ€”as part of the lineage of ancestors that can make interventions on our behalf. The sonic arrangement starts with a gentleness, then builds, almost like a foetus growing in the womb. The break is the idea of giving birth as something that is high frequency. Though it tries to give a sonic feeling of what it means to be a mother, it asks what it means to lose one.â€ â€Amathongoâ€ â€œIn English, we say youâ€™re in â€˜deep sleepâ€™, which has nothing to do with being elsewhereâ€”in a world that functions. In isiZulu, we say â€˜usebuthongweniâ€™, which means he or she is one with the â€˜star godsâ€™ or amathongo. That says something about sleep as this moment where weâ€™re actually alive in another reality. Ntu speaks about how we collapse these two realities. So, when I say, â€˜Vumani vumani vumani weZangoma,â€™ itâ€™s because you have to surrender. Through this invocation of â€˜ukuvumaâ€™ [â€˜to agree or concurâ€™], a collective agreement enables a ritual state where time and space are suspended. When I grew up, jazz musicians had no sense of cultural situatedness. There was no relationship between amathongo and the things that we see around us, until Busi Mhlongo and Zim Ngqawana arrived. They brought these connections in a more deliberate way, so this is part of that codification.â€ â€œEmlilweniâ€ (feat. Jaleel Shaw) â€œIn various creation stories on the [African] continent, the earth was once filled with fire. When water emerged, all the fires escaped to the underworlds as a sign of obedience. As we speak about the underworlds, we also speak about the location of our ancestors, so itâ€™s interesting to me how South Africans use fire as one of our codes for expressing our tiredness. We're so tired, weâ€™re telling our ancestors that we need bigger interventions. This was the language post-coloniality and still is. Throughout these time periods, weâ€™ve viewed musicians as operating from the edges of these burning firesâ€”to propel the fire burning in the middle. Given the urgency of things to change in a very fragile system, thereâ€™s an even deeper urgency for musicians to enunciate from within these burning fires instead of from around them.â€ â€œOmnyamaâ€ â€œWhen I first heard Mfazâ€™Omnyama, his voice would just cut through. He always projected something that was distant from hereâ€”something untouchable by the systems. Babâ€™ Mfazâ€™Omnyama, Mamâ€™ Busi Mhlongo and Babâ€™ Phuzekhemisi were unlocking codes, and if you heard that, that was your access. They were like, â€˜Iâ€™m giving this to you, and the only way to enter is for you to hear, to sense.â€™ I think of Maskanda musicians as a radical movement. To pick up a Western classical instrument and do a full-on colonisation of it is radicalâ€”the guitar was speaking English, and they made it speak isiZulu! Through this unconventional tuning, they were telling us something deeper about how to make these tools obey your own story.â€ â€œSenzeâ€™ Ninaâ€ â€œWeâ€™ve seen how men are targeted in a deep way, even during apartheid. We grew up without our fathers, and these were the creations of dysfunctionality in the Black family. There are problematic constructs weâ€™ve created ourselves, too, and men really need to add gentleness to their vocabulary of masculinity. â€˜Senzeâ€™ Ninaâ€™ is about the truth that at the very core of every man lives a gentleness that is inherent just by the mere fact that they were born of a mother. I propose the idea of the making of a new man when that gentleness needs to be reawakened. Some of the most powerful things are projected with a gentleness!â€ â€œNtuâ€ â€œIn the Spirit of Ntu starts with all these things that are clashing and conflicting, and it ends with this gentle solo pianoâ€”this very utopian place. All the things that happen on this album are things that you can see, but this last song leads into a dream and happens elsewhere. This music is one of those ritual technologies that takes us to different locations, where you enter a space and come out of it different. Ntu is that reconfiguration of self.â€
entries.title: In The Spirit Of Ntu

entries.notes: After the pandemic hit, Harley Streten left his adopted home, LA, for his real one, Australia. He moved to Byron Bay in Northern NSW and set up a new, quieter life for himself. â€œIâ€™ve got property, I live on an acreage, I just live a simple life,â€ he tells Apple Music. â€œI grow my own vegetables. I have a snake that lives in my roof that sometimes crawls down to my front door.â€ Itâ€™s about as far removed as you can get from the bustle and drama of the city that placed him into â€œnot in a particularly productive space or good spaceâ€. Itâ€™s here that he set up a new studio and got to work on the pieces that would become his third album, Palaces. The producerâ€™s first two albums propelled him from Sydneyâ€™s nightclubs to festival stages around the world. His 2016 release, Skin, was built on the warped, unique production style heâ€™d become known for and earned him his first Grammy. The next few years were packed with touringâ€”until the pandemic hit. â€œThis time has been really good for me, mentallyâ€”itâ€™s just really given me a chance to slow down,â€ he says. â€œI got on this train, it started speeding up and getting faster and faster. When I was 19, I started touring and it just didnâ€™t stop. Then COVID happened, and I had two years to just be a normal human. Itâ€™s been fantastic.â€ Palaces stretches in every direction. The sounds and style Streten is known for flings itself into new places, big and small, heavy and tender. Thereâ€™s a healthy array of collaborators, including Caroline Polachek, who sings on the cinematic â€œSirensâ€. â€œIâ€™m really proud of that song,â€ Streten says. â€œCaroline was in lockdown at the time in London and she was hearing all the sirens outside. The song is like, â€˜I wish I could start world peace. It would be really lovely to be able to just wave a wand and end all suffering.â€™â€ Stretenâ€™s trademark head rush of textures is still well-represented on the skittering â€œESCAPEâ€ (featuring longtime collaborator KuÄka), â€œHollowâ€ (featuring Emma Louise) and â€œSay Nothingâ€ (featuring MAY-A)â€”all proof of his continuing expertise when it comes to big, emotive pop. Meanwhile, Spanish DJ and producer Virgen Maria evokes playful sexuality with her vocal contributions on â€œOnly Fansâ€. â€œIt can go from zero to 100 and then back to zero,â€ he says of his musicâ€™s sudden hairpin turns and mood swings. But there are plenty of soft, ruminative moments here, too, such as ambient centrepiece â€œJasperâ€™s Songâ€, featuring pianist Jasper Harris. â€œThat was originally a house track,â€ Streten reveals. â€œIt was a full house banger. But I then felt like it took away from the beauty of it, so I stripped it all the way back and just had it as this ambient piano piece. It feels like a nice contrast in the record. Thereâ€™s a lot of hard stuff, so itâ€™s nice to have some really mellow, warm feelings.â€ And the closing track concludes the album in a gorgeous, atmospheric manner. It starts with field recordings from around Stretenâ€™s property, and slowly builds, rhythm and ambient chords billowing out behind Damon Albarnâ€™s vocals. â€œWorking with him, it was cool,â€ Streten says. â€œIâ€™m a huge fan. I was nervous. I was fucking nervous.â€ A decade since his debut album, Streten has found his stride. Much like how his music darts from intense to meditative, hard-hitting to mellow, heâ€™s realised his life, too, is all about equilibrium. â€œNow, Iâ€™ve got a really nice balance between LA and Australia, two ends of the spectrum,â€ he says. But he canâ€™t overstate how important his choice was to move home, to take a break. In fact, the album name was inspired by the solace he felt after leaving LA. â€œIâ€™d gone home to Australia, started life in the countryside and felt like Iâ€™d found my palace. Thatâ€™s where the record really came together. I was having a bit of trouble with music in the States. Going homeâ€”all that room, the simple life, it just gave me the space to create. And it just felt like a sanctuary.â€
entries.title: Palaces

entries.notes: â€œI had a responsibility to give people what they were asking for, especially during the pandemic,â€ Robert Glasper tells Apple Music. â€œThey wanted another Black Radio, so I had to deliver.â€ The pianist, composer, songwriter and producer has spent the past decade pushing the boundaries of what constitutes jazz music, combining its acoustic instrumentation with hip-hop swagger, R&B melodies and an ear attuned to improvisation. Ten years after the first Black Radio album, he returns to the genre-hopping, collaborative format, producing 13 tracks that seamlessly transition from the power of Amir Sulaimanâ€™s poetry on opener â€œIn Tuneâ€ to an elegantly downbeat version of Tears for Fearsâ€™ â€œEverybody Wants to Rule the Worldâ€ to the funk of â€œWhy We Speakâ€ with Q-Tip and Esperanza Spalding. Here, Glasper talks through all the collaborations, track by track. â€œIn Tuneâ€ (feat. Amir Sulaiman) â€œI was scoring a Dave Chappelle documentary, and in the film, Amir performs a poem that floored me. Iâ€™ve never had a poem reach me that way. I was in tears. I immediately asked Dave to connect us, and we had a short conversation about what I was looking for. Two days later, he came back with this incredible poem that opens the record. A lot has happened in the 10 years since the first Black Radio, and a whole lot has happened for Black people in America in the last two years. I felt like I had to address the elephant in the room with this track and with â€˜Black Superheroâ€™.â€ â€œBlack Superheroâ€ (feat. Killer Mike, BJ The Chicago Kid & Big K.R.I.T.) â€œBJ is my bro, but this is the first time weâ€™ve done something together on wax. He came to the studio, and I was just playing around and testing the keyboard and he said, â€˜That sounds like some superhero shit,â€™ so I kept playing and the concept started from there. After that, I wanted to pick rappers that teach us. I wanted them to say something that spoke to this moment. I knew K.R.I.T. and Killer Mike would do it justice.â€ â€œShineâ€ (feat. Robert Glasper, D Smoke & Tiffany Gouche) â€œâ€˜Shineâ€™ came out of a jam session. I was playing drums and my drummer was playing keys and we came up with this riff that I then looped. I refined it on keys and added bass and then sent it to D Smoke to see what he thought. He sent me back a draft the next day. The song is all about self-love and knowing that youâ€™re enough. Thatâ€™s something I feel like a lot of hip-hop songs donâ€™t talk about, and especially during the pandemic, people needed to hear that.â€ â€œWhy We Speakâ€ (feat. Q-Tip & Esperanza Spalding) â€œA lot of my music starts off with jam sessions. I have my guys come over and we throw down some vibes and see what sticks. We came up with this joint and, immediately, I thought of Esperanza. I sent it to her and a few days later, she sent it back, and I thought something was wrong with the mic. She never told me she was writing it in French! I thought it was so dope, though, and I realised it sounded like something that would fit Q-Tip too. I used to play in his band, but Iâ€™ve never had him rock on an album, so it was perfect.â€ â€œOverâ€ (feat. Yebba) â€œYebba was part of the Fuck Yo Feelings sessions. Sheâ€™s become like a little sister to me since, and I knew I had to have her on the record. While we were at Electric Lady Studios, listening to her latest album, we jammed and came up with this pattern and the skeleton of the song. That was in early 2021, and a few months later, we got back to LA and finished up here at my studio. Her voice is so beautiful, and Iâ€™m so happy we got to make this one together.â€ â€œBetter Than I Imaginedâ€ (feat. H.E.R. + Meshell Ndegeocello) â€œI scored a film called The Photograph, which came out in February 2020. H.E.R. sang the ending song for the movie, and at the premiere, she told me she was so inspired by my score that she wanted to write something together. We literally went from the movie theatre to the studio and wrote â€˜Better Than I Imaginedâ€™. It wasnâ€™t planned for any project, but it did so well when I put it out, it planted the seed for the rest of Black Radio III.â€ â€œEverybody Wants to Rule the Worldâ€ (feat. Lalah Hathaway & Common) â€œI have this thing with Lalah. On the first Black Radio, she did a cover of â€˜Cherish the Dayâ€™ and killed it. The next time, I was like, â€˜Letâ€™s do Stevie Wonderâ€™s â€œJesus Children of Americaâ€.â€™ She recorded it in one take, and it won a Grammy. So why not keep it going? Iâ€™ve always loved â€˜Everybody Wants to Rule the Worldâ€™â€”I donâ€™t think I would trust a person who doesnâ€™t like that songâ€”but I donâ€™t know anyone who has made a version of it. I redid it in my own vibe, and Common loved it so much, he invited himself on it too!â€ â€œEverybody Loveâ€ (feat. Musiq Soulchild & Posdnous) â€œMy DJ, Jahi Sundance, and I wanted to make a house EP together, and this was the first song we wrote for it. I sent it to Musiq Soulchild, who I have known for a long time, and he came up with his joint in three days. Iâ€™ve never done a house song and neither has he, so it was new for both of us. It has a party vibe, and when it comes to party rappers, I always think of De La Soul and Posdnuos. I knew he would kill it, and he delivered.â€ â€œIt Donâ€™t Matterâ€ (feat. Gregory Porter & Ledisi) â€œI have wanted to produce an R&B album with Gregory for a while now, and when his tour with Ledisi got cancelled, I called them both up. I was luckily able to get them in the studio because the COVID restrictions had eased at that point, and they wrote it to fit their voices. Theyâ€™re both so powerful and definitely have their own sound, so this felt like a match made in heaven.â€ â€œHeavenâ€™s Hereâ€ (feat. Ant Clemons) â€œI went to Snoop Doggâ€™s birthday party and on my way out, Ant Clemons stopped me and introduced himself. Terrace Martin told me that heâ€™s high-level and that we should work together. Fast-forward to the next week and we started writing songs. We wrote four or five tracks since he was working with Justin Timberlake on his new album and Usher too. This was one we were going to give to Usher, but it didnâ€™t work out with the timing. I love it so much, I had to put it on Black Radio.â€ â€œOut of My Handsâ€ (feat. Jennifer Hudson) â€œJennifer came to one of my shows with my homegirl Kelly Rowland, who I know from Houston. They both sat in with me onstage, and I knew I had to get Jennifer on something. When I wrote this song, I heard her voice on it. It took us a little while to get together, but she performed it perfectly.â€ â€œForeverâ€ (feat. PJ Morton & India.Arie) â€œPJ worked with me on Black Radio 2 back in 2013, and he wrote the song â€˜Worriesâ€™, which Dwele sang. I love matching people up whoâ€™ve never recorded together, since it makes the song become more special. I knew PJ and India would sound perfect together, and we luckily managed to make this more of a back-and-forth process to make it feel like a duet where we were in the studio at the same time.â€ â€œBright Lightsâ€ (feat. Ty Dolla $ign)â€ â€œIâ€™ve jammed with Ty before. He is a legend who changed the game up, and I wanted to do something with a modern, pop-R&B vibe because thatâ€™s where Ty thrives. Itâ€™s different from any of the other Black Radio tracks that Iâ€™ve made, and so I wanted to end the album with this one because it has such a unique feel.â€
entries.title: Black Radio III

entries.notes: Itâ€™s not easy to dance with oneâ€™s tongue buried deeply in cheek. But Charlotte AdigÃ©ry and Bolis Pupul effortlessly combine lean, punchy electro-pop with an unapologetically sarcastic sense of humour. On the Belgian duoâ€™s debut album, Topical Dancer, the two musicians draw on their multicultural backgrounds to take sly potshots at racism, sexism and self-doubt. On â€œEsperantoâ€, AdigÃ©ry riffs on microaggressions over plunging electric bass, and on â€œBlendaâ€, she marries a crisp, funky groove with a surprisingly vulnerable chorus: â€œGo back to your country where you belong/Siri, can you tell me where I belong?â€ Co-produced by their long-time collaborators Soulwax, the album slices neatly across the overlap between punky disco, indie dance and underground house; â€™80s avant-pop influences (Art of Noise, Talking Heads) brush up against the sing-speaking wit of contemporaries like Marie Davidson and Dry Cleaning. Some of the albumâ€™s most powerful moments transcend language entirely: On â€œHahaâ€, AdigÃ©ryâ€™s laughter is chopped up and dribbled over an EBM-inspired beat, making for a slow-motion floor-filler thatâ€™s as surreal as it is captivating.

As Pitchfork writes: 
Hereâ€™s every iteration of Lana Del Rey weâ€™ve ever seen, each one cracking open to reveal another guise: Norman-era AOR Lana into Ultraviolence-era nihilist Lana into Chemtrails-era folk Lana intoâ€”after the songâ€™s tense, jaw-dropping switch-upâ€”the bratty, half-rapping, trap-loving Lanas of Born to Die, Honeymoon, and Lust for Life. The title â€œA&Wâ€ both refers to the roadside chain restaurant and stands for â€œAmerican Whoreâ€â€”the original title, according to producer Jack Antonoff. In the song, Lana garbles the name of a Marielle Heller film, references a three-star hotel and Forensic Files, and interpolates a doo-wop standard you might know from the Tom Hanks film Big. A man named Jimmy appears, perhaps the same mythic Jim whoâ€™s popped up throughout her discography, as do chopped up, tape-filtered strings that sound like theyâ€™re from â€œNorman Fucking Rockwell.â€ If a single song could act as a crash source in Lana signifiers, this would be it.

And yet, taken as a whole, â€œA&Wâ€ is unlike anything sheâ€™s ever made. Itâ€™s a psychedelic, collagist freakout that rides from exasperationâ€”â€œIâ€™m a princess, Iâ€™m divisive/Ask me why Iâ€™m like this/Maybe I just kinda like thisâ€â€”all the way through to the delirious liberation of accepting your status as a lifelong outcast. By its end, sheâ€™s taunting the object of her affection with a wry, wily grin: â€œYour mom called, I told her youâ€™re fucking up big time/But I donâ€™t care, baby, I already lost my mind.â€ Lana has always operated with a kind of creative abandon seemingly at odds with conventional wisdom, but â€œA&Wâ€ might be the ultimate expression of that wildness, a chimeric, haunted folk-trap ballad welded together with nothing but the heat of her own star power.

And exactly this describes the song best: â€œWithout a doubt, Nayarâ€™s most blissful and impressive demonstration of these compositional skills is displayed on the titanic â€œTetramorphâ€, a ten-minute, three-act astral projection that is not only the best song on Heaven Come Crashing, but one of the best songs released by any artist this year. Disorientingly panned synths introduce the listener to a sunrise over an urban sprawl, followed by heavenly waves of swells and distant tremolo picking. This euphoric combination builds in intensity for four minutes before giving way to the albumâ€™s most aggressive section, marked by skittish hi-hats, glitchier electronics, and towering supersaws. Before this outburst can even be grasped onto, the storm has dissipated, and the songâ€™s intro is stunningly revisited before an ambient guitar outro that is nothing shy of exhilarating.â€

entries.notes: Like its title suggests, Dragon New Warm Mountain I Believe in You continues Big Thiefâ€™s shift away from their tense, early music toward something folkier and more cosmically inviting. Theyâ€™ve always had an interest in Americana, but their touchpoints are warmer now: A sweetly sawing fiddle (â€œSpud Infinityâ€), a front-porch lullaby (â€œDried Rosesâ€), the wonder of a walk in the woods (â€œPromise Is a Pendulumâ€) or comfort of a kitchen where the radioâ€™s on and food sizzles in the pan (â€œRed Moonâ€). Adrianne Lenkerâ€™s voice still conveys a natural reticenceâ€”she doesnâ€™t want to believe itâ€™s all as beautiful as it isâ€”but sheâ€™s also too earnest to deny beauty when she sees it.
entries.title: Dragon New Warm Mountain I Believe In You

entries.notes: Black Thought may be best-known as part of The Roots, performing night after late night for Jimmy Fallonâ€™s TV audience, yet the Philadelphia native concurrently boasts a staggering reputation as a stand-alone rapper. Though heâ€™s earned GOAT nods from listeners for earth-shaking features alongside Big Pun, Eminem and Rapsody, his solo catalogue long remained relatively modest in size. Meanwhile, Danger Mouse had a short yet monumental run in the 2000s that made him one of that decadeâ€™s most beloved and respected producers. His discography from that period contains no shortage of microphone dynamos, most notably MF DOOM (as DANGERDOOM) and Goodie Mobâ€™s CeeLo Green (as Gnarls Barkley). Uniting these low-key hip-hop powerhouses is the stuff of hip-hop dreams, the kind of fantasy-league-style draft youâ€™d encounter on rap message boards. Yet Cheat Codes is realâ€”perhaps realer than real. Danger Mouseâ€™s penchant for quirkily cinematic, subtly soulful soundscapes remains from the old days, but the growth from his 2010s work with the likes of composer Daniele Luppi gives â€œAquamarineâ€ and â€œSometimesâ€ undeniable big-screen energy. Black Thought luxuriates over these luxurious beats, his lyrical lexicon put to excellent use over the feverish funk of â€œNo Gold Teethâ€ and the rollicking blues of â€œClose to Famousâ€. As if their team-up wasnâ€™t enough, an intergenerational cabal of rapper guests bless the proceedings. From living legend Raekwon to A$AP Rocky to Conway the Machine, New York artists play a pivotal role here. A lost DOOM verse, apparently from The Mouse and the Mask sessions, makes its way onto the sauntering and sunny â€œBelizeâ€, another gift for the fans.
entries.title: Cheat Codes
Is It Going To Get Any Deeper Than This?

entries.notes: After recording The Car, there was, for â€œquite a long time, a real edit in process,â€ Arctic Monkeys leader Alex Turner tells Apple Music. Indeed, his UK rock outfitâ€™s daring seventh LP sounds nothing if not composedâ€”a set of subtle and stupendously well-mannered mid-century pop that feels light years away from the youthful turbulence of their historic 2006 debut, Whatever People Say I Am, Thatâ€™s What Iâ€™m Not. If, back then, they were writing songs with the intention of uncorking them onstage, theyâ€™re now fully in the business of craftâ€”editing, shaping, teasing out the sort of sumptuous detail that reveals itself over repeated listens. â€œItâ€™s obviously 10 songs, but, even more than we have done before, it just feels like itâ€™s a whole,â€ he says. â€œItâ€™s its own.â€ The aim was to pay more attention to dynamics, to economy and space. â€œEverything,â€ Turner says, â€œhas its chance to come in and out of focus,â€ whether itâ€™s a brushed snare or a feline guitar line, a feathered vocal melody or devastating turn of phrase. Where an earlier Monkeys song may have detonated outward, a blast of guitars and drums and syllables, these are quiet, controlled, middle-aged explosions: â€œIt doesn't feel as if there's too many times on this record where everything's all going on at once.â€ On album opener â€œThereâ€™d Better Be a Mirrorballâ€, Turner vaults from a bed of enigmatic, opening-credit-like keys and strings (all arranged with long-time collaborator James Ford and composer Bridget Samuels) into scenes of a prolonged farewell. So much of its painâ€”its romance, its dramatic tensionâ€”is in whatâ€™s not said. â€œThe feel of that minute-or-so introduction was what feels like the foundation of the whole thing,â€ he says. â€œAnd it really was about finding what could hang out with that or what could be built around the feel of that. The moment when I found a way to bridge it into something that is a pop song by the end was exciting, because I felt like we had somewhere to go.â€ For years, Turner has maintained a steady diet of side work, experimenting with orchestral, Morricone-like epics in The Last Shadow Puppets as well as lamplit bedroom folk on 2011â€™s Submarine EP, written for the film of the same name. But listen closely to The Car (and 2018â€™s Tranquility Base Hotel & Casino before it) and youâ€™ll hear the walls between the band and his interests outside it begin to dissolveâ€”the string arrangements throughout (but especially on â€œThe Carâ€), the gently fingerpicked guitars (â€œMr Schwartzâ€), the use of negative space (the slightly Reznor-y â€œSculptures of Anything Goesâ€). â€œI think I was naive,â€ he says. â€œI think the first time I stepped out to do anything else was the first Puppets record, and at that moment, I remember thinking, â€˜Oh, this is totally in its own place and it's going to have nothing to do with the Monkeys and what that was going to turn into.â€™ And I realise now that I don't know if that's really possible, for me anyway. It feels as if everything you do has an effect on the next thing.â€
entries.title: The Car

entries.notes: Coming off the back of 2019â€™s excellent The Book of Traps and Lessons and the critically acclaimed play Paradise at Londonâ€™s National Theatre in 2021, MC and poet Kae Tempestâ€™s fourth album is their most ambitious, personal and open to date. Made with longtime collaborator and producer Dan Carey, the record moves in a series of bold musical and thematic suites that take in collaborators including Lianne La Havas, South London rapper Confucius MC, Fontaines D.C.â€™s Grian Chatten and BROCKHAMPTONâ€™s Kevin Abstract. The Line Is a Curve is about letting go of the anxieties and fears that hold you back and embracing lifeâ€™s cyclical nature. â€œThis record is meant to symbolise a journey through different pressures,â€ says Tempest, â€œwhether itâ€™s the pressures of a relationship, or trying to survive and build the name for yourself or just trying to get through the day. It will mean something different to everybody, but thatâ€™s the beauty of language.â€ Here, they talk us through The Line Is a Curve, track by track. â€œPriority Boredomâ€ â€œItâ€™s an evocation of a feeling that I imagine we all are familiar with, which is the relentless pressure of existence and the forces competing for our attention. Itâ€™s meant to plunge you directly into the experience of the dull numbness and the claustrophobia of life in the present moment. What itâ€™s saying is this race to death that we call progress or happiness or the pursuit of normal activity, happy families or whatever the value system is that weâ€™ve swallowed up and are trying to recreate is actually extremely taxing for the individual and also for the community. Itâ€™s quite sarcastic in its own way. Itâ€™s meant to be knowing rather than an actual description of our lives.â€ â€œI Saw Lightâ€ (feat. Grian Chatten) â€œIâ€™ve wanted to work with Grian ever since I met him. My desire was to have Grianâ€™s voice contributing a poem because I feel him in that way, as a poet. When you put somebody elseâ€™s words alongside yours, you create this friction between the verses that creates new meaning. It gives the words a new energy, a new dimension. Grian putting his words down transformed and affected the verse that I had already written. Itâ€™s beautiful.â€ â€œNothing to Proveâ€ â€œItâ€™s a statement song. Itâ€™s powerful in its musicality. I love the beat. The first and the second verses are absolutely phonetically matched. There is communication going on between the transformations in the lyric as it begins in one way, and then as it transforms in the other way, so you have this kind of call-and-response between two verses. For me as a writer, a rhymer and a lyricist, to be doing that on a record is an embodiment of having nothing to prove. Itâ€™s like, â€˜Here, look what this song is doing.â€™ Itâ€™s like this chorus, musicality, lyricism, flow that are all saying the same thing. Thereâ€™s nothing to proveâ€”itâ€™s all to play for.â€ â€œNo Prizesâ€ (feat. Lianne La Havas) â€œItâ€™s close-up portraits of three characters and Lianneâ€™s voice is the overarching theme or the undercurrent of what is common with all of them. The same thing that is occurring for them all, and all of us, in this world where weâ€™ve set the albumâ€”where the dominant mythology says, â€˜Iâ€™ve just got to keep climbing, and I donâ€™t know why.â€™ Iâ€™ve known Lianne for a long time, and I love her voice passionately. Thereâ€™s mutual respect and friendship there, and it just felt like the right time to try and bring some of that energy through into the record.â€ â€œSalt Coastâ€ â€œItâ€™s a love letter to Britain. Within my imagination, this island was embodied as this kid, this young girl. I suppose I was thinking about my childhood. I was thinking about the people I knew and loved as a kid, the people that made the most profound impact on me, and also the particular Britishness of that time. Itâ€™s acknowledging all of the complexities of loving home. Itâ€™s a complex place to love but, for me, itâ€™s no less beautiful than any other. Itâ€™s home. Iâ€™ve gone deeply into why this soil feels the way it feels to me. I really want it to be the unofficial England World Cup anthem. Imagine that on the terraces.â€ â€œDonâ€™t You Everâ€ â€œKwake Bass plays the drums. Weâ€™ve been friends since childhood. Heâ€™s one of the greatest drummers of our generation, I think. The guitar part is by this guy Luke [Eastop]. We were all in a band together when we were about 19 years old, and the music on this, not the lyrics, was something that we used to play together when we were doing all of these hippie festivals. I just thought to myself on this record, â€˜I want to get everybody together again. I want us to play together, and I want to do a kind of grown-up version of that song.â€™ Because itâ€™s a fucking brilliant song.â€ â€œThese Are the Daysâ€ â€œThis is one that me and Dan wrote together in this weird studio lockdown situation. Itâ€™s this big, epic production, but we were writing it on a very minimised kit. We knew we wanted to do it live, so when the band came in to do â€˜Donâ€™t You Everâ€™, we also did â€˜These Are the Daysâ€™ with all of the horns and the same crew playing the bass and the drums. That had a huge impact on it. Itâ€™s us saying, â€˜Yeah, these are the days, this is the time, letâ€™s fucking play this song!â€™â€ â€œSmokingâ€ (feat. Confucius MC) â€œWhen I started rappingâ€”and Iâ€™m talking about 15, 16 years oldâ€”Confucius was instrumental in guiding me. His lyricism was profound for me. We were in a crew together, and he was an important person in my creative life. If it wasnâ€™t for those people, I would not be here, so I wanted to bring my community into my creativity. It sounds the way it does because I recorded it backstage at a festival and sent it to Dan as a voice note, which I often do.â€ â€œWater in the Rainâ€ (feat. Assia) â€œItâ€™s kind of setting myself free from some stuff that Iâ€™ve been suffering from with poor mental health. I think sometimes singing about it, just describing it and going into the experience of it, can take some of the fear out of what you experience when youâ€™re experiencing it in isolation. Itâ€™s a profound moment on the album for me.â€ â€œMoveâ€ â€œI think of the album as a series of suites. You start with â€˜Smokingâ€™ and all of the themes that come up in that and then you move into â€˜Water in the Rainâ€™, which is this unleashing of deep emotion, which then opens up the space for us to get to â€˜Moveâ€™. â€˜Moveâ€™ is a response to whatâ€™s come before. Iâ€™ve connected with the tenderness, so now I can really dig deep and find my strength. This is the time to get up off the floor and stand up for yourself. The idea of â€˜Moveâ€™ is that you earn that strength by being that vulnerable. Itâ€™s a fight song. I might be losing right now, but Iâ€™m not going to give up.â€ â€œMore Pressureâ€ (feat. Kevin Abstract) â€œThe Line Is a Curve builds its momentum. Itâ€™s like a wave: You build up all of this galvanising spirit of fight, and thatâ€™s what enables you to reframe the narrative of the pressures that youâ€™re under. Now you can say, â€˜Right, I get it. Iâ€™m under all this pressure, but Iâ€™m going to use all this pressure, and Iâ€™m going to use this energy to make change and cultivate greater acceptance.â€™ Itâ€™s all part of this swell that begins at the start of the record. Rick Rubin suggested that I give Kevin a shout. Itâ€™s not quite as close to home as the other collaborations, which are very much based in South London, but it opens the record up a bit more and, hopefully, allows more people in.â€ â€œGraceâ€ â€œItâ€™s like a prayer. Itâ€™s this repeated refrain that comes back to me. When Iâ€™m in need, I go back to those words: â€˜Let me be loved. Let me be loving.â€™ I would say those words to myself before going out onstage to do a performance of The Book of Traps and Lessons. Itâ€™s become something to keep me grounded. It feels really fitting that this song came out of the sessions making this album, but then itâ€™s something that had its place in other works that Iâ€™ve done. Dan is playing the synth line to â€˜Priority Boredomâ€™ on the guitar, so it leads you back around in a circle. Itâ€™s such a gentle, tender way of finishing the album.â€

entries.notes: Letâ€˜s start with that speech. In September 2022, as Taylor Swift accepted Songwriter-Artist of the Decade honours at the Nashville Songwriter Awards, the headline was that Swift had unveiled an admittedly â€œdorkyâ€ system sheâ€™d developed for organising her own songs. Quill Pen, Fountain Pen, Glitter Gel Pen: three categories of lyrics, three imagined tools with which she wrote them, one pretty ingenious way to invite obsessive fans to lovingly obsess all the more. And yet, perhaps the real takeaway was the manner in which she spoke about her craft that night, some 20 years after writing her first song at the age of 12. â€œI love doing this thing we are fortunate enough to call a job,â€ she said to a room of her peers. â€œWriting songs is my lifeâ€™s work and my hobby and my never-ending thrill. A song can defy logic or time. A good song transports you to your truest feelings and translates those feelings for you. A good song stays with you even when people or feelings donâ€™t.â€ On Midnights, her tenth LP and fourth in as many yearsâ€”if you donâ€™t count the two sheâ€™s just re-recorded and buttressed with dozens of additional tracksâ€”Swift sounds like sheâ€™s really enjoying her work, playing with language like kids do with gum, thrilling to the texture of every turn of phrase, the charge in every melody and satisfying rhyme. Alongside long-time collaborator Jack Antonoff, sheâ€™s set out here to tell â€œthe stories of 13 sleepless nights scattered throughout [her] lifeâ€, as she phrased it in a message to Apple Music subscribers. Itâ€™s a concept that naturally calls for a nocturnal palette: slower tempos, hushed atmosphere, negative space like night sky. The sound is fully modern (synths youâ€™d want to eat or sleep in, low end that sits comfortably on your chest), while the aesthetic (soft focus, wood panelling, tracklist on the cover) is decidedly mid-century, much like the Mad Men-inspired title of its brooding opener, â€œLavender Hazeâ€â€”a song about finding refuge in the glow of intimacy. â€œTalk your talk and go viral,â€ she sings, in reference to the maelstrom of outside interest in her six-year relationship with actor Joe Alwyn. â€œI just want this love spiral.â€ (A big shout to Antonoff for those spongy backup vocals, btw.) In large part, Midnights is a record of interiors, Swift letting us glimpse the chaos inside her head (â€œAnti-Heroâ€, wall-to-wall zingers) and the stillness of her relationship (â€œSweet Nothingâ€, co-written by Alwyn under his William Bowery pseudonym). For â€œSnow on the Beachâ€, she teams up with Lana Del Reyâ€”an artist whose instinct for mood and theatrical framing seems to have influenced Swiftâ€™s recent catalogueâ€”recalling the magic of an impossible night over a backdrop of pizzicato violin, sleigh bells and dreamy Mellotron, like the earliest hours of Christmas morning. â€œIâ€™ve never seen someone lit from within,â€ Swift sings. â€œBlurring out my periphery.â€ But then thereâ€™s â€œBejeweledâ€, a late, 1989-like highlight on which she announces to an unappreciative partner, a few seconds in: â€œAnd by the way, Iâ€™m going out tonight.â€ And then out Swift goes, striding through the centre of the song like she would the room: â€œI can still make the whole place shimmer,â€ she sings, relishing that last word. â€œAnd when I meet the band, they ask, â€˜Do you have a man?â€™/I could still say, â€˜I donâ€™t remember.â€™â€ There are traces of melancholy layered in (see: â€œsapphire tears on my faceâ€), but the song feels like a triumph, the sort of unabashed, extroverted fun that would have probably seemed out of place in the lockdown indie of 2020â€™s folklore and evermore. But here, side by side with songs and scenes of such writerly indulgence, itâ€™s right at homeâ€”more proof that the terms â€œsinger-songwriterâ€ and â€œuniversal pop starâ€ arenâ€™t mutually exclusive ideas. â€œWhatâ€™s a girl gonna do?â€ Swift asks at its climax. â€œA diamondâ€™s gotta shine.â€
entries.title: Midnights

entries.notes: Although Dry Cleaning began work on their second album before the London quartet had even released their 2021 debut, New Long Leg, there was little creative overlap between the two. â€œI definitely think of it as a different chapter,â€ drummer Nick Buxton tells Apple Music. â€œI think one of the nicest things was just knowing what we were in for a bit more,â€ adds singer Florence Shaw. â€œIt was less about, â€˜What are we doing?â€™ and more thinking about what we were playing.â€ Recorded in the same studio (Walesâ€™ famous Rockfield Studios) with the same producer (PJ Harvey collaborator John Parish) as New Long Leg, Stumpwork sees Shaw, Buxton, bassist Lewis Maynard and guitarist Tom Dowse hone the wiry post-punk and rhythmical bursts of their debut. The jangly guitar lines are melodically sharper and the grooves more locked in as Shawâ€™s observational, spoken-word vocals pull at the threads of lifeâ€™s big topics, even when sheâ€™s singing about a missing tortoise. â€œWhen we finished New Long Leg, I always felt a bit like, â€˜Ah, Iâ€™d like another chance at that.â€™ With this one, it definitely felt like, â€˜Really happy with that,â€™â€ says Buxton. The quartet take us on a tour of Stumpwork, track by track. â€œAnna Calls From the Arcticâ€ Nick Buxton: â€œIt was a very late decision to start the album with this. I think itâ€™s quite unusual because itâ€™s very different from a lot of the other songs on the album.â€ Florence Shaw: â€œI quite liked that the album opened with a question: â€˜Should I propose friendship?â€™ In the outro, we were thinking about the John Barry song â€˜Capsule in Spaceâ€™, from You Only Live Twice. Thereâ€™s quite a bit of that in the outro. At least, it was on the mood board.â€ â€œKwenchy Kupsâ€ NB: â€œItâ€™s named after those little plastic pots you get when youâ€™re a kidâ€”pots full of some luminous liquid, and you pierce the film on the lid with a straw.â€ FS: â€œWe were at a studio in Easton in Bristol, and I wrote a lot of the lyrics on walks around the area. Itâ€™s a really nice little area, and thereâ€™s lots of interesting shops. We wanted to write a few more joyful songs, at least in tone, and the song is so cheerful-sounding. So, some of the lyrics came out of that, too, wanting to write something that was optimistic, the idea of watching animals or insects being just a simple, joyful thing to do.â€ â€œGary Ashbyâ€ NB: â€œThis is about a real tortoise.â€ FS: â€œOn a walk in lockdown, I saw a â€˜lostâ€™ poster for â€˜Gary Ashbyâ€™. The rest of the story came out of imagining the circumstances of him disappearing and the idea that itâ€™s obviously a family tortoise because heâ€™s got this surname. Itâ€™s thinking about family and things getting lost in chaos, when things are a bit chaotic in the home and pets escape. We donâ€™t know what happened to him. We donâ€™t know if heâ€™s alive or dead, which is a little bit disturbing, but hopefully weâ€™ll find out one day.â€ â€œDriverâ€™s Storyâ€ NB: â€œWe were rehearsing at a little studio in the basement at our record label [4AD]. It was just me, Tom and Lewis, and we werenâ€™t there very long, but quite a few ideas for songs came out of that. The main bit of â€˜Driverâ€™s Storyâ€™ was one. It felt different to anything weâ€™d done on New Long Leg. Itâ€™s just got such a nice, oozy feel to it. FS: â€œThereâ€™s a bit in the song about a jelly shoe and the idea of it being buried in your guts. A photographer called Maisie Cousins does photos of lots of bodily stuff and liquids, but with flowers and beautiful things as well. I was looking at a lot of those at the time. The jelly-shoe thing is about thatâ€”something pretty, plastic-y, mixed with guts.â€ Tom Dowse: â€œItâ€™s got my dog barking on the end of it as well. Heâ€™s called Buckley. He is credited on the record.â€ â€œHot Penny Dayâ€ TD: â€œIâ€™d been listening to a lot of Rolling Stones, so this is an attempt at that. We were jamming it through, and it started to take on a bit more of a stoner-rock vibe. â€˜Driverâ€™s Storyâ€™ was also meant to be a bit more stoner-rock until John Parish got his hands in it and took the drugs out of it.â€ Lewis Maynard: â€œI found a bass wah pedal in my sisterâ€™s garage. I just plugged it in and started playing, and I was like, â€˜This is funâ€™. Iâ€™ve unfortunately not stopped playing bass wah.â€ NB: â€œIt conjures up quite a lot of imagery. I was listening to some of Jonny Greenwoodâ€™s music for the film Inherent Vice, and itâ€™s got a washed-out, desert-y feel. This sounds like Dry Cleaning in an alternate, parallel universe somewhere.â€ â€œStumpworkâ€ FS: â€œQuite a lot of the lyrics were gleaned from this archive of newspaper clippings that I went to in Woolwich Arsenal. Itâ€™s millions and millions of newspaper clippings on different subjects. Thereâ€™s a bit [in â€˜Stumpworkâ€™] about toads crossing roads from this little article I found about a special tunnel being built, so that toads could traverse the street without being run over.â€ NB: â€œWhen we were trying to figure out a name for the record, it felt like the best option. We loved it, and it was really succinct. We liked that the word â€˜workâ€™ was in the title.â€ â€œNo Decent Shoes for Rainâ€ TD: â€œThis was two of those jams from the basement of 4AD. We were quite unsure about this song. We took it to show John at the pre-production rehearsals, and he really liked it, and he didnâ€™t really have anything to say about it, which is quite unusual. A lot of people ask, â€˜Why did you record with John again?â€™ And itâ€™s things like thatâ€”because he notices things that are good about you that you donâ€™t notice. I was really self-conscious that the end section sounded too trad, classic rock. It sounded like the safest bit of guitar Iâ€™ve ever written. But once he said he was into it, I started to look at it from a different way, and it grew from that.â€ â€œDonâ€™t Press Meâ€ FS: â€œThis has some recorder on it, which I had to play at half-time because it was really fast. I was like, â€˜Oh, this would be nice if it had this little bit of a recorder on.â€™ I tried to play it, and I was completely incapable. Iâ€™d thought, â€˜Oh, Iâ€™ll be able to do this. Kids play the recorder all the time. Itâ€™s easy.â€™ Even at half-time, I had to have loads of goes at it. So, itâ€™s me playing the recorder, sped up, because I have no skills.â€ â€œConservative Hellâ€ NB: â€œI think this songâ€™s really important because through the course of the record thereâ€™s two different types of song. Thereâ€™s these upbeat, jangle, poppy ones and then thereâ€™s slightly slower, more groovy ones. This song has two very distinct elements that weâ€™re really happy with. Itâ€™s nice as well to be so overtly political, which is not usually our scene.â€ FS: â€œThe reason it ended up being such an on-the-nose phrase is I was thinking it would be really nice to write a song that was something like â€˜Conservative Hellâ€™. And then, after a while, I was like, â€˜Thatâ€™s pretty goodâ€™. I think it almost sounds like a silly headline, but accurate too.â€ â€œLiberty Logâ€ FS: â€œThe title comes from thinking about spring rolls. Theyâ€™re like little logs, arenâ€™t they? Then, later, I was thinking about a stupid monument, something that would be a really dumb statue in a townâ€”just a big log and itâ€™s called the Liberty Log.â€ LM: â€œThis is one of the ones we took to the studio expecting it to be a shit-ton of editing, structuring and that John would really fuck with it. We jammed it, and it just stayed the same. This one was first-take vibes, playing it in that way, expecting it to be changed.â€ â€œIcebergsâ€ NB: â€œI think this is quite a bleak moment for us. Definitely the most icy-sounding track on the album. It feels like a really good end to the record to suddenly have this explosion of brass come in, and then it just peters out very slowly. I like that the album ends on quite an icy tone, even though that doesnâ€™t necessarily represent us in how we feel about things. Itâ€™s a slightly more poignant ending rather than a nice, lovely outro.â€

entries.notes: The contradiction of Bill Callahanâ€™s 2010s output is how an artist seemingly so stoic and withdrawn could be so completely in love with everyday life. His performances get more nuanced and his metaphorical power richer every album, whether itâ€™s the image of his infant daughter suspended angelically above the ground because everyone wants to carry her around (â€œFirst Birdâ€), or the way a horse inside a house reminds him of the way we have to â€bow our heads to get in and out of what weâ€™re living inâ€â€”a mix of American surrealism and Buddhist humility he can safely call his own. And for a singer who once said that the only time he felt part of the world is when he was alone in his room (Smogâ€™s â€œEx-Conâ€), now he canâ€™t wait to get out with the stroller for another trip around the neighbourhood (â€œNatural Informationâ€) with a horn section and backup singers in tow. Peace, love and funâ€”and evidently hard-won.
