entries.notes: If The Smile ever seemed like a surprisingly upbeat name for a band containing two members of Radiohead (Thom Yorke and Jonny Greenwood, joined by Sons of Kemet drummer Tom Skinner), the trio used their debut gig to offer some clarification. Performing as part of Glastonbury Festivalâ€™s Live at Worthy Farm livestream in May 2021, Yorke announced, â€œWe are called The Smile: not The Smile as in â€˜Aaah!â€™â€”more the smile of the guy who lies to you every day.â€ To grasp the mood of their debut album, itâ€™s instructive to go even deeper into a name that borrows the title of a 1970 Ted Hughes poem. In Hughesâ€™ impressionist verse, some elemental forceâ€”compassion, humanity, love maybeâ€”rises up to resist the deception and chicanery behind such disarming grins. And as much as the 13 songs on A Light for Attracting Attention sense crisis and dystopia looming, they also crackle with hope and insurrection. The pulsing electronics of opener â€œThe Sameâ€ suggest the racing hearts and throbbing temples of our age of acute anxiety, and Yorkeâ€™s words feel like a call for unity and mobilisation: â€œWe donâ€™t need to fight/Look towards the light/Grab it in with both hands/What you know is right.â€ Perennially contemplating the dynamics of power and thought, he surveys a world where â€œdevastation has comeâ€ (â€œSpeech Bubblesâ€) under the rule of â€œelected billionairesâ€ (â€œThe Oppositeâ€), but itâ€™s one where protest, however extreme, can still birth change (â€œThe Smokeâ€). Amid scathing guitars and outbursts of free jazz, his invective zooms in on abuses of power (â€œYou Will Never Work in Television Againâ€) before shaming inertia and blame-shifters on the scurrying beats and descending melodies of â€œA Hairdryerâ€. These arenâ€™t exactly new themes for Yorke and itâ€™s not a record that sits at an extreme outpost of Radioheadâ€™s extended universe. Emboldened by Skinnerâ€™s fluid, intrepid rhythms, A Light for Attracting Attention draws frequently on various periods of Yorke and Greenwoodâ€™s past work. The emotional eloquence of Greenwoodâ€™s soundtrack projects resurfaces on â€œSpeech Bubblesâ€ and â€œPana-Visionâ€, while Yorkeâ€™s fascination with digital reveries continues to be explored on â€œOpen the Floodgatesâ€ and â€œThe Sameâ€. Elegantly cloaked in strings, â€œFree in the Knowledgeâ€ is a beautiful acoustic-guitar ballad in the lineage of Radioheadâ€™s â€œFake Plastic Treesâ€ and the original live version of â€œTrue Love Waitsâ€. Of course, lesser-trodden ground is visited, too: most intriguingly, math-rock (â€œThin Thingâ€) and folk songs fit for a â€™70s sci-fi drama (â€œWaving a White Flagâ€). The album closes with â€œSkrting on the Surfaceâ€, a song first aired at a 2009 show Yorke played with Atoms for Peace. With Greenwoodâ€™s guitar arpeggios and Yorkeâ€™s aching falsetto, it calls back even further to The Bendsâ€™ finale, â€œStreet Spirit (Fade Out)â€. However, its message about the fragility of existenceâ€”â€œWhen we realise we have only to die, then weâ€™re out of here/Weâ€™re just skirting on the surfaceâ€â€”remains sharply resonant.
entries.title: A Light for Attracting Attention
For the Sake of Bethel Woods

entries.notes: â€œWhen itâ€™s just us two, itâ€™s really easy to make music,â€ JD BECK tells Apple Music. â€œWe play around, and the tracks come pouring out.â€ Instrumental prodigies DOMi & JD BECK certainly have a telepathic connection when it comes to creativity. First meeting in 2018 at the NAMM trade show in Southern California, where the two teenagers were individually invited to perform as part of a larger ensemble, Texas-born drummer BECK formed an instant connection with French keyboardist and Berklee student DOMi Louna (born Domitille Degalle). The pair soon began writing fast-paced, note-packed jams to upload to their Instagram, and by 2020, they had caught the attention of multi-instrumentalist Anderson .Paak. Swiftly signing them to his APESHIT label, he challenged the duo to release an updated body of work as a debut. â€œHe basically told us we could do better than the albumâ€™s worth of material we already had,â€ BECK says. â€œSo, we put together a wish list of collaborators and got to work.â€ The result is NOT TiGHT, a 15-track jazz-fusion odyssey of head-nodding hip-hop, psychedelic vocoder experiments and rhythmic freakouts. â€œWe just wanted to surprise ourselves with this album,â€ DOMi says. â€œThis music is an expression of ourselves at our core.â€ Here, DOMi & JD BECK offer their thoughts on each of the albumâ€™s tracks. â€œLOUNAâ€™S iNTROâ€ DOMi Louna: â€œWe thought the album needed book-ending to help bring the listener in and then back out of the tracks. We already had the outro, â€œTHANK Uâ€, so we wrote these chords and added synth patches before sending it to violin, double bass, viola, cello and harp players all around the world. It was like a mini online orchestra opening the album for us.â€ â€œWHATUPâ€ DL: â€œWeâ€™ve had these chords since 2018, as they were part of a track that was going to be the intro for our original album. We kept playing around with it when we were locked down together during the pandemic, and after deconstructing it a few times, we decided to make a new tune. We added a drum solo section, and so now the record has two intros before we get into â€˜SMiLEâ€™.â€ â€œSMiLEâ€ JD BECK: â€œI sing dumb little melodies a lot, and when I was in the bathroom on my phone one day in 2018, the melody just came to me. I put it together in my head and shouted to DOMi to quickly set it to some chords.â€ â€œBOWLiNGâ€ (feat. Thundercat) JDB: â€œWe met Thundercat around the same time as meeting each other. Whenever we were in LA, we would go and stay with him and take over his house. We always write a lot with him when weâ€™re thereâ€”we must have 50 song ideas together already. Back in 2018, weâ€™d all go bowling a lot, as itâ€™s his favourite thing to do, and so we wrote this song about hanging out in the bowling alley.â€ â€œNOT TiGHTâ€ (feat. Thundercat) JDB: â€œItâ€™s probably the closest representation of our soundâ€”just singing random melodic lines to crazy chord combinations. In 2019, we played it for Thundercat, and he loved it so much that he wanted to be on it. He became the first instrumentalist to collaborate with us, and it was incredible to have him soloing on the track with DOMi.â€ â€œTWO SHRiMPSâ€ (feat. Mac DeMarco) DL: â€œWe wrote the instrumental for this track while we were on tour in 2019. JD had a little drum machine, which he made a loop on, and then I added the keyboard parts and put it in a 9/8 time signature. We met Mac the same day we met Anderson .Paak in 2019, and by 2020, we were spending a lot of time at Macâ€™s house. We played him this instrumental, and he started singing along to it, just listing random sandwich names. The track was originally called â€˜Sandwiches of Americaâ€™. We ended up re-recording new lyrics with him, but thankfully itâ€™s still food-related.â€ â€œU DONâ€™T HAVE TO ROB MEâ€ JDB: â€œIâ€™ve been playing gigs by myself since I was 11, and I got used to the element of danger, being in cities late at night. When DOMi and I started going out in LA, you could feel when there was danger, like one day we were in the parking lot of the bowling alley at 1 am, and this dude asked us for a cigarette, and it really felt like he might pull a knife on us too. It made us think about how we never have cashâ€”only cards that we can cancel easilyâ€”so why even go through that trouble of robbing us?â€ â€œMOONâ€ (feat. Herbie Hancock) JDB: â€œAndy made us write down all our goals for the record, and among them was a list of people weâ€™d love to work with. Herbie was at the top of those names. One of Andyâ€™s managers had a connect with Herbie, and he called us one day to say that Herbie had watched our videos on YouTube and was down to collaborate.â€ DL: â€œWe were shitting our pants, as we knew we now had to come up with the best song weâ€™d ever written. Sunlight is some of our favourite stuff that Herbie has done with the vocoder, and so we wrote â€˜MOONâ€™ to that same vibe. Luckily, we got him on piano, too, and when we recorded it together in 2021, we got to hang out with him, which was amazing.â€ â€œDUKEâ€ JDB: â€œThis track is a George Duke reference. We had been hanging out a lot with Earl Sweatshirt and his producer Black Noise, and they inspired us to put three of our loops together into one track and then record it as a new song. The record is full of crazy songs, and we needed something to chill after Herbieâ€”a track that has a natural feel.â€ â€œTAKE A CHANCEâ€ (feat. Anderson .Paak) DL: â€œWe really wanted a feature from Anderson, as weâ€™re huge fans of his, and so we had to come up with something unique and very pretty for him to sing and play on. JD wrote this hook, and when we played it to Andy, he just started rapping over the verses, and then we all sang on the chorus. The whole track was a bunch of surprises and sections put together, since Andy can fit over pretty much anything.â€ â€œSPACE MOUNTAiNâ€ JDB: â€œWhen we first got to LA, I couldnâ€™t get into any clubs, so the only thing we ended up doing, apart from making music, was going to Disneyland. We went on the ride Space Mountain a lot, and it felt like the perfect title for this crazy tune. The first section is a loop we wrote in 2019, where I recorded the drums through an intense compressor, and then the second half used to be part of the original intro to our first album.â€ â€œPiLOTâ€ (feat. Anderson .Paak, Busta Rhymes & Snoop Dogg) DL: â€œWe made this beat in 2020, before we signed with Anderson. We used to send him clips of what we were making, and the day after we sent him this, he emailed it back with him and Busta on it, which was amazing. Once we signed, we had Snoop Dogg on our dream list of collabs, and we thought he would be perfect for â€˜PiLOTâ€™. He was down for it, so we went to Snoopâ€™s studio for six hours one day and recorded it all super smooth. It was very cool to see him and Andy interact and write to our loop.â€ â€œWHOAâ€ (feat. Kurt Rosenwinkel) JDB: â€œDOMi wrote the first part of this tune when she was 12. It was on a random Sibelius session that she played by accident, and I loved it. I knew we had to do a song with it, and Kurt felt like the perfect fit. We met him through the drummer Louis Cole when we were in New York in 2019. A week after he had the track, he sent it back with him soloing from beginning to end. It was perfect.â€ â€œSNiFFâ€ DL: â€œThe original title for this was â€˜You Can Sniff My Buttâ€™. JD wrote it in 2018, all in one go in front of meâ€”and itâ€™s one of my favourite things heâ€™s ever made. We played it at every show as a closer and people loved its pace, so it felt like a good idea to close the record with it too. It was one of the earliest songs we came up with together.â€ â€œTHANK Uâ€ JDB: â€œThis used to be a crazy loop in a 13 time signature, which was called â€˜Dermatologistâ€™ because DOMi had just learned what that word was. We wrote it in an Airbnb somewhere in 2018 and then, when we came back to it a few years later for this record, we realised it was perfect to send to the mini-orchestra who played on the intro. It rounds out the album really well.â€
entries.title: NOT TiGHT

entries.notes: Unique, strong and sexyâ€”thatâ€™s how BeyoncÃ© wants you to feel while listening to RENAISSANCE. Crafted during the grips of the pandemic, her seventh solo album is a celebration of freedom and a complete immersion into house and dance that serves as the perfect sound bed for themes of liberation, release, self-assuredness and unfiltered confidence across its 16 tracks. RENAISSANCE is playful and energetic in a way that captures that Friday-night, just-got-paid, anything-can-happen feeling, underscored by reiterated appeals to unyoke yourself from the weight of othersâ€™ expectations and revel in the totality of who you are. From the classic four-on-the-floor house moods of the Robin S.- and Big Freedia-sampling lead single â€œBREAK MY SOULâ€ to the Afro-tech of the Grace Jones- and Tems-assisted â€œMOVEâ€ and the funky, rollerskating disco feeling of â€œCUFF ITâ€, this is a massive yet elegantly composed buffet of sound, richly packed with anthemic morsels that pull you in. There are soft moments here, too: â€œI know you canâ€™t help but to be yourself around me,â€ she coos on â€œPLASTIC OFF THE SOFAâ€, the kind of warm, whispers-in-the-ear love song youâ€™d expect to hear at a summer cookoutâ€”complete with an intricate interplay between vocals and guitar that gives BeyoncÃ© a chance to showcase some incredible vocal dexterity. â€œCHURCH GIRLâ€ fuses R&B, gospel and hip-hop to tell a survivorâ€™s story: â€œI'm finally on the other side/I finally found the extra smiles/Swimming through the oceans of tears we cried.â€ An explicit celebration of Blackness, â€œCOZYâ€ is the mantra of a woman who has nothing to prove to anyoneâ€”â€œComfortable in my skin/Cozy with who I am,â€ â€ BeyoncÃ© muses on the chorus. And on â€œPURE/HONEYâ€, BeyoncÃ© immerses herself in ballroom culture, incorporating drag performance chants and a Kevin Aviance sample on the first half that give way to the disco-drenched second half, cementing the song as an immediate dance-floor favourite. Itâ€™s the perfect lead-in to the album closer â€œSUMMER RENAISSANCEâ€, which propels the dreamy escapist disco of Donna Summerâ€™s â€œI Feel Loveâ€ even further into the future.
entries.title: RENAISSANCE

entries.notes:
Traditionally, a band release their debut album and head out for an extended stretch on the road, honing their live chops, twisting their songs into new shapes. But when Black Country, New Road released For the First Time in February 2021, that route was blocked off by the pandemic. Instead, the London-based band set out to tweak and tamper with their experimental post-rock sound for a transformative second album. They might not have been able to travel, but their music could. â€œBy the time the first album came out, those songs had existed for so long that we were very keen to change the way we wrote music,â€ bassist Tyler Hyde tells Apple Music. The material that makes up their second record, Ants From Up There, soon came to life, the group using the labyrinthine â€œBasketball Shoesâ€, which had been around before their debut, as a springboard. â€œWe wanted to explore the themes weâ€™d created on that song,â€ says Hyde. â€œItâ€™s essentially three songs within one, all of which relatively cover the emotions and moods that are on the album. Itâ€™s hopeful and light, but still looks at some of the darker sides that the first album showed.â€
The resultant record sees the band hit hypnotic new peaks. Ants From Up There, recorded before the departure of singer Isaac Wood in January 2022, is less reliant on jerky, rhythmic U-turns than their debut (although there is some of that), with expansive, Godspeed You! Black Emperor-ish atmospherics emerging in their place. â€œFundamentally, we relearned an entirely new style of playing with each other,â€ says drummer Charlie Wayne. â€œWe learned a lot about how to express ourselves just for each other rather than for anything else going on externally.â€ Here Hyde, Wayne and saxophonist Lewis Evans take us through it, track by track.
â€œIntroâ€ Lewis Evans: â€œThis uses the theme from â€™Basketball Shoesâ€™, compressed into these little micro cells and repeated over and over again. Itâ€™s just a straight-up, impactful welcome to the album.â€
â€œChaos Space Marineâ€ Tyler Hyde: â€œIn this song, we allowed ourselves to get out all the stupid, funny joke style of playing. It was just our way of saying yes to everything. There are many things across the albumâ€”and in previous songs from the last albumâ€”that are seemingly good ideas, but theyâ€™ve come about through a joke. I think the rest of the album is much more considered than that. Itâ€™s our silly song. Itâ€™s a voyage. Itâ€™s a sea shanty. Itâ€™s a space trip.â€
â€œConcordeâ€ Charlie Wayne: â€œI love how it follows the same chord progression the whole way through, and itâ€™s driven but very soft. Itâ€™s got real moments of delicacy, and itâ€™s a song that we all thought quite a lot about when we were getting it together. When youâ€™re restricted to that one-chord sequence, you want it to feel as though itâ€™s going somewhere and progressing, so the peaks and troughs have to be considered.â€
â€œBread Songâ€ LE: â€œItâ€™s like two different songs in one. Youâ€™ve got this really quite flowing and free track in a melodic and conventional harmonic way, but rhythmically free and flowing accompaniment to Isaacâ€™s vocals. It feels quite orchestral, and the way that we all play together on this recording is so in sync with each other. We were listening to each other so much, so the swells that one person starts making, people start responding to, and everybody is swelling at the same time and getting quieter at the same time. Then it turns into this almost Soweto, kind of township-style pop tune at the end. Itâ€™s a really fun ending to an intense, emotional tune.â€
â€œGood Will Huntingâ€ LE: â€œThis is another slightly silly one, and itâ€™s got a really silly ending which actually never made the cut on the album, but itâ€™s heavily driven by the riff on the guitars. I think at the time we were listening to quite a bit of Kurt Vile, especially rhythmically. I can remember a conversation about when we wanted the drums to come in and to be super straight, super driven. Then for the choruses, rhythmically, to completely flip and not feel like they were big at all. So for both the choruses, the drums are just tiny.â€
â€œHaldernâ€ TH: â€œWe were playing at Haldern Pop Festival in north Germany during lockdown. Weâ€™d just been allowed to fly for work purposes, and we were doing this session. We did two performances there, and the second one was a livestream, and we werenâ€™t allowed to play songs that werenâ€™t released. At the time, that left us with not very much that we werenâ€™t already bored with, so we decided to do some improv. It was a very lucky day where we were all very in sync with one another. So â€˜Haldernâ€™ was totally from improv, which is not how we write ever.â€
â€œMarkâ€™s Themeâ€ LE: â€œThis is a tune written kind of for my uncle who passed away from COVID in 2021. I wrote it on my tenor saxophone as soon as I found out. I just started playing and wrote that. Itâ€™s a reflection on him and my feelings towards him passing away and everything being really bleak. He was a massive fan and supporter of the band, so it felt right to put that on the album and to have his name remembered with our music.â€
â€œThe Place Where He Inserted the Bladeâ€ CW: â€œFor me, this is about as far away as we went from the first album. Aesthetically, where the first album has moments of real dissonance and apathy, â€˜The Place Where He Inserted the Bladeâ€™ is very warm and rich and quite uplifting. I think it strikes right to the heart of what the album is for me, which is fundamentally being in the room, making music with my friends.â€
â€œSnow Globesâ€ LE: â€œThis is another tune where we really thought about what we wanted from it before we wrote it. We had examples of things we liked, and one of them was Frank Oceanâ€™s â€˜White Ferrariâ€™. We liked the idea of it almost being like two different bands [playing] at the same time. So youâ€™ve got this quite simple but quite heart-wrenching, fugal-sounding arrangement of all the instruments with a drum solo that is just crazy and doesnâ€™t really relate too much to what is going on in the other instruments. We react to the drum solo, but he doesnâ€™t react to us. Itâ€™s that kind of idea.â€
â€œBasketball Shoesâ€ TH: â€œItâ€™s essentially a medley of the whole album. Itâ€™s got literal musical motifs that are repeated on different songs in the album. It touches on all the themes that weâ€™ve been exploring, and itâ€™s the most climactic song on the album. It wouldnâ€™t really make sense to not finish with it, itâ€™s so exhausting. Itâ€™s such a journey. I think you just wouldnâ€™t be able to pay much attention to anything that followed it because youâ€™d be so wiped out after listening to it.â€
entries.title: Ants From Up There

entries.notes: Twenty years into their time together as a bandâ€”and approaching the 10-year milestone of being a hugely successful oneâ€”The 1975 felt in better shape than ever. Self-reflection, sobriety, even fatherhood have influenced the way the four-piece, assisted by producer Jack Antonoff, approached the creation of their fifth studio album, resulting in 11 songs that distil the essence of The 1975 without ever feeling like theyâ€™re treading old ground. â€œThe working title, up until I chickened out, was At Their Very Best,â€ singer/guitarist Matty Healy tells Apple Music. â€œBut I knew we were coming out in sunglasses and suits, and it could look like a bit of a joke. Iâ€™m not joking.â€ It wouldnâ€™t have been an unfair assumption. Healy has carved out a reputation for building to a punchlineâ€”in his lyrics, in conversation, on social media. But he has (mostly) put that defensive reflex aside for this album, dialling back the sardonic interrogations of society which dominated previous records in favour of more soul-baring tracks. â€œMy work has been defined by postmodernism, nihilism, individualism, addiction, need, all that kind of stuff,â€ says Healy. â€œAs you get a bit older, life starts presenting you with different ideas, such as responsibility? Family? Growing up in general? But theyâ€™re less sexy, less transgressive ideas. It would be easy to do another record where Iâ€™m being clever and funny. Whatâ€™s hard to do is just be real and super open.â€ Being Funny in a Foreign Language is indisputable evidence that those 20 years together and the experience gained has paid off. â€œThis is the first time that weâ€™ve been really good artists and really good producers and grown men at the same time,â€ Healy says. â€œIt was the right time for this album to not just reaffirm, but almost celebrate who we are. It was a self-analysis and then a reinvention.â€ Here, he guides us through that reinvention, track by track. â€œThe 1975â€ â€œOn the first three albums, â€˜The 1975â€™ was a rework of the same piece of music. It came from video games, like how you would turn on a Sega Mega Drive, and it had a check-in, load-up sound. The purpose it serves on this album, apart from being this conceptual thing that weâ€™ve done, is to be like the status update. On our previous albums, the whole record has been about the cultural environment, but here Iâ€™m setting that scene up right at the beginning, and then the rest of the album is about me living in this environment and talking about how it makes these bigger ideas of love and home and growing up and things like that really difficult.â€ â€œHappinessâ€ â€œâ€˜Happinessâ€™ is where we acknowledged that there was a certain lyrical and sonic identity to what The 1975 was. We felt like it wouldnâ€™t be a â€™75 record if we didnâ€™t have a song that owned what we did best. The thing is, we werenâ€™t actually very â€™80s; we just used loads of sounds that grunge and Britpop made unfashionable because they were associated with Phil Collins or whoever, but we were like, â€˜No, that sounds better than that.â€™ Itâ€™s a live record, so thereâ€™s a lot of call-and-response, a lot of repetition, because we were in the room, jamming.â€ â€œLooking for Somebody (To Love)â€ â€œIf Iâ€™m going to talk about guns, itâ€™s probably good for me to talk about the thing that I probably understand or empathise with the most, which is that the only vocabulary or lexicon that we provide for young boys to assert their dominance in any position is one of such violence and destruction. Thereâ€™s a line that says, â€˜Youâ€™ve got to show me how to push/If you donâ€™t want a shove,â€™ which is me saying we have to try and figure this crisis out because there are so many young men that donâ€™t really have guidance, and a toxic masculinity is inevitable if we donâ€™t address the way we communicate with them.â€ â€œPart of the Bandâ€ â€œI really just trusted my instinct. As a narrative, I donâ€™t know what the song is about. It was just this belief that I could talk, and that was OK, and it made sense, and I didnâ€™t have to qualify it that much. I have a friend who is much more articulate than me, and thereâ€™s been so many times that heâ€™s explained my lyrics back to me better than I ever could. So, Iâ€™ve learned I can sit there and spend five hours articulating what I mean, but I donâ€™t think I need to. A movie doesnâ€™t start by explaining whatâ€™s going to happen; it opens on a conversation, and you get whatâ€™s going on straight away. So, thereâ€™s a level of abstraction in this song where Iâ€™m giving the audience the benefit of the doubt.â€ â€œOh Carolineâ€ â€œThe chorus of this song came firstâ€”â€˜Oh Caroline/I wanna get it right this time/â€™Cos youâ€™re always on my mindâ€™â€”and it just felt really, really universal. I was like, â€˜OK, this doesnâ€™t have to be about me. It doesnâ€™t have to be â€œI was in Manchester in my skinny jeans.â€â€™ You donâ€™t need to have lived a story to write one. Caroline is whoever you want it to beâ€”you can change that name in your head. Sometimes we call songs like this â€˜â€œsongâ€ songsâ€™ because they can be covered by other people and still make sense. Well, â€˜â€œgetting cucked,â€ I donâ€™t need itâ€™ would be a weird line for someone, but itâ€™s close enough.â€ â€œIâ€™m in Love With Youâ€ â€œI was trying to make it like a traditional 1975 song. I wanted to debase the sincerity. But [guitarist, Adam] Hann and George [Daniel, drummer] really challenged me on it, so I was like, â€˜OK, fuck it. Iâ€™ll just write a song about being in love.â€™ At the time, I was in a relationship with a Black girl who was so beautiful, and I was in love with, and there were all these things that came upâ€”especially with the political climate over the last two yearsâ€”that you can only really learn from experience and living together. Like, our bathroom was full of specific products for skincare and stuff like that. Things you canâ€™t just get at [UK high-street drugstore] Boots. So, thereâ€™s the line that goes â€˜You show me your Black girl thing/Pretending that I know what it is (I wasnâ€™t listening),â€™ which came from this moment when she was talking about something that I had no cultural understanding of, and all I was thinking was, â€˜Iâ€™m in love with you.â€™ And maybe I should have been focusing on what it was, but in that moment, I didnâ€™t care about anything cultural or political. I just loved her.â€ â€œAll I Need to Hearâ€ â€œThinking objectively as a songwriter, â€˜All I Need to Hearâ€™ is maybe one of my best songs. I was in a big Paul Simon phase, and I was kind of trying to do something similar to what he did on â€˜Still Crazy [After All These Years]â€™. He can be as verbose as me, but that song was really, really tight. Almost lullaby-esque. I wanted to write something that was earnest and sincere and didnâ€™t require me, specifically, to deliver it. I almost hope it will be covered by someone else, and that will become the definitive version.â€ â€œWinteringâ€ â€œThis is very much a vignette, a little story in the middle that paints a picture but doesnâ€™t really tell you much of where Iâ€™m at. Itâ€™s kind of about my family, and itâ€™s kind of a Christmas song, but itâ€™s also that thing of relatable specificity because everyone knows that feeling of getting home for Christmas and the wanting to, but the not wanting to, but the needing to, and having to do all the driving and that whole thing. Other parts of the record have a bit more purpose, even though theyâ€™re slightly more abstract, but â€˜Winteringâ€™ is just this moment of brevity, and I think itâ€™s really nice.â€ â€œHuman Tooâ€ â€œThereâ€™s lines on the record where I talk about being cancelled and acknowledge that it was something that I was dealing with. Thereâ€™s no insane smear campaign. No one is going to the trouble of ruining my life for a hobby like they do with Meghan Markle. But it does sting when it happens, and this is the first time Iâ€™m saying, â€˜It does affect me a bit. I totally get it, Iâ€™m a messy person...but Iâ€™m a good person. Give me a break a bit.â€™ I was worried about this song because I didnâ€™t want to sound self-pitying, but it works because itâ€™s really just about empathy and giving each other the benefit of the doubt as humans. Weâ€™re all peopleâ€”letâ€™s not pretend that weâ€™re not going to make mistakes.â€ â€œAbout Youâ€ â€œWarren Ellis from Nick Cave & The Bad Seeds came in to do the arrangement for this song. It was really simpleâ€”it sounded like â€˜With or Without Youâ€™ essentiallyâ€”and he made it all weird and shoegazey. Even though itâ€™s major key, he gave it this terror, which makes my performance in it a lot less romantic because everything is mushing together, and itâ€™s violent. I think this has a similar vibe to â€˜Inside Your Mindâ€™ from the third album. Iâ€™ve always loved those kinds of [David] Cronenberg, body-horror analogies, the tension between death and sex. I think that the morose can be quite sensual, and thereâ€™s quite a bit of that in my work.â€ â€œWhen We Are Togetherâ€ â€œThe album was finished with. â€˜About Youâ€™ was Track 11 and there was a Track 10 called â€˜This Feelingâ€™. But because of what the song was about, and also sonic reasons, I was like, â€˜That song canâ€™t be on the album.â€™ But we had to deliver it in four days. So, I said if I could get to New York tomorrow, and Jack [Antonoff] was around, with a drum kit and a bass, I had a half-finished acoustic song that would be better for the record. It needed to finish, and at that moment, it didnâ€™tâ€”there was no emotional resolve. So, I went out there, a bit heartbroken post-breakup, and this was written, recorded and mixed in 30 hours, which is the perfect example of what making this album was like. Thereâ€™s always been this â€˜will they/wonâ€™t they?â€™ question with The 1975. Are they going to split up? Will Matty go mental? That sort of thing. Totally created by me. But Iâ€™ve stopped doing that, and I think of it more as instalments of your favourite thing. Or like seasons from a TV show. â€˜When We Are Togetherâ€™ is the end of this season.â€
entries.title: Being Funny In a Foreign Language

entries.notes: Roland Orzabal and Curt Smith have been through a lot together in their 40-plus years as collaborators. Theyâ€™ve toured the world countless times in Tears for Fears, the New Wave group they founded in 1981; bounced back from a breakup in the â€™90s; and released their sixth album, Everybody Loves a Happy Ending, as well as a smattering of singles, in the 2000s. Their 1982 breakout single â€œMad Worldâ€, â€œHead Over Heelsâ€, â€œShoutâ€ and â€œEverybody Wants to Rule the Worldâ€ remain timeless favourites for generations of listeners, and several chart-topping artists, from The Weeknd to Kanye West and Drake, have sampled their hits to elevate their own. With The Tipping Point, their seventh studio album and first LP in 18 years, theyâ€™re immensely satisfied with what theyâ€™ve written togetherâ€”partly because they took their time to write their way back to each other, and largely because they did so on their own terms. â€œWe spent a lot of time doing all these writing sessions over a bunch of years with a lot of what are considered more modern songwriters, and it didn't really work out for us because we felt it was slightly dishonest,â€ Smith tells Apple Music. â€œWe were left with a lot of things that seemed like attempts at making a modern hit single, and I don't think that's what we do. We're really an album band. We made The Hurting before 'Mad World' was released. We made Songs From the Big Chair before 'Everybody' and 'Shout' were released. We sat down, just the two of us, with two acoustic guitars, and tried to forge a path forward. It felt more honest, and the material at the end of it was far better, probably because it was more honest.â€ â€œNo Small Thingâ€, The Tipping Point's first track, is a folk-tinged ballad that builds into a sweeping epic, and it's one Smith points to as an example of what they hoped to achieve when they reconnected and started writing: â€œThis song is definitely a journey, and albums for us should be a journey.â€
entries.title: The Tipping Point

entries.notes: In the context of NilÃ¼fer Yanyaâ€™s second album, the word â€œpainlessâ€ has a few different meanings. â€œI was enjoying the process of making the record, and thinking, â€˜Why do you have to beat yourself up in order to make something?â€™â€ the London singer/guitarist tells Apple Music. â€œObviously, you have to work hard, but often the idea of really struggling is something that people inflict on others, just because it's the idea they sell to them, like, â€˜Oh, you need to go through this.â€™â€ Yanya felt that she hadn't given herself enough time and space to make her 2019 debut, Miss Universeâ€”a record based loosely, and playfully, around the concept of self-help and wellness, and what happens when you get too in your head about things. So, in the thick of the pandemic, she eased into making PAINLESS, writing the songs more collaborativelyâ€”mostly with producer Will Archerâ€”than she had been used to. â€œI kind of felt a bit like, â€˜Am I cheating?â€™ Because you're sharing the work, it feels lighter,â€ she says. "But then because of that, I kind of delved in deeper and it got a bit darker.â€ (The album title actually comes from the â€œshamelessâ€ lyric â€œUntil you fall, it's painless.â€) Those depths can be felt both in Yanya's vocal dynamics and the sense of urgency that underpins much of the album, particularly on opener â€œthe dealerâ€ and â€œstabiliseâ€, the first single. â€œI think the rhythm plays a big part in these songs,â€ Yanya says. â€œYou feel like there needs to be an escape somewhere.â€ Here Yanya talks through PAINLESS, track by track. â€œthe dealerâ€ â€œIt's like when someone's hiding behind their layers, or not being honest, but then also you're not being honest with yourself. My favourite lyric is 'I hope it's just the summertime you grew attached to,' because it's like you're lying to yourself. Youâ€™re not saying, 'Oh, it was this person that made the difference, or it was this person that I miss.' You're just saying, 'I had a great time,' and you're not being honest about why.â€ â€œL/Râ€ â€œ[Producer] Bullion played me this beat, and it had this pitched drum in it. It just made me feel really happy and warm. It had this kind of marching feeling to it, which I really liked. It took us like a year to finish it, but the initial idea came really quickly. I like the almost spoken element to it, because it sounds like you're speaking rather than singing, but then the chorus is very much singingâ€”and it took a while to get that right. It's kind of about so many things. In my notebook at the time, I'd written, 'Do less things'â€”like, less is more. That was my thinking behind the song: trying to enjoy simple things and not overcomplicate things.â€ â€œshamelessâ€ â€œIt's a really intimate song. I felt like it was about someone that's trying to run away from stuff in their life, but they kind of don't have much hope. The vocals are very celestialâ€”not something I really experimented with in the past. At first, I was going to kind of speak the words, but it needed a lighter touch, like something even more delicate.â€ â€œstabiliseâ€ â€œThat was the first one me and Will did together. All the others kind of grew off that song. It's about environments and the way they impact you, and not being able to escape your environment, taking it with you wherever you go. And it kind of becomes your cage or the way you view things. You know when you've been somewhere too long and then it's hard to imagine the world another way? Definitely a very lockdown song.â€ â€œchase meâ€ â€œI really liked the line 'Through corridors your love will chase me,' because it was like the safe feeling you can get when you know you are loved, but you don't necessarily want it. It's almost like an ego song for me. It's very confident.â€ â€œmidnight sunâ€ â€œI was digging into more of an overall feeling and a mood. I feel like it's a song about confidence and finding your own voice in order to speak up, whether that's about your own feelings or bigger issues: â€˜I can't keep my mouth shut this time. I can't keep my head down. I'm not going along with this anymore.â€™â€ â€œtroubleâ€ â€œThat song is so sadâ€”in a beautiful way, if I may say so. It also felt like quite a brave one for me because it's very different. When I was writing, I was like, 'Am I doing a straight-up pop song?' It's not. I think it definitely has that take on it. The vocals needed to be more intimate. Like one voice, and it just all keeps spilling out. It's quite challenging to sing. â€˜Troubleâ€™ is one of those wordsâ€”I think I heard it in a Cat Stevens songâ€”'Trouble, set me free'â€”and I really loved the way it was being referred to almost like a person. In the lyrics here, it's something that's quite persistent and it's not going away. Something's definitely broken that you can't fix.â€ â€œtryâ€ â€œThis one is about getting better, and feeling the need to connect on a deeper level, finding new depths and making new connections, but becoming confused, tired and dejected with the effort it takes.â€ â€œcompanyâ€ â€œIt's about giving up and you're not in a happy place. Originally it started out as, like, you're in a relationship that you are just really not sure about and you're trying to give signs across that you're trying to get rid of someone. But I think the song now is definitely about your inner demons, and they're not really going away.â€ â€œbelong with youâ€ â€œI did this with Jazzi Bobbi, who's in my band. I feel like these are all the songs, in a way. Itâ€™s like, escapeâ€”but you can't escape.â€ â€œthe mysticâ€ â€œIt's about watching other people get on with their lives and feeling like you're being left behind. entries.notes:
â€œYou are now listening to 103.5 Dawn FM. Youâ€™ve been in the dark for way too long. Itâ€™s time to walk into the light and accept your fate with open arms. Scared? Donâ€™t worry. Weâ€™ll be there to hold your hand and guide you through this painless transition. But whatâ€™s the rush? Just relax and enjoy another hour of commercial â€˜free yourselfâ€™ music on 103.5 Dawn FM. Tune in.â€ 
The Weeknd's previous album After Hours was released right as the world was falling into the throes of the pandemic; after scrapping material that he felt was wallowing in the depression he was feeling at the time, Dawn FM arrives as a by-product ofâ€”and answer toâ€”that turmoil. Here, he replaces woeful introspection with a bit of upbeat fantasyâ€”the result of creatively searching for a way out of the claustrophobic reality of the previous two years. With the experience of hosting and curating music for his very own MEMENTO MORI radio show on Apple Music as his guiding light, Dawn FM is crafted in a similar fashion, complete with a DJ to set the tone for the segments within. â€œItâ€™s time to walk into the light and accept your fate with open arms,â€ the host, voiced by Jim Carrey, declares on the opening track. â€œScared? Don't worry.â€ 
Indeed, there is nothing to fear. The Weeknd packs the first half with euphoric bursts that include the Swedish House Mafia-assisted â€œHow Do I Make You Love Me?â€ and â€œSacrificeâ€. On the back half, he moves into the more serene waters of â€œIs There Someone Else?â€ and â€œStarry Eyesâ€. Despite the somewhat morose album cover, which reflects what many feel like as they wade through the seemingly endless purgatory of a life dictated by a virus, heâ€™s aiming for something akin to hope in all of this gloom.
entries.title: Dawn FM

entries.notes: Itâ€™s not easy to dance with oneâ€™s tongue buried deeply in cheek. But Charlotte AdigÃ©ry and Bolis Pupul effortlessly combine lean, punchy electro-pop with an unapologetically sarcastic sense of humour. On the Belgian duoâ€™s debut album, Topical Dancer, the two musicians draw on their multicultural backgrounds to take sly potshots at racism, sexism and self-doubt. On â€œEsperantoâ€, AdigÃ©ry riffs on microaggressions over plunging electric bass, and on â€œBlendaâ€, she marries a crisp, funky groove with a surprisingly vulnerable chorus: â€œGo back to your country where you belong/Siri, can you tell me where I belong?â€ Co-produced by their long-time collaborators Soulwax, the album slices neatly across the overlap between punky disco, indie dance and underground house; â€™80s avant-pop influences (Art of Noise, Talking Heads) brush up against the sing-speaking wit of contemporaries like Marie Davidson and Dry Cleaning. Some of the albumâ€™s most powerful moments transcend language entirely: On â€œHahaâ€, AdigÃ©ryâ€™s laughter is chopped up and dribbled over an EBM-inspired beat, making for a slow-motion floor-filler thatâ€™s as surreal as it is captivating.
entries.title: Topical Dancer

entries.notes: Panda Bearâ€™s music has always felt connected to the innocence and melancholy of â€™60s pop, but Reset is the first time heâ€™s made the connection so explicit. Built on simple loops of often familiar songs (The Driftersâ€™ â€œSave the Last Dance for Meâ€, The Everly Brothersâ€™ â€œLove of My Lifeâ€), the music here is both an homage to a bygone style and a rendering of how that style could play out in a modern contextâ€”in other words, time travel. Together with Sonic Boomâ€”formerly of Spacemen 3 and himself an expert interpreter of â€™60s pop and psychedeliaâ€”he gives you his handclaps (â€œEverydayâ€) and heartaches (â€œDangerâ€) and windswept sha-las (â€œEdge of the Edgeâ€). But they also summon the fatalism that made artists like The Shangri-Las so bewitching (â€œGo Onâ€) and the space-age wonder that characterised producers like Joe Meek and the early electronic musician Raymond Scott (â€œEverythingâ€™s Been Leading to Thisâ€). And like the supposedly basic teenage sounds it came from, Resetâ€™s smile conceals a yearning and complexity that runs deep.

entries.notes: Harry Stylesâ€™ third solo album, Harryâ€™s House, is the product of a chain reaction. Had the pandemic not thrown his world into a tailspin in early 2020, he wouldâ€™ve continued to tour behind Fine Line, his critically adored sophomore album, and played its songs hundreds of times for sold-out crowds around the world. A return to the studio was planned, of course, but when COVID-19 cancelled those plans too, Styles faced an empty calendar for the first time in a decade. The singer opted to use this free time carefully, taking a solo road trip through Italy and visiting with family and friends for rare long, drawn-out stretches. It was an important moment of re-evaluation. â€œYou miss so many birthdays,â€ he told Apple Musicâ€™s Zane Lowe. â€œAnd eventually it's just assumed you're unable to be at stuff. Finally I was like, â€˜I want to balance my life out a bit. Working isnâ€™t who I am, it's something I do. I want to be able to put that down.â€™â€ His upbeat, lightly electronic third LP riffs on the concept of home, viewing it less as a geographical location and more as a state of mindâ€”his mind. â€œImagine itâ€™s a day in my house, a day in my mind,â€ he said. â€œWhat do I go through? Iâ€™m playing fun music. Iâ€™m playing sad music. I have doubts. Iâ€™m feeling stuff.â€ Because of the pandemic, Styles recorded the songs with a small handful of long-time friends and close collaborators who gathered in a single room to drink wine, write and play. That intimacy is reflected in the songs, which are conversational and casually confessional, as if heâ€™s thinking out loud. Blending vintage folk rock with flickers of disco and a generally more relaxed sensibility, they illustrate a turning point in Stylesâ€™ career as he transitions even further towards career singer-songwriter. â€œFor a while it was, how do I play that game of remaining exciting?â€ he says. â€œBut I finally had a moment where I felt like, â€˜Okay, Iâ€™m not the young thing, so I would like to really think about who I want to be as a musician.â€™â€ Read on for the inside story behind a handful of standout selections from Harryâ€™s House. â€œMusic for a Sushi Restaurantâ€ â€œAfter Fine Line, I had an idea of how I thought the next album would open. But there's something about â€˜Sushiâ€™ that felt like, â€˜Nah, that's how I want to start.â€™ It becomes really obvious what the first song should be based on what you play for people when theyâ€™re like, â€˜Oh, can I hear a bit of the music?â€™ It's like, how do you want to set the tone?â€ â€œDaylightâ€ â€œWe were like, â€˜We have to find a way to stay awake and finish this, because if we all go to bed, then this wonâ€™t turn out the way it would if we finished tonight.â€™ So we powered through, finished it and went down to the beach as the sun was coming up and it was like, â€˜Okay. Yeah.â€™ It felt correct that we'd finished it in that place. Life, and songs in particular, are so much about moments. In surfing, for example, sometimes you don't get the wave and sometimes the wave comes and you haven't practised. But every now and again, the wave comes and youâ€™re ready, you've practised enough that you can ride it. Sometimes when the songs write themselves like that, it feels like, â€˜Okay, there's a reason why sometimes I sit out there, falling off the board a bunch. It's for this moment.â€ â€œAs It Wasâ€ â€œâ€˜As It Wasâ€™, to me, is bittersweet. Itâ€™s devastating. It's a death march. Itâ€™s about metamorphosis and a perspective change, which are not necessarily things you have time with. People arenâ€™t like, â€˜Oh, we'll give you a couple more days with this moment and let you say goodbye to your former self,â€™ or whatever. No. Everyone is changing, and by the time you realise whatâ€™s happened, [the moment] is already gone. During the pandemic, I think we all at some point realised that it would never be the same as it was before. It was so obvious that it wouldnâ€™t. You can't go backwardsâ€”we canâ€™t as a society and I canâ€™t in my personal life. But you learn so much in those moments because youâ€™re forced to face things head-on, whether theyâ€™re your least favourite things about the world or your least favourite things about yourself, or all of it.â€ â€œMatildaâ€ â€œI had an experience with someone where, in getting to know them better, they revealed some stuff to me that was very much like, â€˜Oh, that's not normal, like I think you should maybe get some help or something.â€™ This song was inspired by that experience and person, who I kind of disguised as Matilda from the Roald Dahl book. I played it to a couple of friends and all of them cried. So I was like, â€˜Okay, I think this is something to pay attention to.â€™ It's a weird one, because with something like this, it's like, â€˜I want to give you something, I want to support you in some way, but it's not necessarily my place to make it about me because it's not my experience.â€™ Sometimes it's just about listening. I hope that's what I did here. If nothing else, it just says, â€˜I was listening to you.â€™â€ â€œBoyfriendsâ€ â€œâ€˜Boyfriendsâ€™ was written right at the end of Fine Line. I'd finished the album and there was an extra week where I wrote â€˜Adore Youâ€™, â€˜Lights Upâ€™ and â€˜Treat People With Kindnessâ€™. At the end of the session for â€˜Lights Upâ€™, we started writing â€˜Boyfriendsâ€™ and it felt like, â€˜Okay, there's a version of this story where we get this song ready for this album.â€™ But something about it just felt like, no, itâ€™ll have its time, let's not rush it. We did so many versions of it. Vocal. Acoustic. Electric guitar. Harmonies on everything, and then we took them out for chunks and put them back in for chunks. You try not to get ahead of yourself when you write a song, but there was something about this one where I felt like, â€˜Okay, when I'm 50, if I'm playing a show, maybe there's someone who heard me for the first time when they were 15 and this is probably the song they came to see.â€™ Because I'm learning so much by singing it. Itâ€™s my way of saying, â€˜Iâ€™m hearing you.â€™ Itâ€™s both acknowledging my own behaviour and looking at behaviour I've witnessed. I grew up with a sister, so I watched her date people, and I watched friends date people, and people don't treat each other very nicely sometimes.â€ â€œCinemaâ€ â€œI think I just wanted to make something that felt really fun, honestly. I was on a treadmill going, â€˜Do-do-do-do-do-do.â€™ I tend to do so much writing in the studio, but with this one, I did a little bit here and then I went home and added a little bit there, and then kind of left it, and then went into the studio to put it all together. That was a theme across the whole album, actually: We used to book a studio and be like, â€˜Okay, we've got it for two months, grind it out.â€™ But some days you just don't want to be there, and eventually you've been in the studio so long, the only thing you can write about is nothing because you haven't done anything. So with this album, weâ€™d work for a couple of weeks and then everyone would go off and live their lives.â€ â€œLove of My Lifeâ€ â€œâ€˜Love of My Lifeâ€™ was the most terrifying song because it's so bare. It's so sparse. Itâ€™s also very much in the spirit of what Harry's House is about: I wanted to make an acoustic EP, all in my house, and make it really intimate. Itâ€™s named after [the Japanese pop pioneer Haruomi] Hosono, who had an album in the '70s called Hosono House. I immediately started thinking about what Harryâ€™s House might look like. It took time for me to realise that the house wasn't a geographical location, it was an internal thing. When I applied that concept to the songs we were making here, everything took on new meaning. Imagine it's a day in my house or a day in my mind. What do I go through? I'm playing fun music. I'm playing sad music. I'm playing this, I'm playing that. I have doubts. Iâ€™m feeling stuff. And itâ€™s all mine. This is my favourite album at the moment. I love it so much. And because of the circumstances, it was made very intimately; everything was played by a small number of people and made in a room. To me, it's everything. It's everything I've wanted to make.â€
entries.title: Harry's House

entries.notes: In sharply differing ways, thoughts of place and identity run through Fontaines D.C.â€™s music. Where 2019 debut Dogrel delivered a rich and raw portrait of the bandâ€™s home city, Dublin, 2020 follow-up A Heroâ€™s Death was the sound of dislocation, a set of songs drawing on the introspection, exhaustion and yearning of an anchorless life on the road. When the five-piece moved to London midway through the pandemic, the experiences of being outsiders in a new city, often facing xenophobia and prejudice, provided creative fuel for third album Skinty Fia. The music that emerged weaves folk, electronic and melodic indie pop into their post-punk foundations, while contemplating Irishness and how it transforms in a different country. â€œThatâ€™s the lens through which all of the subjects that we explore are seen through anyway,â€ singer Grian Chatten tells Apple Musicâ€™s Matt Wilkinson. â€œThere are definitely themes of jealousy, corruption and stuff like that, but itâ€™s all seen through the eyes of someone whoâ€™s at odds with their own identity, culturally speaking.â€ Recording the album after dark helped breed feelings of discomfort that Chatten says are â€œnecessary to usâ€, and it continued a nocturnal schedule that had originally countered the claustrophobia of a locked-down city. â€œWe wrote a lot of it at night as well,â€ says Chatten. â€œWe went into the rehearsal space just as something different to do. When pubs and all that kind of thing were closed, it was a way of us feeling like the world was sort of open.â€ Here, Chatten and guitarist Carlos Oâ€™Connell talk us through a number of Skinty Fiaâ€™s key moments. â€œIn Ã¡r gCroÃ­the go deoâ€ Grian Chatten: â€œAn Irish woman who lived in Coventry [Margaret Keane] passed away. Her family wanted the words â€˜In Ã¡r gCroÃ­the go deoâ€™, which means â€˜in our hearts foreverâ€™, on her gravestone as a respectful and beautiful ode to her Irishness, but they werenâ€™t allowed without an English translation. Essentially the Church of England decreed that it would be potentially seen as a political slogan. The Irish language is apparently, according to these people, an inflammatory thing in and of itself, which is a very base level of xenophobia. Itâ€™s a basic expression of a culture, is the language. If youâ€™re considering that to be related to terrorism, which is what theyâ€™re implying, I think. That sounds like itâ€™s something out of the â€™70s, but this is two and a half years ago.â€ Carlos Oâ€™Connell: â€œAbout a year ago, it got turned around and [the family] won this case.â€ GC: â€œThe family were made aware [of the song] and asked if they could listen to it. Apparently they really loved it, and they played it at the gravestone. So, thatâ€™s 100,000 Grammys worth of validation.â€ â€œBig Shotâ€ CO: â€œWhen youâ€™ve got used to living with what you have and then all these dreams happen to you, itâ€™s always going to overshadow what you had before. The only impact that [Fontainesâ€™ success] was having in my life was that it just made anything that I had before quite meaningless for a while, and I felt quite lost in that. Thatâ€™s that lyric, â€˜I travelled to space and found the moon too smallâ€™â€”itâ€™s like, go up there and actually itâ€™s smaller than the Earth.â€ GC: â€œWeâ€™ve all experienced it very differently and thatâ€™s made us grow in different ways. But that song just sounded like a very true expression of Carlos. Perhaps more honest than he always is with himself or other people. All the honesty was balled up into that tune.â€ â€œJackie Down the Lineâ€ GC: â€œItâ€™s an expression of misanthropy. And thereâ€™s toxicity there. Thereâ€™s erosion of each otherâ€™s characters. Itâ€™s a very un-beneficial, unglamorous relationship that isnâ€™t necessarily about two people. I like the idea of it being about Irishness, fighting to not be eroded as it exists in a different country. The name is Jackie because a Dubliner would be called, in a pejorative sense, a Jackeen by people from other parts of Ireland. Thatâ€™s probably in reference to the Union Jack as wellâ€”itâ€™s like the Pale [an area of Ireland, including Dublin, that was under English governmental control during the late Middle Ages]. So itâ€™s this kind of mutation of Irishness or loss of Irishness as it exists, or fails to exist, in a different environment.â€ â€œRoman Holidayâ€ GC: â€œThe whole thing was coloured by my experience in London. I moved to London to be with my fiancÃ©e, and as an Irish person living in London, as one of a gang of Irish people, there was that kind of searching energy, there was this excitement, there was a kind of adventureâ€”but also this very, very tight-knit, rigorously upkept group energy. I think thatâ€™s what influenced the tune.â€ â€œThe Couple Across the Wayâ€ GC: â€œI lived on Caledonian Road [in North London] and our gaff backed onto another house. There was a couple that lived there, they were probably mid-seventies, and they had really loud arguments. The kind of arguments where youâ€™d see London on a map getting further, further away and hear the shout resounding. Something like The Simpsons. And the man would come out and take a big breath. Heâ€™d stand on his balcony and look left and right and exhale all the drama. And then heâ€™d just turn around and go back in to his gaff to do the same thing the next day. The absurdity of that, of what we put ourselves through, to be in a relationship that causes you such daily pain, to just always turn around and go back in. I couldnâ€™t really help but write about that physical mirror that was there. Am I seeing myself and my girlfriend in these two people, and vice versa? So I tried to tie it in to it being from both perspectives at some point.â€ â€œSkinty Fiaâ€ GC: â€œThe line â€˜There is a track beneath the wheel and itâ€™s there â€™til we dieâ€™ is about being your dadâ€™s son. There are many ways in which we explore doom on this record. One of them is following in the footsteps of your ancestors, or your predecessors, no matter how immediate or far away they might have been. Iâ€™m interested in the inescapability of genetics, the idea that your fate is written. I do, on some level, believe in that. That is doom, even if your faith is leading you to a positive place. Freedom is probably the main pursuit of a lot of our music. I think that that is probably a link that ties all of the stuff that weâ€™ve done togetherâ€”autonomy.â€ â€œI Love Youâ€ GC: â€œItâ€™s most ostensibly a love letter to Ireland, but has in it the corruption and the sadness and the grief with the ever-changing Dublin and Ireland. The reason that I wanted to call it â€˜I Love Youâ€™ is because I found its clichÃ© very attractive. It meant that there was a lot of work to be done in order to justify such a basic song and not have it be a clichÃ©d tune. Itâ€™s a song with two heads, because youâ€™ve got the slow, melodic verses that are a little bit more straightforward and then the lid is lifted off energetically. I think that the friction between those two things encapsulates the double-edged sword that is love.â€ â€œNabokovâ€ GC: â€œI think thereâ€™s a different arc to this album. The first two, I think, achieve a sense of happiness and hope halfway through, and end on a note of hope. I think this one does actually achieve hope halfway throughâ€”and then slides back into a hellish, doomy thing with the last track and stuff. I think that was probably one of the more conscious decisions that we made while making this album.â€

entries.notes: â€œI literally donâ€™t take breaks,â€ ROSALÃA tells Apple Music. â€œI feel like, to work at a certain level, to get a certain result, you really need to sacrifice.â€ Judging by MOTOMAMI, her long-anticipated follow-up to 2018â€™s award-winning and critically acclaimed EL MAL QUERER, the mononymous Spanish singer clearly put in the work. â€œI almost feel like I disappear because I needed to,â€ she says of maintaining her process in the face of increased popularity and attention. â€œI needed to focus and put all my energy and get to the centre to create.â€ At the same time, she found herself drawing energy from bustling locales like Los Angeles, Miami and New York, all of which she credits with influencing the new album. Beyond any particular source of inspiration that may have driven the creation of MOTOMAMI, ROSALÃAâ€™s come-up has been nothing short of inspiring. Her transition from critically acclaimed flamenco upstart to internationally renowned starâ€”marked by creative collaborations with global tastemakers like Bad Bunny, Billie Eilish and Oneohtrix Point Never, to name a fewâ€”has prompted an artistic metamorphosis. Her ability to navigate and dominate such a wide array of musical styles only raised expectations for her third full-length, but she resisted the idea of rushing things. â€œI didnâ€™t want to make an album just because now itâ€™s time to make an album,â€ she says, citing that several months were spent on mixing and visuals alone. â€œI donâ€™t work like thatâ€. Some three years after EL MAL QUERER, ROSALÃAâ€™s return feels even more revolutionary than that radical breakout release. From the noisy-yet-referential leftfield reggaetÃ³n of â€œSAOKOâ€ to the austere and Yeezus-reminiscent thump of â€œCHICKEN TERIYAKIâ€, MOTOMAMI makes the artistâ€™s femme-forward modus operandi all the more clear. The point of view presented is sharp and political, but also permissive of playfulness and wit, a humanising mix that makes the album her most personal yet. â€œI was like, I really want to find a way to allow my sense of humour to be present,â€ she says. â€œItâ€™s almost like you try to do, like, a self-portrait of a moment of who you are, how you feel, the way you think." Things get deeper and more unexpected with the devilish-yet-austere electronic punk funk of the title track and the feverish â€œBIZCOCHITOâ€. But there are even more twists and turns within, like â€œHENTAIâ€, a bilingual torch song that charms and enraptures before giving way to machine-gun percussion. Add to that â€œLA FAMAâ€, her mystifying team-up with The Weeknd that fuses tropical Latin rhythms with avant-garde minimalism, and you end up with one of the most unique artistic statements of the decade so far.
entries.title: MOTOMAMI

entries.notes: Folky, direct soul-pop and balladry made Paolo Nutini famous as a teen during the mid-2000s, but it was his adventurousness that quickly separated him from other British singer-songwriters emerging at that time. When second album Sunny Side Up arrived in 2009, he was drawing on ska, Dixieland jazz, country and doo-wop, before 2014â€™s Caustic Love played out like an expansive history of soul and R&B. From the off, Last Night in the Bittersweet reveals the Scotsmanâ€™s horizons have only broadened during the intervening eight years. â€œAfterneathâ€ begins the album with feedback, motorik rhythms and Tarantino samples as Nutiniâ€™s spoken-word lyrics herald â€œa deep dive into an open mindâ€. From there, the songs circle around New Wave (â€œPetrified in Loveâ€), epic indie rock (â€œShine a Lightâ€) and hymnal, muted electronica (â€œStranded Words [Interlude]â€). At the heart of it all is Nutiniâ€™s voice. Precociously expressive and versatile from day one, itâ€™s aged handsomely, sounding more lived-in than ever. Here, he contemplates regret, anxiety, optimism and love as it both blossoms and falters. When the record ends on its most unadorned moment, the gentle folk ballad â€œWriterâ€, Nutini sings, â€œI am your writer who bleeds indecision.â€ Itâ€™s that restless, capricious spirit that continues to make him such an absorbing artist.
entries.title: Last Night In The Bittersweet

entries.notes: Part of the appeal of Alex Gâ€™s homespun folk pop is how unsettling it is. For every Beatles-y melody (â€œMissionâ€) or warm, reassuring chorus (â€œEarly Morning Waitingâ€) thereâ€™s the image of a cocked gun (â€œRunnerâ€) or a mangled voice lurking in the mix like the monster in a fairy-tale forest (â€œS.D.O.Sâ€). His characters describe adult perspectives with the terror and wonder of children (â€œNo Bitternessâ€, â€œBlessingâ€), and several tracks make awestruck references to God. With every album, he draws closer to the conventions of American indie rock without touching them. And by the time you realise he isnâ€™t just another guy in his bedroom with an acoustic guitar, itâ€™s too late.

entries.notes: On â€œTick Tockâ€, the second track on Warm Chris, Aldous Harding asks, â€œNow that you see me, what you gonna do? Wanted to see me.â€ The New Zealand singer-songwriterâ€™s lyrics have always been veiled and poetically crypticâ€”and sheâ€™s made a point of not explaining the meaning behind any of it. But her fourth album feels assured and open in a way that makes you wonder whether the question is directed at an audience whoâ€™ve been wanting to learn more about this singular artist. Thereâ€™s a lot to see here, and like a well-directed film, it benefits from multiple replays, with more nuances and hidden meanings uncovered on each listen. Across her four albums, youâ€™ll notice a linear emotional evolution. Speaking to Apple Music in 2019 about her then-new album Designer, she said, â€œI felt freed upâ€¦ I could feel a loosening of tension, a different way of expressing my thought processes.â€ The journey clearly continued. Warm Chris is as intimate and curious as ever, but itâ€™s more grounded, more confident. If the tension was loosening on Designer, here, Harding has grown accustomed to the relaxed space and made herself at home. The album seems to deal primarily with connections and relationships. She reflects on a lost love during opener â€œEnnuiâ€ (â€œYouâ€™ve become my joy, you understandâ€¦ Come back, come back and leave it in the right placeâ€), hunts for faded excitement on â€œFeverâ€ (â€œI still stare at you in the dark/Looking for that thrill in the nothing/You know my favourite place is the startâ€), comically complains on â€œPassion Babeâ€ (â€œWell, you know Iâ€™m married, and I was bored out of my mind/Of all the ways to eat a cake, this one surely takes the knifeâ€¦ Passion must play, or passion wonâ€™t stayâ€) and accepts an ending on â€œLawnâ€ (â€œThen if you're not for me, guess I am not for you/I will enjoy the blue, Iâ€™m only confused with youâ€). On the whole, Warm Chris feels light and folksy, and the music is relatively simpleâ€”though not without its surprises. There are brass embellishments here, a psychedelic guitar solo there, even a brief foray into forlorn vintage blues on â€œBubblesâ€. It leaves space for Hardingâ€™s voice to remain in the spotlight. Her vocal acrobatics are as strange and versatile as everâ€”she can shift from breathy, dramatically deep bass to ultra-fine, ultra-high falsetto in moments, sometimes for only a word at a time. She sounds innocent and paper-thin on the gentle â€œLawnâ€, livelyâ€”and inflected with an unusual accentâ€”on â€œPassion Babeâ€. Her delivery is so pronounced and hyperbolic on the heart-wrenching â€œSheâ€™ll Be Coming Round the Mountainâ€ that it sounds like something out of a musical. And album closer â€œLeathery Whipâ€ feels inspired by The Velvet Underground, complete with a deep Nico drawl (occasionally flipping to a Kate Bush-style nasal tone), backing harmonies, a jangling tambourine and a cheeky refrain: â€œHere comes life with his leathery whip.â€

entries.notes:
Mitski wasnâ€™t sure sheâ€™d ever make it to her sixth album. After the release of 2018â€™s standout and star-making record Be the Cowboy, she simply had nothing left to give. â€œI think I was just tired, and I felt like I needed a break and I couldn't do it anymore,â€ she tells Apple Music. â€œI just told everyone on my team that I just needed to stop it for a while. I think everyone could tell I was already at max capacity.â€ And so, in 2019, she withdrew. But if creating became painful, not doing it at allâ€”eventuallyâ€”felt even worse. â€œI was feeling a deep surge of regret because I was like, â€˜Oh my god, what did I do?â€™â€ she says. â€œI let go of this career that I had worked so hard to get and I finally got, and I just left it all behind. I might have made the greatest mistake of my life.â€
Released two years after that self-imposed hiatus, Laurel Hell may mark Mitskiâ€™s official return, but she isnâ€™t exactly all in. Darkness descends as she moves back into her own musical world (â€œLetâ€™s step carefully into the dark/Once weâ€™re in Iâ€™ll remember my way aroundâ€ are this albumâ€™s first words), and it feels like she almost always has one eye on her escape route. Such melancholic tendencies shouldnâ€™t come as a surprise: Mitski Miyawaki is an artist who has always delved deep into her experiences as she attempts to understand themâ€”and help us understand our own. More unexpected, though, is the glittering, â€™80s-inspired synth-pop she often embraces, from â€œThe Only Heartbreakerâ€â€”whose opening drums throw back to a-haâ€™s â€œTake On Meâ€, and against which Mitski explores being the â€œbad guyâ€ in a relationshipâ€”to the bouncy, cinematic â€œShouldâ€™ve Been Meâ€ and the intense â€œLove Me Moreâ€, on which she cries out for affection, from a lover and from her audience, against racing synths. â€œI think at first, the songs were more straightforwardly rock or just more straightforwardly sad,â€ she recalls. â€œBut as the pandemic progressed, [frequent collaborator] Patrick [Hyland] and I just stopped being able to stay in that sort of sad feeling. We really needed something that would make us dance, that would make us feel hopeful. We just couldnâ€™t stand the idea of making another sad, dreary album.â€
This being a Mitski record, there are of course still moments of insular intensity, from â€œEveryoneâ€ to â€œHeat Lightningâ€, a brooding meditation on insomnia. And underneath all that protective pop, this is an album about darkness and endingsâ€”of relationships, possibly of her career. And by its finish, Mitski still isnâ€™t promising to stick around. â€œI guess this is the end, Iâ€™ll have to learn to be somebody else,â€ she says on â€œI Guessâ€, before simply fading away on final track â€œThatâ€™s Our Lampâ€.
entries.title: Laurel Hell

entries.notes: When Kendrick Lamar popped up on two tracks from Baby Keemâ€™s The Melodic Blue (â€œrange brothersâ€ and â€œfamily tiesâ€), it felt like one of hip-hopâ€™s prophets had descended a mountain to deliver scripture. His verses were stellar, to be sure, but it also just felt like way too much time had passed since weâ€™d heard his voice. Heâ€™d helmed 2018â€™s Black Panther compilation/soundtrack, but his last proper release was 2017â€™s DAMN. That kind of scarcity in hip-hop can only serve to deify an artist as beloved as Lamar. But if the Compton MC is broadcasting anything across his fifth proper album Mr. Morale & The Big Steppers, itâ€™s that heâ€™s only human. The project is split into two parts, each comprising nine songs, all of which serve to illuminate Lamarâ€™s continually evolving world view. Central to Lamarâ€™s thesis is accountability. The MC has painstakingly itemised his shortcomings, assessing his relationships with money (â€œUnited in Griefâ€), white women (â€œWorldwide Steppersâ€), his father (â€œFather Timeâ€), the limits of his loyalty (â€œRich Spiritâ€), love in the context of heteronormative relationships (â€œWe Cry Togetherâ€, â€œPurple Heartsâ€), motivation (â€œCount Me Outâ€), responsibility (â€œCrownâ€), gender (â€œAuntie Diariesâ€) and generational trauma (â€œMother I Soberâ€). Itâ€™s a dense and heavy listen. But just as sure as Kendrick Lamar is human like the rest of us, heâ€™s also a Pulitzer Prize winner, one of the most thoughtful MCs alive and someone whose honesty across Mr. Morale & The Big Steppers could help us understand why any of us are the way we are.
